/* ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
   stories-extended.js
   Fifty additional myths, expanding the codex from eight
   civilizations to nineteen. Same structural conventions as
   stories.js: each entry is { id, title, subtitle, civilization,
   themes, content }.

   Stories are pushed into the global window.MYTHOLOGY.stories
   array, then re-sorted at the end by canonical civilization order
   (the sort step at the foot of stories.js does the heavy lift —
   we just append).
   ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ */

window.MYTHOLOGY = window.MYTHOLOGY || {};
window.MYTHOLOGY.stories = window.MYTHOLOGY.stories || [];

/* ═══════════════════════════ GREEK (additions) ═══════════════════════════ */

window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "icarus",
    title: "The Fall of Icarus",
    subtitle: "Wax wings, a warning, and a sun the boy could not bear to look away from",
    civilization: "greek",
    themes: ["Hubris", "Father & son", "Flight", "Warning"],
    content: [
        "Daedalus was the cleverest man in the world. He had built the Labyrinth at Knossos for King Minos — built it so well that he himself could barely find his own way out, and the Minotaur paced its bone-strewn corridors without ever finding a wall that meant anything. When the king's daughter Ariadne later helped Theseus through that maze with a thread, Minos understood at once that there had been only one mind in his court capable of designing the maze and only one mind in his court capable of imagining a way through it. He locked Daedalus in a high tower, with his small son Icarus, and threw away the key.",
        "From the tower window the world ran on without them. Boats came in. Boats went out. Daedalus watched the gulls. He watched the way the gulls leaned into the wind and were carried — not pushed, not strained — carried, as if the wind owed them passage. He watched the white feathers shed onto the rocks below. Every day he gathered the feathers when the guard let him take Icarus down for water. He hid them under his cloak. He carried them up.",
        "He had wax. He had been a candlemaker once, among many trades. He melted it in a small bronze cup over the lamp. He laid the feathers in tiers — the long flight feathers at the back, the short coverts toward the leading edge — and he glued them to a wooden frame shaped like a folded gull. He worked at night, with his back to the door. The boy held the candle.",
        "When the wings were finished he made a smaller pair for Icarus, and he taught the boy to lift his arms and feel where the wind would catch.",
        "\"Listen,\" he said. \"Listen now. We have one chance. Do not fly low — the salt spray will soak the feathers and pull you down. Do not fly high — the sun will melt the wax and the feathers will come away in strands. Stay in the middle air. Stay where I am. Watch me. I will not look back to see if you are following — I will trust you. You must trust me to trust you.\"",
        "The boy nodded. He was twelve. He had spent a year in a stone room. He would have agreed to anything.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "They jumped at dawn. The wind was clean. The wings caught. Daedalus felt — for the first time in his long life of cleverness — the one thing his cleverness had not yet given him, which was the joy of a creature who had become its own escape. He laughed out loud. The boy beside him laughed too, in a higher voice.",
        "They flew. They passed the small island of Samos and saw the temple of Hera burning her dawn fires. They passed the rocks where the sirens used to sing before someone clever stopped them. They passed fishing boats; the fishermen looked up and shaded their eyes and could not understand what they were seeing.",
        "And the boy, whose body had never known anything but stone walls and a low ceiling, felt the air flow under his wings and felt himself rise on the warm thermal coming off a sun-struck cliff, and he could not — could not — keep himself in the middle air.",
        "He went up. He went a little higher. The wind got cleaner. He went higher. He could see, far below, the boat-shape of his father, very small now, still flying steady. He thought: my father is afraid of the sun. My father is always afraid. The sun is not so terrible. The sun is wonderful. The sun is what a boy was made for.",
        "He went higher. He went into the warm bright country directly under the sun-disk. His wings had not changed. He felt nothing wrong. Then, soft as a sigh, the first feather slipped. Then a second. Then a third. The wax was running down the inside of his elbow in a thin clear bead. He looked at it. He did not understand at first.",
        "Then the whole left wing came undone all at once.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He fell.",
        "He fell with the brightness all around him and the air rushing up into his face and the feathers — every feather his father had patiently glued onto a wooden frame in a tower at midnight by candlelight — coming free of him in a slow drift, like a flock of small white birds startled out of his shoulders. He did not have time to scream. He had time only to think a single small clear thought, which was: oh.",
        "Daedalus, ahead, did not at first see. He had promised not to look back. He kept his eyes forward. He felt, however, the small shift in the air beside him — a ripple, a thinning — and he knew, the way a man knows when the room has gone quiet behind him, that the boy was no longer there.",
        "He turned. He saw the white feathers in the air. He saw, on the surface of the sea below, a small splash already widening, already calming, already gone.",
        "He flew down. He hovered above the place. He could see, in the green water, the small body, face-up, drifting. The wings were still attached at the shoulders. The wings were also broken.",
        "He pulled the body out. He flew with it to the nearest island and laid it on the sand. He buried it there. He sat with it for two days. Then he flew on. He had nowhere left to go but on.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The middle air is a hard place to stay. It is not where the heart wants to be. The heart wants the dazzle of the upper air or the cool deep cradle of the sea. The middle air is the discipline of fathers, and the boys do not always learn it in time." },
        "The island where he buried his son is called Icaria. The sea around it is called the Icarian Sea. They are still on every map. Every ship that sails through them passes over the small bones of a boy who could not stop himself from going up."
    ]
},

{
    id: "medusa",
    title: "Medusa",
    subtitle: "Of the woman who was punished for being looked at",
    civilization: "greek",
    themes: ["Curse", "Beauty", "Vengeance", "Sisterhood"],
    content: [
        "Before the snakes there was a girl. Her name was Medusa, and she was a priestess in the temple of Athena at Athens, and the qualification for her office was a vow of chastity she had taken willingly when she was young enough to mean it forever. She was beautiful. She had two sisters who were not beautiful — Stheno and Euryale, both of them already gorgons in the old sense, neither of them mortal — but Medusa was mortal, and she had skin that the lamplight loved, and hair so long and dark it could be braided in seven different ways depending on what the goddess required of her on a given evening.",
        "Poseidon, the lord of the sea, saw her when she was sweeping the steps of the temple. He came in. He did not knock. He did not announce himself. He took her on the marble floor of the goddess's house, and the goddess's image looked down without intervening — because the goddess was not in the room, and even if she had been, the older laws between the gods made interference complicated. Medusa wept and could not stop weeping for a long time afterward. She did not, when she was strong enough to walk again, leave the temple. She went to the goddess and laid the broken silence at her feet and said, this happened in your house, on your watch.",
        "Athena was a goddess of wisdom and a goddess of wrath, and she could not always tell which of those two was speaking when she opened her mouth. She heard the priestess. She felt the desecration of her temple. She did what older justice systems often do when they cannot reach the powerful actor — she punished the smaller one. She turned Medusa into a monster.",
        "Not a complete monster. A face that men would still find beautiful, frozen in the moment of a small terrible cry. A body that was still a woman's body. But for hair, the long dark hair, she gave Medusa a writhing crown of serpents — small, fanged, alive, hissing on her shoulders, never asleep. And to make the punishment final, she added the curse of the gaze: any living thing that met Medusa's eye would turn to stone where it stood, instantly, in mid-step, in mid-word.",
        "Medusa, when she understood what had been done to her, did not speak. She walked out of the temple. She went to find her sisters.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Stheno and Euryale lived on a far island in the western sea, beyond where the boats went. They had been waiting for her. When she came up the beach with her crown of small writhing serpents, they took her in their arms and smoothed the snakes flat against her scalp and said, sister, sister, come in, come away from the world, the world will not be safe for you and you will not be safe for it.",
        "She lived with them. She made a kind of life. She would walk on the cliffs at dusk and the snakes would breathe in her hair and she would talk to them as if to any companion. Sometimes she would weep, looking out at the sea. Sometimes — when the moon was full and the snakes were quiet — she could almost remember the shape of the woman she had been before. But she could not return to her. The woman she had been was gone.",
        "Sometimes a sailor came to the island. Sometimes a soldier. Sometimes a fool with a dagger and a story he had been told in an inn about a treasure on a far western island guarded by a witch. Medusa would meet them at the path. She would not turn away. She would let them look. There was no other power left to her, after all. The snakes hissed once. The man met her eyes. The man became a stone. There were many stones on her island, after a while. They stood in attitudes of surprise.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Then came Perseus. He was a boy, more or less. He had been sent on this errand by a king who wanted his mother as a wife and wanted Perseus dead in some glamorous unprovable way. Athena gave him a polished shield, mirror-bright. Hermes gave him winged sandals. Hades gave him a helmet of invisibility. He was equipped beyond his deserving. He flew west. He came to the island.",
        "He approached Medusa where she slept. He looked at her only through the reflection in the shield, never directly. The snakes stirred but did not wake. He raised the sword. He cut.",
        "From the wound — from the moment of severance — sprang two strange children Medusa had been carrying without knowing: Pegasus, the white winged horse, who took flight at once into the upper air; and Chrysaor, a young man with a golden sword, who stepped out and stood beside the body and looked down. Both of them were Poseidon's. Both of them were also hers.",
        "Stheno and Euryale, on the cliffs, woke at the moment of their sister's death and screamed a scream that the islands of the western sea remember to this day, and they came running with their wings unfolding, but the boy with the helmet of invisibility was already gone.",
        "He carried the head in a sack. The head, even severed, kept its power. The eyes kept their gaze. He used the head as a weapon — turned an army to stone with it once, turned a sea-monster to stone with it once, turned a king to stone in his own throne room — and when at last he was finished with it he gave it to Athena, who set it in the center of her own war-shield, the aegis, where it stayed forever after. The face of the priestess in the temple, frozen in its small terrible cry, became the icon the goddess wore into every battle.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Whoever has been turned into a monster for what was done to them has the right to a story that does not end at the moment a hero comes for their head. The hero does not get to write the whole of it." },
        "On the island in the western sea, Stheno and Euryale buried the body. They could not weep tears that the body would have understood any longer, but they wept anyway. The stones on the island were never moved. They stand still. The path Medusa used to walk at dusk has grown over with sea-thrift, and the snakes that were her hair, when the head was taken away, slid quietly off the shoulders and into the grass, and there are snakes on that island to this day, small and dark, who do not bite anyone."
    ]
},

{
    id: "arachne",
    title: "Athena and Arachne",
    subtitle: "The contest of looms, and what a goddess could not bear to lose",
    civilization: "greek",
    themes: ["Pride", "Craft", "Divine envy", "Transformation"],
    content: [
        "Arachne was a weaver. She was the daughter of a small dyer in Lydia who could turn wool any shade of purple between sunset and bruise, and she had grown up among the long pots of his craft, and her hands had known thread before they had known anything else. By the time she was sixteen no woman in her town could match her at the loom; by twenty no woman in Lydia could; by twenty-five — her hair gone grey early, the way it does in the great craftspeople — no woman in any country could.",
        "She wove tapestries that travelers would walk three days out of their way to see. She wove them on simple looms, with simple shuttles, with no more equipment than a girl in a back room would have. The miracle was in the hands. People said the nymphs of Mount Tmolus would come down to watch her work and would forget to return to their own springs.",
        "Someone said to her, casually, in admiration: \"Athena herself must have taught you. You weave the way the goddess weaves.\"",
        "Arachne, who was tired of being told her hands were not her own, said: \"I had no teacher. I weave better than the goddess. Let her come and try me.\"",
        "There was a silence in the room.",
        "An old woman in the corner — bent, grey-cloaked, leaning on a stick — coughed and said softly, \"Daughter, take it back. It is one thing to be proud of your craft. It is another to challenge a god. Apologize, and the goddess is generous, and nothing more will be said.\"",
        "Arachne, whose pride was now committed in front of witnesses, said: \"I take nothing back. Let her come.\"",
        "The old woman straightened. Her cloak fell away. She was not old. She was tall and grey-eyed and her hair was the color of sun-bleached oak, and she wore a polished shield on her back, and she was very calm.",
        "\"Then we begin,\" said Athena.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "They set up two looms in the courtyard of Arachne's house. The whole town stood behind a low wall to watch. The two women — for Athena had taken a working woman's form, sleeves rolled, hair bound — sat down at their looms and began.",
        "Athena wove the gods. She wove the great myth of her own contest with Poseidon for the patronage of Athens — the salt spring his trident had struck in the rock, the olive tree she had set into the earth, the long council in which the gods chose her gift over his. She wove Zeus on his throne. She wove Hera at his side. She wove the punishment of Tantalus, the wheel of Ixion, the fall of the rebel giants. She wove, in short, the official anthology — the complete authorized works, grand, magisterial, very nearly unbearable in its perfection.",
        "Arachne wove the gods too. But she wove a different anthology. She wove Zeus as a swan covering Leda. She wove Zeus as a bull carrying Europa across the sea. She wove Zeus as a shower of gold falling onto Danae in her bronze prison. She wove Poseidon as a horse, taking Demeter. She wove Apollo's many disguises, the hunt for Daphne who became the laurel, the hunt for the boy Hyacinth who became the flower. She wove the bad behavior of every Olympian — exhaustively, unflinchingly, in colors so accurate that a woman in the crowd recognized her own grandmother's face on Leda and crossed herself and walked away weeping.",
        "When both tapestries were finished the town fell silent. Both were perfect. The two were not, however, equal in the matter of form: Athena's was magnificent, Arachne's was magnificent and also true. Athena, who was a goddess of crafts and a goddess of wisdom but also — though she did not always like to admit it — a goddess of war, looked at Arachne's tapestry. She looked at the long row of small Zeuses behaving badly. She looked at the woman who had woven them.",
        "Athena was not used to losing.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "She tore the tapestry in half. She tore it down the loom from top to bottom with one quick motion of her hand. The town gasped. Then she struck Arachne three times across the forehead with the shuttle.",
        "Arachne fell back. She understood, in the moment of being struck, that she had won the contest and had nonetheless lost, because the goddess could not be defeated and the goddess therefore would write the ending. She climbed onto a low beam in the courtyard. She tied a length of her own woven thread around her neck. She let herself fall.",
        "Athena, watching, felt — for one brief moment — what every powerful being feels when their power has gone too far and they understand it. She held out her hand. She caught the dying woman by the throat and softened the rope. She did not let her die. She did not, however, let her remain a woman, either.",
        "\"Live,\" said the goddess. \"Live, and weave. Weave forever. Weave in every doorway and every window and every dark corner of every house. Weave so that no one can forget, in any age that comes, that there was once a woman whose loom was as good as a god's. Weave on those terms.\"",
        "And she shrank. Her body grew small and dark and many-legged. Her arms became eight thin spinning limbs. Her belly swelled with the silken substance she would now produce out of herself, without need of flax or wool, and from it she would draw the thread of all her future weavings.",
        "She became the first spider.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The craftswoman who beat a goddess at the loom kept on weaving. She weaves still. Every web in every corner is a small remaining tapestry of the original contest. The ones who sweep them away have not understood whose work they are sweeping." },
        "The Greek word for spider is arachne. The whole class of them — every web, every silken sac of eggs, every long delicate creature drifting on a thread of its own making — is named after her, and the name is the Greek language's quiet acknowledgment of the older injustice. She wove the truth and was punished for the truth, and was given immortality only as a long sentence of work, but the work goes on, and the work is — still — better than any goddess has done since."
    ]
},

{
    id: "trojan-horse",
    title: "The Wooden Horse",
    subtitle: "Of the gift the city should not have brought through its gate",
    civilization: "greek",
    themes: ["Cunning", "War", "Trust", "City"],
    content: [
        "Ten years the Greeks had been camped before the walls of Troy. Ten summers of dust and ten winters of mud, and the long grey wave of their ships drawn up on the beach, and the long grey faces of their kings around the council fire, none of them as young as they had been on the day they sailed. The walls of Troy had not fallen. The walls of Troy could not be made to fall. They had been built, the old men said, by Apollo and Poseidon themselves in the days when those gods owed a king a debt, and what the gods build does not yield to mortal weapons.",
        "The greatest Greek hero had been killed: Achilles, struck in the heel by an arrow guided by Apollo. The greatest Trojan hero had been killed: Hector, dragged behind Achilles's chariot through the dust under his own wife's window. The war had been costly enough that neither side could now imagine what victory was supposed to look like, only that they had paid too much to leave with nothing.",
        "Odysseus, king of Ithaca — the cleverest man in the camp — went for a long walk along the beach one evening. When he came back he had a plan. He explained it to Agamemnon. Agamemnon stared at him for a long time, then laughed for the first time in a year.",
        "\"It cannot work,\" said Agamemnon.",
        "\"It will work,\" said Odysseus, \"because it cannot work. They will let it through the gate precisely because no army would ever be foolish enough to imagine it.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The Greeks built a horse.",
        "They built it of pine timbers from the slopes of Mount Ida. They built it taller than the gate of Troy. They built it on rollers so it could be moved. They polished its wooden mane. They carved its mouth open in a noble grin. They did not put any visible door on it. They set into its hollow belly, by way of a hatch under the tail, a small ladder leading down into a chamber large enough to hide thirty armed men.",
        "Then the army — the entire Greek army, every tent, every cookfire, every horse, every standard — was struck and loaded onto the long grey ships, and the ships were rowed out beyond the headland of Tenedos, where they could not be seen from the walls of Troy. The beach was empty by morning. The wooden horse stood alone on the sand. And on a small jutting rock, alone, was a single Greek soldier named Sinon, gagged and bound and weeping.",
        "The Trojans came down to look. They had spent ten years looking at the same Greek camp, and now the camp was gone, and there was only this strange enormous wooden horse and one weeping man.",
        "Sinon, untied, told them his story. The Greeks, he said, had given up. They were sailing home. They had built the horse as an offering to Athena, to make the goddess favor their voyage. They had built it tall on purpose so that the Trojans would not be able to bring it inside their city — for a Trojan-housed Athena would mean Trojan victory in any future war, and the Greeks did not wish that. They had left him, Sinon, behind because they had drawn lots for a sacrifice and his lot had fallen.",
        "He spoke convincingly. He had been chosen for his face.",
        "The Trojans debated. The priest Laocoön ran down to the shore shouting, \"Do not trust it! I fear the Greeks even when they bring gifts!\" — and as he was shouting two great serpents rose out of the sea and wrapped themselves around him and his two sons and dragged them all under, and the watching crowd took the omen for what it appeared to be. Cassandra, the prophet-princess who was always right and was never believed, came down weeping and said, \"There is death in that horse, do not bring it in,\" and the watching crowd agreed she was probably right and brought it in anyway, because they could not stop themselves.",
        "They tore down a section of their own wall to fit it through. They had to. They could not bear to leave it on the beach.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The horse stood in the central square of Troy. The city held a feast. The first feast in ten years. There was wine on every table. There was music. There were old people who had not danced since they were young dancing again, stiffly, in the firelight. There were children who had been born during the siege seeing for the first time what their city looked like on a happy night. By midnight every adult in Troy was either drunk or asleep, and the wine had been deep, and the streets were quiet.",
        "Sinon, who was no prisoner at all, climbed a tower and lit a small lantern and held it out toward the headland of Tenedos. The Greek ships, hidden behind the headland, saw the small light and silently lifted their oars and rowed back toward the beach.",
        "Inside the wooden horse, in the small belly chamber, Odysseus tapped the man next to him on the shoulder. The man passed it on. One by one the thirty men inside the horse stretched their cramped legs as quietly as they could. The hatch under the tail opened. They climbed down on a knotted rope. They moved through the dark city.",
        "They opened the great main gate of Troy from the inside.",
        "The Greek army, freshly landed, came through it.",
        "What followed cannot be described in detail because it does not bear describing. King Priam was killed at his own household altar, where he had gone to pray. The Trojan princes were killed in their beds. The temple of Athena was full of women who had run there for sanctuary and who did not receive any. Hector's small son was thrown from the wall. The city burned. By dawn the smoke from Troy was visible from the island of Lesbos.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The walls of a city are only the second-strongest line of its defense. The strongest is the discernment of its citizens. Whoever cannot tell a gift from a trick has lost their city already, before the trick has even arrived." },
        "The Greeks sailed home. Most of them did not arrive. The gods, who do not approve of any sack however clever, scattered them across the wine-dark sea. Odysseus took ten years to find Ithaca again. Agamemnon walked through his own door and was killed by his wife in his bath. Menelaus alone got Helen back, and did not, in the end, know what to do with her. The wooden horse remained for a season in the smoking ruin of the central square, and then the rains came, and the timber softened, and the horse — like every clever thing — eventually fell down."
    ]
},

{
    id: "atalanta",
    title: "Atalanta and the Golden Apples",
    subtitle: "The fastest woman in Greece, and the three apples she could not run past",
    civilization: "greek",
    themes: ["Speed", "Choice", "Pride", "Trickery"],
    content: [
        "Atalanta had been left as an infant on a hillside because her father wanted a son and could not bear what he saw in the cradle. A she-bear that had been hunting found her there, lifted her gently in her teeth, carried her back to the cave and raised her among cubs. Atalanta grew up among bears and learned, before she learned anything else, how to run.",
        "She could outrun a deer over a long course. She could outrun a horse over a short one. By the time she was a young woman she could outrun any man in Greece, including the heroes. She joined the great hunt for the Calydonian Boar that was tearing up the wheatfields of Aetolia, and she was the one who shot the first arrow into the boar's flank, and the prize hide was awarded to her at the end, although the men of the hunt argued about it for months. She rowed with the Argonauts for a season. She was at every event a hero would be at.",
        "Her father — finding, after some years, that the daughter he had thrown away had become more famous than any son he might have had — sent for her and welcomed her home and asked her, with the grace of a king who has reconsidered, to consider marriage.",
        "She did not want to marry. She had been told by an oracle that marriage would be the end of her, and she was not in the habit of disobeying oracles. But she also did not want to refuse her father a second time in his life. She made him a counter-offer.",
        "\"I will marry,\" she said, \"any man who can beat me in a footrace. The course will be from the temple to the river and back. He must run it without armor and without weapon. If he wins, he marries me. If he loses, he dies. Those are the terms. Spread the word.\"",
        "Her father blanched. \"Daughter,\" he said, \"those are very hard terms.\"",
        "\"They are the terms,\" she said.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Many young men came. Many young men were beautiful, and many were strong, and many were certain they would be the one. They stood at the start line in their loose tunics, full of hope, and they ran their hearts out, and Atalanta — who was always a few yards behind them at the turn, just to make a fair show — would catch them at the temple steps coming back, and pass them, and finish first by ten paces, and she would not look down as the king's executioner did the work she had warned them about. The line of small graves outside the city wall grew long.",
        "She did not enjoy this. She had hoped, perhaps, that the conditions would dissuade. They did not. Pride is a strong runner too.",
        "There came at last a young man named Hippomenes. He was not famous. He had not been at any of the great hunts. He had stood in the crowd at the last race and watched the previous suitor die and had seen Atalanta walk back to the temple alone, looking at no one, and he had been struck — not by her speed, but by the terrible loneliness in her gait. He decided, in that moment, that he would race her.",
        "He had no chance. He knew he had no chance. He went to the temple of Aphrodite at the edge of the city and knelt and said, \"Goddess of love, the strongest goddess. I am asking. I have nothing else. Help me run this race not for myself but for her, because the woman is being broken by the rules she made.\"",
        "Aphrodite, who had been watching the long string of small graves with an interest of her own, considered. She came down. She gave Hippomenes three small things. Three apples — not ordinary apples, but the gold apples from the orchard of the Hesperides at the western edge of the world, where the Titan held the sky.",
        "\"When she gains on you,\" said the goddess, \"throw one. When she gains again, throw another. When she gains a third time, throw the last. Do not look back to see if she has stopped. Just keep running.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "They stood at the start line. Atalanta saw the young man and felt — though she did not know why — a small twist of regret. He looked, somehow, at the small graves behind the wall as if he had counted them. \"Run well,\" she said quietly, almost gently. He said nothing.",
        "The horn sounded. He ran.",
        "He ran better than he had ever run in his life. Aphrodite was in his calves. But Atalanta was Atalanta, and within a hundred paces she had drawn level with him, and within a hundred more she was past him, and she was running at the relaxed easy lope of a runner who knew she would have him at the temple steps as she had had every other man.",
        "Hippomenes, panting, threw the first apple. It landed twelve feet ahead of her and rolled into the grass beside the path. The metal flashed in the sun.",
        "She had never seen an apple of gold before. She had won every game she had ever played and had taken home prizes more elaborate, but a thing made of solid gold the size of a real fruit — that was a different kind of object. She slowed. She bent. She picked it up. She tucked it into the fold at her waist and ran on.",
        "But she had lost a few yards. Hippomenes was past her. She accelerated and caught him by the second milestone. He threw the second apple, slightly further off the path this time so she had to break stride to fetch it. She did. She caught him again at the third milestone. He threw the third apple — the last one — and threw it hard, far off the path into a stand of long grass, and Atalanta hesitated for the first time, and then she went after it, because she was not a woman who left a thing on the field.",
        "By the time she had it she could see, ahead, Hippomenes touching the temple steps. He had won.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "She walked back to him slowly, holding the three apples. She had not been beaten in a race in her life. She felt, mostly, a strange light feeling, as if a long burden she had not known she was carrying had been lifted by a goddess who had loved both of them, both her and the boy. She put the apples in his palm.",
        "\"You ran well,\" she said, and she meant it.",
        "They were married that evening. There was no execution to perform. The king wept. The crowd cheered. The line of small graves outside the city wall received no addition.",
        { style: "quote", text: "There are races a runner needs to lose. There are oracles that come true sideways. The husband who catches the wife by throwing three small bright things into her path is, perhaps, the only kind of husband she could have been caught by." },
        "Later — much later — they made the mistake of lying together in the temple of a different god, on the wrong floor at the wrong hour, and that god, offended, turned them both into lions, and they were yoked together to the chariot of Cybele to draw her through the wild country, and they did not return. The oracle had not been wrong. The marriage had been the end of her, in the long view. But it had been a long view. In the meantime they had had years of running together at evening, on roads, hand in hand, neither one trying to win."
    ]
}
);

