window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "romulus-remus",
    title: "Romulus and Remus",
    subtitle: "Twin boys, a she-wolf at a riverbank, and the founding of an eternal city",
    civilization: "roman",
    themes: ["Twins", "Founding", "Wolf", "Brother against brother"],
    content: [
        "There was a king named Numitor in the city of Alba Longa, and Numitor had a brother named Amulius, and Amulius wanted the throne. Amulius killed Numitor's son, took the throne, and forced Numitor's daughter Rhea Silvia to become a Vestal virgin so that there could be no further heirs in that bloodline. The math, on paper, was finished. The throne would stay in Amulius's family.",
        "But Mars, the god of war, came to Rhea Silvia in her sleep. Months later it became impossible to conceal that the new vestal was carrying twins. When the boys were born — two of them, both healthy, both screaming, both undeniably the children of a god — Amulius did not have the courage to kill them outright. He ordered a servant to take them down to the river Tiber in a basket and let the river do the work. The servant, weeping, set the basket adrift in the floodwater and walked away without looking back.",
        "The basket floated. The basket did not sink. The basket caught in the roots of a fig tree on the far bank, where a she-wolf had come down at dusk to drink. The wolf was lean — it had been a hard winter — and she was nursing cubs of her own, and what she did when she found the basket nobody can quite explain except that she pulled it onto the bank and lay down beside the two infants and let them feed.",
        "She fed them for many days. A woodpecker, sacred also to Mars, brought them berries and small grubs. They lived. A shepherd named Faustulus eventually found the small camp under the fig tree and took the boys home to his wife and raised them as his own. He never told them where he had found them. He named them Romulus and Remus.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "They grew up wild. They were stronger than other boys, faster than other boys, more impatient with rules. They led a gang of shepherd-boys in the hills around the Palatine, and the gang was less a gang of friends than a small standing militia, and they fought the boys of other villages over boundaries, and they won. By the time they were eighteen they were, in effect, the local power.",
        "A quarrel with a neighboring village over a stolen herd brought them at last to the attention of King Amulius's officers. Remus was captured. He was brought to Alba Longa. The king, looking at him, felt — though he could not name it — a chill. The grandfather Numitor, summoned from his exile, looked at the captive and felt a different chill. He asked the boy his age. The boy said eighteen. Numitor asked who had raised him. The boy said a shepherd named Faustulus. Numitor said, \"Tell me one more thing. Was there a brother?\"",
        "Romulus came at the head of the shepherds and broke into the palace and freed his brother, and the two of them killed Amulius in his own hall. They restored their grandfather to the throne. Numitor wept. Numitor offered them anything in his city.",
        "The brothers said no. They had decided, on the long walk to the city, that they wanted to found a city of their own.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "They went back to the hills above the Tiber. They knew the country well — it was the country they had been raised in. There were two hills they had loved as children: the Palatine and the Aventine. They could not agree on which one to build on.",
        "They decided to consult the gods by augury. Each brother climbed his preferred hill and watched the sky for a sign. Remus, on the Aventine, saw six vultures cross the sky. He took it as confirmation. Romulus, on the Palatine, saw twelve vultures cross the sky a little later. He took it as the better confirmation.",
        "They argued. Remus said his sign had come first. Romulus said his sign had been larger. Their respective gangs of shepherd-boys took sides. The argument did not resolve.",
        "Romulus, fed up, began to plow a furrow around the base of the Palatine — the sacred founding furrow that traced the line where the city wall would stand. The furrow was a line a man did not cross. To cross it without permission was a desecration of the city before the city had even been built.",
        "Remus, watching, laughed. He vaulted the furrow. He stood on the inside of his brother's wall.",
        "Romulus killed him.",
        "He killed him with a single blow. The killing was so quick neither brother had time to feel it had become possible. Remus fell on the inside of the line. Romulus stood over him with the bloodied tool in his hand and said, in a voice that was not entirely his own, \"So perish whoever crosses my walls.\" Then he sat down beside the body and could not get up for a long time.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He did, eventually. He buried his brother on the Aventine. He named the city Roma after himself. He brought in shepherds and exiles and outlaws as his first citizens, because no settled people would come to a city founded on the death of a brother. He had no women. He held a great festival and invited the neighboring tribe of the Sabines and stole their daughters at the festival and, after a long war, persuaded them to stay — and they did stay, on terms negotiated by themselves, and the Sabine women became the founding mothers of the new city alongside the rough founding fathers.",
        "The city grew. It grew slowly at first, then quickly, then at the long inexorable pace of an empire. It became, in time, the eternal city, the capital of an empire that would stretch from Britain to Mesopotamia and would last in some form, in some inheritor, for two millennia. The Roman Senate met under the Palatine. The Roman emperors lived on the Palatine. The Roman she-wolf — the lupa — became the icon of the state, set in bronze in the public squares, suckling two infant boys whose later quarrel had founded a country.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Cities of any duration are usually founded on a brother's grave. The grave is buried under the floor of the senate house and the senate house meets above it for a thousand years and pretends not to hear, and the city, which knows, does not say." },
        "Romulus, in his old age, was caught up into a thunderstorm on the Field of Mars and was never seen again. The senators of his time said he had been taken up among the gods. They named him Quirinus and made him one of the trinity of Roman state divinities. Some of the citizens said quietly, in the wineshops, that the senators had killed him in the storm and divided the body. We do not know which is true. The city went on either way."
    ]
},

{
    id: "cupid-psyche",
    title: "Cupid and Psyche",
    subtitle: "A wife who lit a lamp, and the sorting of seeds at the foot of a goddess",
    civilization: "roman",
    themes: ["Love", "Trust", "Trial", "Soul"],
    content: [
        "Psyche was the youngest of three princesses, and she was so beautiful that the people of her country began, very quietly at first and then very loudly, to neglect their offerings to Venus and to leave them at Psyche's gate instead. Venus, the goddess of love, watching this from her marble pavilion in the upper sky, did not take it well. She summoned her son Cupid — winged boy, archer of the small arrow that makes a person love whoever they see next — and she told him to go down and shoot Psyche. \"Make her fall in love,\" she said, \"with the lowest, ugliest, most contemptible creature you can find on the road. Let her be the laughingstock of every village.\"",
        "Cupid, dutiful, took his bow and flew down. He found Psyche asleep on a balcony in the moonlight. He drew an arrow. He bent and looked at her — to aim, only to aim — and his hand slipped, and the arrow grazed his own arm.",
        "He fell in love with her on the spot.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "What he did then was complicated. He did not return to his mother. He did not wake Psyche. He arranged, instead, for an oracle to instruct her parents to dress her as a bride and leave her on a high lonely rock to be carried away by a monster. The parents wept and obeyed.",
        "Psyche stood on the rock at dawn, alone, and a soft west wind picked her up and carried her — gently, like a leaf — across a long valley and set her down at the gate of a palace that had not been there yesterday. The palace was empty of people. Voices spoke to her out of the air, polite voices, that drew her bath and laid out her meal and showed her her chamber. By night a husband came to her in the dark. He was tender. He was clearly young. He would not let her see him. \"Trust me,\" he said. \"Do not light a lamp. Ask me anything but that.\"",
        "She lived in the palace this way for some time. She was happy, in a strange way. Her body was honored. Her mind was less so, because she could not see the face of the man who came to her. She asked, eventually, if her sisters could visit. He warned her against it but he did not refuse her.",
        "Her sisters came. Her sisters had been jealous of her since they were children. They saw the gold on the walls and the soft beds and the silent attentive food. They listened to her describe the husband she had not seen. They said, gently, with the small smile of people enjoying themselves, \"Sister. The oracle said a monster. You have not seen him. He comes only in the dark. He has forbidden you to look. What if he is a monster, and is fattening you up, and one of these nights he means to eat you and the child you are now carrying?\"",
        "Psyche, who had been sure, became unsure. She could not unhear the small smile. After her sisters had left she lay awake a long time. That night, when the husband had fallen asleep beside her, she lit a small oil lamp.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "She bent over him with the lamp.",
        "She saw — not a monster — but a young man with golden curls and the smooth shoulder-blade of a sleeping boy and a pair of soft white wings folded against his back, the bow and quiver of an archer leaning against the bedside. She saw him and she understood at once who he was, and she understood at once that her sisters had lied, and she leaned closer in love and gratitude and stunned wonder.",
        "A drop of hot oil fell from the lamp onto the boy's bare shoulder.",
        "He woke. He looked at her. His face went through three expressions: surprise, sorrow, and the calm of a boy who has just understood that the world is going to be, from this moment forward, a much harder place to live in. He said only one thing — \"Oh, Psyche\" — and then he stood up and his wings caught him and he flew out the open window into the dawn.",
        "She tried to follow. She fell. She could not fly. The palace dissolved around her into the morning mist. She found herself on the bare grass of an empty hilltop with no walls in any direction, alone, holding a small extinguished lamp.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "She walked. She walked for months. She begged for shelter at every temple she came to. The other gods were sympathetic but would not help — they would not cross Venus, and they had figured out by now whose son the boy in question was. At last, with nowhere else to go, Psyche walked up to the palace of Venus herself and knelt at the door.",
        "Venus opened it. Venus had her son's bandage on her dressing table. She looked at the small dusty pregnant girl on her doorstep and she said, sweetly, \"You wish to win him back? You wish me to consider you. Very well. There are tasks. Begin with this one.\"",
        "She took Psyche to a vast room and dumped onto the floor a heap of mixed seeds — wheat, barley, millet, lentil, poppy, vetch — a small mountain of them, mingled. \"Sort them,\" she said. \"By dawn. Each kind into its own pile. If you fail, you die.\"",
        "She left. Psyche sat down beside the heap and wept. She could not have sorted a fraction of it in a week.",
        "Then a single ant came across the floor. The ant looked at her, then at the heap. The ant tapped his antennae, and from every crack in the floor and every gap in the wall a long line of ants began to come out. They came in their thousands. They went to work. Tiny mandibles picked up tiny seeds. Tiny legs carried them in tiny processions to seven separate corners. By dawn the seeds were sorted.",
        "Venus, returning, frowned. She set a second task. Bring me, she said, a tuft of wool from the savage golden sheep that graze in the river meadows. Bring me a cup of water from the river that flows down from the cliff at the edge of the world. Bring me, for the last task, a small box of beauty from Persephone, the queen of the underworld.",
        "Psyche went into the lower country. She had been told, by a kind voice in the air, exactly which path to take, exactly which coins to put on her tongue, exactly when to refuse a hand offered, exactly when to refuse a meal. She took the box from Persephone. She carried it back. She had been warned not to open it. She was, by then, very tired and very curious and only a little bit pregnant. On the long climb back up she stopped and opened the lid for one small moment.",
        "It was not beauty. It was the sleep of the underworld, and it rolled out of the box like a slow grey smoke and folded over her, and she went down on the path in a dead faint.",
        "And Cupid — who had been healing on his mother's couch, and who had loved Psyche the whole time, and who had been watching her from the high windows of his recovery — could no longer bear it. He flew out the window. He found her on the path. He scraped the sleep back into the box with his hand. He kissed her awake.",
        "He took her up to Olympus. He stood her in front of his mother and the assembled gods and said, \"Enough. I am marrying her. Make her immortal. Make this the wedding of a god.\"",
        { style: "quote", text: "The soul, in the older language, has to walk through her own ashes before she is ready to live in the upper country with her love. The walking is the marriage. The blister on the heel is the wedding ring." },
        "They did. Psyche, who had been a princess, was given a cup of nectar and became a goddess herself. The child she carried was born safely and was named Voluptas, which is to say, joy. Venus, who had been outflanked, smiled the small smile of a woman who has decided to call this a victory and to claim the credit for it. The wedding feast was attended by all the gods. The girl who had once stood on a high lonely rock at dawn drank from the same cup as her husband at the end of a very long road."
    ]
},

{
    id: "aeneas-underworld",
    title: "Aeneas in the Underworld",
    subtitle: "A father, a sibyl, a golden bough, and the long parade of unborn Romans",
    civilization: "roman",
    themes: ["Father & son", "Underworld", "Destiny", "Founding"],
    content: [
        "Aeneas was a Trojan. He had escaped the burning of Troy by carrying his old father Anchises out on his back through the smoke, his small son Iulus walking alongside, his wife Creusa, who was supposed to have followed, lost in the confusion of the night. He had wandered the Mediterranean for years afterward — survived storms, survived Carthage and the queen Dido who had loved him, buried his old father at last on the western coast of Sicily — and he had come, at the gods' insistence, to the shore of Italy. There was a city he was meant to found there. He did not know yet exactly where, or how, or whether he had it in him.",
        "He went, on the advice of an oracle, to consult the Sibyl of Cumae. She lived in a cave on the Italian coast, an old woman with a hundred mouths in the rock around her chamber, and the prophecies came out of those mouths in a wind that scattered them across the floor on dry leaves, and the asker had to be quick to catch them before they blew away.",
        "Aeneas knelt at the threshold. He said, \"I need to see my father. I need his counsel. Show me the path down.\"",
        "The Sibyl looked at him a long time. \"The path down,\" she said, \"is easy. The doors of dark Dis are open day and night. But to come back up — that is the work. To come back up takes the favor of a god, and a token. Find me, in the wood beyond the cave, a tree on which a single golden bough is growing. Pluck the bough. If it comes free in your hand, the gods are with you. If it does not, no force on earth will tear it loose, and you will not pass.\"",
        "He went into the wood. The wood was thick. He walked for hours. He saw, at last — high in a single oak — a small soft glimmer. He climbed. The bough came away in his hand at the first touch, like a ripe fruit. He brought it back.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The Sibyl led him down. She made the offerings. She spoke the words. The earth opened.",
        "They walked first through a vestibule where the small bad spirits live — Worry, Old Age, Disease, Hunger, Want, Sleep, the bad Dreams. They passed without stopping. They came to the river Acheron. Charon the ferryman saw the golden bough in Aeneas's hand and grunted and let them aboard without coin.",
        "On the far bank a great crowd of dim souls stood, the unburied, the ones whose bodies had not been given proper rites. They could not cross. They had to wait a hundred years on that shore. Among them Aeneas saw the helmsman of his own ship, Palinurus, who had fallen from the deck unseen one night and had washed up on a beach where no one had buried him. Aeneas wept and promised that the place would be marked and a tomb built; the helmsman's face calmed slightly and he stepped back into the crowd.",
        "Past Cerberus — whom the Sibyl drugged with a honey-cake — they walked into the country of the dead proper. Aeneas saw, in a section reserved for those who had died of love, a familiar figure walking under the trees. Dido, the queen of Carthage, who had killed herself when he had sailed away from her on the gods' command. He went to her. He stretched out his hands. He tried to speak. He said, weeping, \"Queen — I did not want to leave. The gods compelled me.\"",
        "She turned her face away. She would not answer him. She walked on into the trees with her former husband Sychaeus, who had been waiting for her. Aeneas stood in the path and could not move for a long time.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "They came at last to the Elysian Fields, where the blessed walk in long bright grass under a sun that never sets. There Aeneas found his father. Anchises was younger here than he had been at his death — not the bent old man Aeneas had carried out of Troy, but the strong man he had been before. He came to Aeneas and embraced him three times. Three times the embrace passed through and gathered nothing, because the dead are made of a different substance than the living. Anchises laughed gently and said, \"Son. Don't try. I cannot be held. But I can be heard. Walk with me. There is something I want you to see.\"",
        "He led Aeneas to a quiet glade. In the glade ran a river — the river Lethe, the river of forgetting — and along the river drifted a long line of souls, indistinct, waiting their turn at the water.",
        "\"These,\" said Anchises, \"are the souls who are about to be born. They drink from this river to forget what they were before. Then they go up. Look — look. I want to show you who they will be.\"",
        "He pointed. He named names. He named, one by one, the long line of unborn Romans who would descend from Aeneas's small son Iulus. Numa, the law-giving king. The Tarquins, good and bad. Brutus, who would expel the kings and found the Republic. The Scipios, who would crush Carthage. The Catos. The Gracchi. Marius. Sulla. Caesar. Augustus, his shoulders broader than any king's, who would close the gates of war and give the Mediterranean a hundred years of peace under one law. Marcellus, the young heir who would die before his time, walking with his head lowered, sad even in the queue.",
        "Aeneas saw them all. He saw the long shape of his descendants. He saw Roman armies marching over Britain, Roman senators arguing in marble halls, Roman highways running across maps that had not been drawn yet. He saw the city he had not yet founded standing at the center of it for a thousand years.",
        "His father, beside him, said quietly: \"Others, perhaps, will sculpt softer faces in marble than the Romans will. Others will hammer out arguments in court better. Others will track the courses of stars more elegantly. But you, Roman — you remember to rule the peoples with rule of law, to spare the conquered, and to break the proud. Those are your arts. Carry them well.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Aeneas climbed back up. He had been changed by what he had seen. He was no longer a man wandering — he was a man with a known weight on his shoulders, the small heavy weight of an unborn city. He went out the gate of the underworld, the gate of ivory through which (the poet hints, in a line scholars have argued about for two thousand years) false dreams pass — and he stepped back into the upper sun, and the Sibyl walked beside him, and the war that lay ahead in Italy and the city he would build at its end were no longer abstract to him.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Whoever has seen the long line of their descendants drinking forgetfulness on the bank of a river is no longer free. They cannot choose otherwise. They must build the road that line will walk on, and they must not waste it." },
        "He fought the war he had to fight. He married the Italian princess Lavinia he had been promised. He founded the small city of Lavinium, from which his son Iulus would, in time, found Alba Longa, from which two grandsons of an exiled king would be raised by a wolf and would found the city Anchises had named at the river bank. He never spoke afterward of what he had seen in the underworld. He had been told that the strength to bear it was in the not-saying. He bore it that way."
    ]
}
);

