window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "sekhmet",
    title: "The Rage of Sekhmet",
    subtitle: "How the lion-headed daughter was stopped, at the last hour, by a flood of red beer",
    civilization: "egyptian",
    themes: ["Wrath", "Mercy", "Lion", "Cunning kindness"],
    content: [
        "Ra, the sun-god, was old. He had ruled the upper and lower kingdoms for so long that his bones, the priests said, had become silver and his flesh had become gold and his hair had become lapis lazuli, and the people of the upper kingdom — having seen, generation after generation, that he was old and seemed to be growing slower — had begun to plot against him. They said: he is no longer the king he was. We could rule ourselves. We could even rule him. They held meetings about it.",
        "Ra heard. Ra had not become as old as he had become without keeping an ear to the ground of his own country. He summoned a council of the gods. He told them what he had heard. He asked their advice. The gods, after some discussion, recommended his daughter Hathor — the cow-eyed goddess of joy and music and motherhood — for a delicate task. \"Send her down,\" they said. \"She has a side most mortals have not seen. Let her show it to them. The plotters will think twice afterward.\"",
        "Ra spoke a word and Hathor changed. Her cow ears became a lion's. Her gentle wide face became a long muzzle full of teeth. Her hands became paws with claws like sickles. She was no longer Hathor. She was Sekhmet — \"The Powerful One\" — the lion-headed daughter, the breath of the desert wind, the goddess of plague and war and any kind of killing the day asked for. She went down to the upper kingdom.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "She fell upon the people who had been plotting. She fell on them in the fields where they were harvesting wheat. She fell on them in the squares of their towns. She tore them. The blood was a kind of wine to her — she had never tasted it before, and she found that she liked it, and she could not stop. She killed her father's enemies in a single morning. The morning ran into afternoon. The afternoon ran into evening. She kept killing.",
        "She had begun to kill not only the conspirators but the bystanders also. She had begun to kill not only the bystanders but the children. She had begun to kill not only the children but the cattle. She had begun, in short, to be unable to differentiate between what had been ordered of her and what was simply the ongoing momentum of her appetite, and she was now well into the second.",
        "Ra, watching from the high country, understood with a slow horror what he had unleashed. He called her back. She did not hear him. She kept killing. He sent messengers. They were eaten by the desert wind that was now her breath. The lion-headed daughter walked across the upper kingdom and the wheat lay flat behind her and the wells ran red.",
        "Ra summoned his council again. \"Stop her,\" he said. \"I made an error. Stop her. She will leave nothing.\"",
        "The gods conferred. Then a small minor god — a brewer, by trade, kept around the council mostly for his beer — coughed and said: \"Lord. Listen. The blood is what is doing this. She loves the blood. We cannot take that away from her by force. But we can perhaps trick her with a substitute.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "They sent down to the temple at Heliopolis a thousand jars of the strongest beer in the kingdom — barley beer, eight times distilled — and they dyed every jar of it the deep dark red of fresh blood with the juice of pomegranates and red ochre and certain ground roots. They had the jars carried by night to a great flat stretch of plain where the goddess was expected to pass at dawn. They tipped the jars over. The blood-colored beer flooded across the plain — a shallow lake of it, three fingers deep, sun-warm, smelling, to a creature who had been gorging on blood for two days, exactly like more.",
        "Sekhmet came over the rise at dawn. She saw the lake. She bent her muzzle and drank.",
        "She drank for a long time. She drank, in fact, until she had drained most of the lake — for she was a goddess, and her thirst was a goddess's thirst — and then she sat down on the warm sand and her enormous golden eyes blinked once, and twice, and the world swayed pleasantly around her, and she thought: I have not felt this way before. This is a new way. This is also nice.",
        "She fell back into the dust and slept. She slept for three days. While she slept the surviving people of the upper kingdom crept out of their hiding places and tended their wounded and buried their dead. The ground around her, where she had drunk, was the color of evening.",
        "When she woke, she was Hathor again. Her cow ears had returned. Her face was wide and gentle. She did not remember most of what she had done. She remembered only that she had been thirsty and that the thirst had been very large and that someone had brought her something kind to drink at the edge of it. She got up. She walked back up to her father's high country.",
        { style: "quote", text: "There are rages that cannot be stopped by an order or by a counter-rage. They can be stopped only by a kindness so well-disguised that the rage itself does not notice that it is being healed. The brewer is sometimes more useful than the army." },
        "From that day forward the priests of Egypt held a great festival every year called the Festival of Drunkenness, in which jars of red beer were poured out by the thousand and the people drank deeply and danced and slept on the warm sand of the temple courtyards. They were re-enacting the moment the lion-headed daughter had been turned back. They were also reminding the gods, gently, that the world had been pulled back from her once, and could be again, and ought not to be tested twice."
    ]
},

{
    id: "hathor-distant",
    title: "Hathor and the Distant Goddess",
    subtitle: "How Thoth went south to coax a sulking goddess out of the Nubian desert",
    civilization: "egyptian",
    themes: ["Music", "Persuasion", "Reconciliation", "Wandering"],
    content: [
        "Some time after the affair of the red beer, Hathor — peaceable Hathor, cow-eared, mistress of music — had a quarrel with her father Ra. The exact cause is not preserved in the records. Some priests say she felt unappreciated. Some say she had been blamed for the killing in the upper kingdom even though it had been Sekhmet, the other side of her, who had done it. Some say she was simply tired. In any case, she walked out. She went south. She kept going south until she was past the cataracts of the Nile, deep into the desert of Nubia, and there she settled, and there she would not come back.",
        "Without Hathor the upper kingdom went grey. Music went out of it. Cattle went dry. Couples no longer fell in love. Babies were not conceived. Festivals stopped because nobody had the heart for them. Ra noticed within a season. He sat on his throne and the throne felt thin under him. He understood that he could not run a kingdom on grain alone. He needed his daughter back.",
        "He could not himself go after her. He was the sun. The sun does not go to fetch a daughter; the daughter comes to the sun. He sent Thoth instead.",
        "Thoth was the ibis-headed god, the god of writing and of mediation and of the long patient sentence. He took the form of a baboon — for the baboon was sacred to him also, and a baboon could climb the cliffs and could speak to a goddess in a familiar mammalian voice that an ibis perhaps could not. He took with him a small drum and a satchel of stories. He went south.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He found her in a stony valley deep in the desert. She had taken on her lion form again, but a smaller, leaner version — a desert cat, mostly hidden in the rocks. She was watching gazelle. Her tail twitched. Her eyes were yellow.",
        "Thoth, the baboon, sat down on a rock at a respectful distance. He did not approach. He did not address her by name. He took his small drum out of his satchel and tapped a slow soft pattern on it. He began to talk.",
        "He told her a story. He told her the story of the bull and the bee — a small fable, no morals, just a long detailed account of how the bull had wanted to eat the flower the bee was sitting on, and how the bee had explained, patiently, all the reasons not to. The lion in the rocks, hearing the story, did not move. But her tail stopped twitching.",
        "He told her another story. The story of the cat and the vulture, who had each had a nest in the same tree and had fought, and had been judged in court by the lion of the tribunal, and the judgment had not pleased either of them. The lion in the rocks let out a small puff of breath through her nose, which was almost a laugh.",
        "He told her another. And another. The light shifted. The day grew old. The lion crept, by small degrees, closer. She began to lie on her belly with her eyes half-closed. She listened.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He told her, eventually, the story of her father. Of how the king of the gods sat on a high seat in a country that had grown grey, of how the festivals had stopped, of how he was old and he was lonely and he had begun, in the last few weeks, to talk to the wall of his throne room because there was nobody else who would understand him.",
        "He told her, in particular, that her father had wept. He told her how he had wept. He told her — for the baboon was a god of accurate description — what shape the tears had taken on the silver of the king's old beard.",
        "The lion lifted her head. Her eyes were no longer yellow. They were the color of warm earth. She uncoiled herself and stood up, and as she stood she lengthened, and as she lengthened her face changed, and the cow ears came back. By the time she was on her feet she was Hathor again. She wore the rough cloak of the desert and her hair was tangled with sand, but she was Hathor.",
        "\"Take me home,\" she said quietly.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "They walked north together. Thoth, still in his baboon form, walked beside her. As they passed each town the people, who had been told nothing, somehow knew. They came out of their houses. They began to play music — small drums, small flutes — that they had not played in months. Couples reached for each other's hands. The cattle in the byres pressed their faces against the slats and lowed.",
        "By the time Hathor reached her father's city the road behind her was a long slow dancing procession of every village she had passed. Ra came out of his throne room into the courtyard. He was very small in his old age. He looked at his daughter. He held out his arms.",
        "She walked into them. She stayed.",
        { style: "quote", text: "What is gone is not always brought back by an army. Sometimes it is brought back by a small ibis-headed god in the form of a baboon, sitting on a rock, telling stories until the listener has forgotten why she went away." },
        "The Festival of the Return of the Distant Goddess was kept in the temples for two thousand years afterward. The priests would carry her image down the river by night, in a small barque, and would meet it at the temple steps with drums and dancers and the long slow songs of welcome, and the festival was held to ensure that no goddess would ever be allowed to forget the way home, and no king to forget that there are arts of bringing back which are older than the arts of holding."
    ]
},

{
    id: "two-brothers",
    title: "The Tale of the Two Brothers",
    subtitle: "Bata, Anubis, and the heart in the cedar tree",
    civilization: "egyptian",
    themes: ["Brotherhood", "Falsehood", "Heart", "Resurrection"],
    content: [
        "Anubis was the elder. Bata was the younger. They were brothers; both farmers; both careful. Anubis had a wife. Bata, who had no wife of his own, lived with them in his brother's house and worked the fields, and he was so strong he could carry a heavier load than any other man in the village, and he was so gentle the cattle in the byre would lower their heads to his hand without flinching.",
        "One afternoon Anubis sent Bata back to the house from the field to fetch more seed. The wife was inside. She had been watching the younger brother for some time without anyone knowing. When he came in she put a hand on his arm and said softly, \"Stay. Lie with me. There is no one to know.\"",
        "Bata stepped back. He said — gently, because he had been raised gently — \"You are my brother's wife. You raised me almost as a mother. I will not. And I will not say to him what you have said today, because saying so would break his house. But do not say it to me again.\"",
        "He took the seed and walked back to the field. The wife stood in the doorway and watched him go. By the time he had reached the field her face was already arranged into a different story.",
        "When Anubis came home at evening he found his wife on the floor of the house with her hair torn and bruises she had given herself, and she was weeping. She told him a long terrible story about what his brother had tried to do that afternoon. She wept very convincingly. Anubis, who loved his wife, took up his sickle and went out into the field to find his brother and kill him.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Bata, in the byre that evening tending the cattle, heard the cattle low in alarm. The lead cow turned her head and spoke to him in a human voice — for the cattle of Bata had always loved him and had always known things — and she said, \"Brother, your brother is on the path with a sickle and his face is wrong. Run.\"",
        "He ran. He ran across the irrigated lands and across the dry lands, and Anubis ran after him, and the gap between them held. Bata called out as he ran to the sun-god Ra: \"Lord, witness, I have done nothing. Place a barrier between us so I can speak to him before one of us is dead.\"",
        "Ra heard. A river opened in the dry land between the two brothers. The river was deep, and the river was full of crocodiles. Anubis stopped at the bank. Bata stopped on the far bank. They stood looking at each other across the impossible water.",
        "Bata called: \"Brother. Listen. I did nothing. The truth is the opposite of what your wife has told you. Look — \" and he took out a small flint and cut himself, in front of his brother, in a place a man does not cut himself except in the most desperate proof. \" — I am leaving the world of men. I will go far. I will not curse you. But this is what your wife has cost you.\"",
        "He turned and walked away into the country beyond the river.",
        "He went to a far valley in Lebanon. He hid his heart in the topmost branches of a cedar tree there — for he had become, by the cutting, no longer entirely a mortal man — and he made a small cottage at the foot of the tree, and he lived alone.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Anubis, on the home bank, stood for a long time. Then he went back to his house. He found his wife where she had told him to find his brother. He killed her. He threw her body to the dogs. He sat in the empty house for many days.",
        "At length he could no longer bear it. He had lost his brother. He stood up and walked north. He walked for years. He had been told, by an oracle at a shrine on the road, that his brother could be found if he came to a certain valley in Lebanon, and that a sign would be given if his brother yet lived.",
        "The sign was this: when Bata was at last killed in his cottage by a strange chain of misfortunes — for the gods, who were curious, had given him a wife of their own making, and the wife had betrayed him to a passing king who had cut down the cedar tree — the small jar of beer in Anubis's house, far away, would foam over by itself. Anubis kept the jar by him. He waited. One evening the foam came up. Anubis stood up and walked to Lebanon.",
        "He found, in the valley, the small cottage and the felled cedar. He searched the woodchips. He found at last, in the heart of the cedar, the small dried heart of his brother, like a seed. He took it home. He soaked it in cool water for four days and four nights, and on the fourth night the heart began to beat again, and Bata sat up — alive, restored — and the two brothers embraced, and Anubis fell on his face and asked his brother's pardon for having believed his wife.",
        "Bata gave it. Bata had had a long time alone in a cottage to think about pardon. He took up the work of the world again, in a different shape — he became, in some tellings, a sacred bull; in others, a king of Egypt himself — and Anubis lived out his days as the keeper of his brother's house, and the wife who had begun the trouble was already dust.",
        { style: "quote", text: "There are betrayals that take everything and there are forgivenesses that take longer. Both can be done. The brother who walks for years to find a heart in a cedar tree has paid the price of his believing too quickly, and the price is fair." },
        "The story of the two brothers was written down by an Egyptian scribe named Ennana on a long roll of papyrus that survives to this day. It is the oldest story in any human language about a man wrongly accused and a brother who eventually walked to the ends of the earth to make it right, and every later version of that story — and there are many — owes something to this one, in some quiet inheritance the storytellers do not always know they are paying."
    ]
}
);

