window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "baldur",
    title: "The Death of Baldur",
    subtitle: "How a mother got an oath from every thing in the world, except one",
    civilization: "norse",
    themes: ["Death", "Oath", "Mistletoe", "Mother's grief"],
    content: [
        "Baldur was the most beloved of the gods. He was the son of Odin and Frigg, and he was beautiful in a way that the other gods, even the beautiful ones, could not quite match. Light came off him visibly, the way light comes off a clean piece of pale wood at dawn. He was kind. He had no wit, exactly — wit was Loki's department — but he had the rarer gift of being a presence that made the company easier on itself. The whole hall was warmer when he was in it.",
        "He began, one summer, to dream badly. He dreamed of his own death. He dreamed it more than once. He woke shaking. He told his mother.",
        "Frigg, the queen of the gods, did not panic. She was a goddess of the household and a goddess of foresight, and she had the steady practical mind of a woman who had administered a long marriage to Odin. She left her hall and walked the worlds. She went to every thing in every world that could harm her son. She went to fire. She went to water. She went to iron. She went to stone. She went to oak and ash and elm. She went to every disease and every poison. She went to every animal that bites. She asked each of them, individually, by their old name, to swear to her that they would never harm Baldur. And every thing she asked — fire and water and iron and stone and oak and ash and the wolf and the bear and the small biting things in the marshes — every one of them swore. They loved Baldur too.",
        "When she came home she was tired and her face was bright. She told the gods. The gods, delighted, made a game of it. They threw weapons at Baldur. They struck him with iron clubs. They shot arrows at his chest. The weapons turned aside in mid-air. The arrows fell. Baldur stood in the middle of the hall, smiling, untouched, and the gods laughed and threw the next thing.",
        "It became the favorite party game of Asgard. The afternoon of throwing-stuff-at-Baldur. He was, after all, the most beloved.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Loki was watching. Loki had never quite forgiven Baldur for being everyone's favorite. He took the form of an old woman and approached Frigg in the kitchen one evening.",
        "\"Frigg,\" he said, in the old woman's voice. \"It is wonderful, what is happening in the hall. The young god is invulnerable. May I ask — did you really get an oath from every single thing in every world?\"",
        "Frigg, tired and pleased and a little proud, said: \"Every single thing. Except — well, except a small soft plant that grows on the trunks of oaks west of Valhalla. Mistletoe. It is too young and too soft to harm anyone. I did not bother to ask it.\"",
        "Loki nodded courteously. He left the kitchen. He walked west of Valhalla. He found the small soft pale plant on the side of an oak. He cut a sprig. He sharpened the stem to a point.",
        "He went back to the hall. The game was still going on. The gods were laughing and throwing things. Standing at the edge of the circle, watching, was Hodr — Baldur's brother, who was blind. Hodr was not throwing anything. He could not see to throw.",
        "Loki put the small mistletoe dart into Hodr's hand. \"Brother,\" he said, gently, \"why are you not joining? Don't you love him too?\"",
        "Hodr said sadly, \"I am blind. I cannot aim.\"",
        "\"I will guide your hand,\" said Loki. \"Throw.\"",
        "Hodr — innocent, eager, glad to be included — let Loki turn his shoulders. He threw. The small soft sprig of mistletoe flew across the hall and went into Baldur's heart up to the clenched green hand of its leaves.",
        "Baldur, in the middle of the hall, looked down at his chest with the faint surprise of a man who has been told that something cannot happen and is finding that it has. He fell.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The hall went silent.",
        "Frigg, in the kitchen, dropped the spoon she was holding. She did not have to be told. She came running through the doors. She knelt by her son. She took his face in her hands. She had been so careful. She had been so careful. She had asked every thing.",
        "The gods, around her, stood without moving. None of them looked at Hodr, who was holding his empty hand and beginning to understand. None of them, yet, looked at Loki.",
        "Frigg did not weep — not yet. She said, \"Hermod. Brother. Take Sleipnir. Ride to Hel. Beg the queen of the dead to release my son. Promise her anything. Promise her every god will weep. Promise her the world will not stop weeping. Just bring him back.\"",
        "Hermod went. Hel — the queen of the dead, the half-blue half-pale daughter of Loki — heard him out and was, by her own standards, generous. \"If every thing in every world will weep for Baldur,\" she said, \"I will release him. If even one thing refuses to weep, he stays.\"",
        "Hermod rode home. The gods sent out the request. Across all the worlds the message went: weep for Baldur. Weep, every fire, every river, every mountain, every man, every woman, every child, every animal, every blade of grass, every grain of sand. Weep, that he may be released.",
        "And every thing wept. The fires guttered. The rivers slowed. The mountains let down small silver streams. The men in the halls and the women at the looms and the children in the cradles — all of them wept. The animals wept. The trees wept. The grass bent under the weight of its own tears.",
        "All but one.",
        "In a cave by a road sat an old giantess named Thokk. She was very ugly and very alone, and she answered the messenger when he came: \"Thokk will weep dry tears for Baldur's death. He gave me nothing in life and shall have no tears now. Let Hel keep what she has.\"",
        "And the gods, when this report came back, knew at once who Thokk was. There is a kind of malice that even disguise does not hide, and they knew. But the bargain had been made on Hel's terms. One thing had refused. Baldur stayed.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The mother who has gotten an oath from every thing in the world has not yet gotten one from the small soft plant she did not think to ask. The malice that finds the gap is older than the oath." },
        "Baldur was burned on his great ship Hringhorni. His wife Nanna, who could not bear his absence, died of her grief on the threshold and was laid on the pyre beside him. The fire was so bright that it lit the long dark sea between the worlds for a night. The gods stood in a half-circle on the shore and said nothing. They were waiting now, all of them, for the long quiet darkness that would come — for Baldur was the light of the upper hall and the upper hall, without him, was already in some sense a hall already on fire, only nobody would let themselves say so. He would return, the prophecies said, but only after Ragnarok, in the new world, walking out of a hollow oak with the sun on his hair, having waited in Hel's quiet hall the whole long time. They held to that. It was what they had."
    ]
},

{
    id: "mead-of-poetry",
    title: "The Mead of Poetry",
    subtitle: "How Odin became, briefly, an eagle, and brought back the poet's gift",
    civilization: "norse",
    themes: ["Poetry", "Cunning", "Theft for the world", "Eagle"],
    content: [
        "After the war between the Aesir and the Vanir — the two old families of gods — the two families brewed a peace by spitting into a common cauldron. Out of the spit was made a man. He was called Kvasir. He had been formed of the wisdom of both families, and he was, accordingly, the wisest man who had ever lived. He walked the worlds answering questions. There was no question he could not answer. He sat in halls and gave counsel. He sat at fires and gave consolation.",
        "He stayed too long, eventually, with two dwarves named Fjalar and Galar. The dwarves were jealous of him. They killed him. They drained his blood into three vessels: two crocks and a kettle. They mixed the blood with honey. The result was a mead — the first mead of poetry — and whoever drank of it would be able to compose verses that turned a fire warm and made the listeners forgive their old enemies. The dwarves kept the mead in a deep cellar under their hall.",
        "They told the gods, when asked, that Kvasir had choked on his own wisdom — that he had drowned in the volume of his own thoughts. The gods, sad but not yet suspicious, accepted the story.",
        "The dwarves, however, killed a giant later in some other quarrel and were caught. The giant's son Suttung tied them both to a rock at low tide and walked away. They begged for their lives. They had nothing to offer except the mead. They told him about it. They gave it to him. He took it. He let them go.",
        "Suttung carried the mead home and locked it inside a hollow mountain called Hnitbjorg. He set his daughter Gunnlod to guard it. She was not to drink any of it. She was not to give any of it to anyone. He was very strict. He had paid for it in his father's death, and he meant to keep it.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Odin, in his high seat, heard about the mead. He understood at once that without it the world would never have any poetry. He decided he would have to fetch it.",
        "He went south. He took the form of a workman. He came to a field where nine giants were mowing hay together. Their scythes were dull. Odin produced a small whetstone from his pocket. \"For sharpening,\" he said cheerfully, and threw it into the air.",
        "The nine giants caught the whetstone in turn, sharpened their scythes, and the work went so much faster that they could not bear to give the whetstone back. They each grabbed for it. The whetstone is small. They each got a hand on it. The hands tangled. The scythes, which were now extremely sharp, were waving in the air. Within a minute all nine giants were dead, throats cut by each other.",
        "Odin walked on. He came to the farmhouse of the man who had owned the nine giants. The man was called Baugi. Baugi was Suttung's brother. Baugi was now in trouble — the nine giants had been his entire harvest crew and the hay was lying in the fields ungathered.",
        "Odin offered to do the work of the nine, single-handed, for the entire summer. \"In return,\" he said, \"I want one drink of your brother's mead.\"",
        "Baugi laughed. \"That is between you and my brother. He is a hard man. But for the harvest, yes — I will help you ask.\"",
        "Odin worked through the summer. He did the work of nine. The hay was in by the time the snows came. He went with Baugi to Suttung's hall. They asked. Suttung refused. He would not part with a drop. He had paid in blood for it.",
        "Baugi shrugged. He had done what he had promised. Odin had had his asking. Odin, who had not become Odin without expecting precisely this answer, drew Baugi aside and produced a small auger.",
        "\"Drill,\" he said. \"Through the wall of Hnitbjorg. Into the chamber where the mead is kept. Just one small hole. Your brother need not know.\"",
        "Baugi, who was bored and slightly afraid of his brother and also slightly resentful of him, drilled. The auger went through. He pulled it out. \"Done,\" he said.",
        "Odin then changed himself into a snake — a small slim snake, slightly thinner than a worm — and he slipped into the hole. Baugi, realizing too late what was happening, stabbed the auger after him, but the snake had already passed beyond the wall.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Inside the hollow mountain Odin took back his own form. He came face to face with Gunnlod, the giant's daughter, who guarded the three vessels.",
        "She was lonely. Her father had set her there years ago. She had not seen another face but his. Odin spoke to her gently. He stayed three nights with her. She loved him in those three nights — not the love of a fool, but the love of a long-imprisoned daughter for the first interesting person to pass through her cell — and she gave him three drinks of the mead, one each night.",
        "He drained all three vessels in the three drinks. There was none of the mead left in the mountain.",
        "He kissed her. He thanked her. He took the form of an eagle — a very large eagle, the largest the world had ever seen — and he flew up through the smoke-hole of the mountain.",
        "Suttung, outside, saw the eagle come up out of his own mountain. He understood. He took the form of an eagle himself and gave chase.",
        "The two of them flew north across the long sky. Suttung, behind, was gaining. Odin, ahead, was carrying the mead in his crop and could not fly faster without spitting some of it out. The gods of Asgard, watching from the high seats, saw the chase and put out three great vessels in the courtyard of their hall, ready to catch what their king brought.",
        "Odin came in over the wall of Asgard. He was just out of Suttung's reach. He spat the mead into the three vessels — most of it, almost all of it — and as he did, in the strain of the long flight, a few drops escaped him backward, the wrong way, and fell to earth uncaught.",
        "Suttung, just behind, was killed at the wall by the gods who had been waiting for exactly this.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The mead of poetry, brought back by a god who was prepared to be a snake and a workman and a lover and an eagle to bring it, is shared among true poets. The drops that fell the wrong way, and were not caught, are the lot of the bad poets, and there are many of them, and they will not stop." },
        "From that day the gods gave the mead to those mortals who deserved it. The world finally had its poets. They could compose verses that turned a fire warm. They could compose verses that made the listeners forgive their old enemies. They could even compose verses that made a queen weep for a son she had not yet lost. The few drops that had fallen wrong, however, sustained a separate tribe of bad poets that has also continued, in unbroken succession, into every age — and the way to tell them apart from the good ones is the only critical art that has ever finally mattered."
    ]
},

{
    id: "hel",
    title: "Hel and the Dead",
    subtitle: "Of the daughter who was given a kingdom no one else would take",
    civilization: "norse",
    themes: ["Underworld", "Justice", "Solitude", "Inheritance"],
    content: [
        "Loki had three children by the giantess Angrboda. The first was a wolf, named Fenrir, and the gods bound him on an island. The second was a serpent, named Jormungandr, and the gods threw him into the sea. The third was a daughter. Her name was Hel.",
        "Hel was a strange child even by the standards of the children of Loki. From the navel up she was a beautiful young woman — pale, dark-haired, calm-eyed. From the navel down she was a corpse, the flesh greenish and beginning to fall away from the bone. She did not seem to mind. She walked steadily on her dead legs. She ate. She slept. She did not weep.",
        "When the gods took her from Loki and brought her up the long road to Asgard for inspection, Odin looked at her for a long moment. He understood, perhaps faster than anyone else has ever understood, that there was no good place in any of the worlds for this child. The upper hall would not have her. The country of giants would not have her. The world of men was no place for a child who was already partly dead.",
        "He gave her a kingdom of her own.",
        "He sent her down to a country called Niflheim, in the far north, beyond the rim of the worlds, where the cold is older than fire and the dark is older than light. He gave her, in that country, a hall called Eljudnir. He made her queen of it. He told her: every dead person who does not die in battle — every old woman who dies in her sleep, every child who dies of fever, every farmer who dies in his bed — comes to you. They are yours. You are their hostess. Run the hall well.",
        "She bowed her head and went down. She did not weep. She was nine years old.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Eljudnir was a strange hall. The threshold was called Stumbling-block. The bed was called Sick-bed. The plate was called Hunger. The knife was called Famine. Hel had named the furnishings herself in those first long years alone, when she was learning the geography of her own kingdom.",
        "She was not a cruel hostess. She was not a kind one either. She was — and the dead, when they arrived, often noticed it with a strange relief — exactly what they had expected. She did not pretend that the long quiet country was something it was not. She let the new dead sit by the fire. She let them speak of the lives they had left. She did not make them dance. She did not tell them stories. She let the country be what it was, which was a place where one was not asked to be brave or witty any longer.",
        "The dead gathered. Year by year the hall grew larger — for Hel was a queen with a queen's authority, and she could expand her hall as the population required — and the small fires in the long halls of Eljudnir multiplied. Each new arrival was given a place. Each old arrival was allowed to stay. There was no leaving Niflheim. The gates were one-way. Hel was the only one who could open them, and she opened them only for entrance.",
        "Once, only once, was she asked to open them for an exit. The god Hermod came on his eight-legged horse to ask her to release Baldur. Hel listened. Hel was, perhaps, slightly amused that the gods had finally remembered her name. She set her conditions: every thing in every world must weep, and if even one thing refused, Baldur stayed. The bargain was, by her standards, scrupulously fair. One thing did refuse. Baldur stayed.",
        "Baldur sat in the high seat beside her at her own invitation. They had — she said — a great deal to discuss. He was not unhappy in her hall. He had expected, on dying, to be tortured or to be at least neglected. He was instead, for the first time in his life, listened to. Hel had a long quiet attention. She had built her court on it.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "There is a small detail about Hel that the storytellers do not always include but that is worth knowing. When the long darkness of Ragnarok comes and the wolf Fenrir slips his cord and the serpent Jormungandr rises from the sea, Hel — last of Loki's children — sails north on a ship of her own building. Her ship is called Naglfar, and it is built from the untrimmed nails of dead men, because in the country of Hel the long careful keeping of the small refuse of mortality has had its uses. She is the captain of that ship. The dead of her kingdom — the ones who did not die in battle, the ones the upper hall did not want — sail with her. They have been waiting. They sail north, the long line of them, to take part in the ending of the gods.",
        "It is not, however, a vengeful sailing. Hel is not vengeful. She has lived a long time in a quiet country and has acquired the calm of those who know they will be there at the end of every story. She sails because the prophecy has summoned her. She does what is required. She does not gloat.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The daughter who was given a kingdom because no one else would take her became, in time, the queen the dead asked for by name. There are inheritances of refuse that turn out to be inheritances of crown." },
        "After Ragnarok, when the new world rises out of the long sea and the new sun comes up and the few surviving gods sit on the new green grass, the country of Hel does not, the prophecies say, immediately empty. It empties slowly, over an age, as the dead one by one drift up out of Niflheim into the new light. Hel walks her cold halls until the last of them has gone. She is the last to leave. When the last fire in Eljudnir is out she shuts the door behind her and walks up the long road north herself, and what becomes of her after that the prophets do not know. The prophets know only that she goes, and that the cold halls behind her remain unattended forever after, and that the kingdom of the dead, in the new world, has no queen at all because perhaps the new world does not need one."
    ]
}
);

