window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "izanagi-izanami",
    title: "Izanagi and Izanami",
    subtitle: "The first marriage, the first death, and a husband who looked back too soon",
    civilization: "japanese",
    themes: ["Creation", "Death", "Underworld", "Looking back"],
    content: [
        "When the world was a thin grey soup and the islands had not yet been made, the high gods of the upper plain sent down two of their younger members — a brother and a sister, Izanagi and Izanami — and gave them a long jeweled spear and told them: go, make land. The two of them went down to the floating bridge of heaven, which is a kind of long curved cloud-causeway, and they leaned out and lowered the spear into the soup, and they stirred. They lifted the spear. From the tip of it a few drops of brine fell back, and where the drops fell they made islands. The islands cooled and dried. The islands became Japan.",
        "Izanagi and Izanami went down to live on the islands they had made. They built a hall on a quiet bay. They walked around the central pillar of the hall — Izanagi to the left, Izanami to the right — and when they met on the far side, Izanami spoke first: \"How wonderful! What a fine man I have met.\"",
        "They had a child. The child was malformed, a soft creature without bones, called Hiruko, the Leech-Child. They put it into a reed boat and pushed it out to sea, and they grieved.",
        "They went back up to the high plain to ask what had gone wrong. The elder gods listened. The elder gods said, kindly, \"You walked the pillar correctly. But she spoke first. The man should have spoken first. Try again. Walk again. Speak again, in the right order.\"",
        "They went back down. They walked the pillar again. They met on the far side. Izanagi, this time, spoke first: \"How wonderful! What a fine woman I have met.\" Izanami answered. They had children. They had eight more major islands. They had every river and every mountain and every wind. They had the gods of grain and the gods of fire.",
        "The god of fire — Kagutsuchi — burned his mother as he came out of her. Izanami died of the burning.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Izanagi could not bear it. He wept on her cooling body. He could not be persuaded to leave the hall. He held her until the body grew heavy. Then he laid her down and stood up and went out into the country.",
        "He had loved her. He went after her.",
        "He walked west. He walked into the country of the dead. The road went down. The road grew dim. He came at last to a great stone hall with a heavy door. He called her name through the door.",
        "She answered from inside. Her voice was the voice he knew, but slower, with a small reverberation as if from a cold room. \"Husband. You should not have come. I am sorry. I would come back with you, but I have already eaten the food of this country. I cannot leave easily. Wait at the door. Let me ask the lords of this place if there is any way. Do not — please, do not — open the door before I return. Promise.\"",
        "He promised. She went back into the hall.",
        "He waited. He waited a long time. Time in the country of the dead does not run quite at the rate of time above. He grew restless. He grew impatient. He had been told not to look. He decided to look.",
        "He broke off one tooth from the comb in his hair, lit it as a small torch, and pushed open the door.",
        "She was there in the dim hall. She was on the floor. The body had grown beyond recognition — swollen, dark, the small white things of decay already moving across her shoulders, the eight thunder-gods born of her decay sitting in a half-circle around her. She was no longer the woman who had walked the pillar. She was the country of the dead made flesh.",
        "She turned her face to the small light of the comb-tooth. She saw him. She saw what he had seen.",
        "Her face did not weep. Her face went, instead, to a slow contained fury — the fury of a woman who had been seen against her own request, in the worst moment of her existence, by the man she had most wanted not to see her like that. She rose. She set the eight thunder-gods after him. She set the foul hags of the underworld after him. She came running herself.",
        "Izanagi ran. He ran out of the hall. He ran up the long road. He threw down behind him three peaches he had brought as offerings, and the peaches confused his pursuers and slowed them. He ran to the mouth of the cave that connected the lower country to the upper. He came out into the gray light. He pushed a great boulder across the entrance of the cave — a rock so heavy a thousand men could not move it — and sealed her in.",
        "From the other side of the rock she called out, in a voice that was no longer his wife's: \"Husband. For this — for what you have done — I will kill a thousand of your people every day. I will take them down here with me.\"",
        "He answered, weeping but firm: \"Then I will see to it that fifteen hundred are born every day. The world will go on. It will go on without you, but it will go on.\"",
        { style: "quote", text: "Whoever insists on looking at the death of what they loved does not always get to keep the love. Some thresholds are doors of ivory: what you see beyond them, you cannot unsee, and what you have unsealed, you cannot reseal in time." },
        "He went down to a river and bathed. He washed off the dust of the lower country. From the washing of his left eye came the goddess Amaterasu, the sun. From the washing of his right eye came the god Tsukuyomi, the moon. From the washing of his nose came the storm-god Susanoo. The three of them rose up out of the water as he washed, his three best children, and the world that was going to go on was already, in his hands, beginning."
    ]
},

{
    id: "tamamo-no-mae",
    title: "Tamamo-no-Mae",
    subtitle: "The most beautiful woman at court, and the nine tails she had been hiding",
    civilization: "japanese",
    themes: ["Trickster", "Court intrigue", "Disguise", "Nine tails"],
    content: [
        "She came to the imperial court at Kyoto when she was perhaps twenty. No one quite knew where she had come from. A retainer had brought her in with a letter of introduction from a minor governor in the provinces. The letter, when later examined, turned out to bear the seal of a man who had been dead for ten years. Nobody had thought to check at the time.",
        "Her name, she said, was Tamamo-no-Mae. She was, beyond argument, the most beautiful woman ever to enter the court. She was also the most accomplished. She could compose poetry in seven styles. She could play the koto. She could hold her own in a conversation about the Lotus Sutra with the chief abbot of the imperial chapel and emerge from it having the better of him. She was witty without being cruel. She was learned without being pedantic. She seemed always to know what the other person needed to hear, and to know it just before they themselves did.",
        "The young Emperor Toba fell in love with her within a season. He made her his favorite. Within a year she was, in everything but title, the most powerful woman at court.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Then the Emperor began to fall ill.",
        "The illness was strange. He had no fever. He had no cough. He simply grew weaker. Some days he could not get out of bed. Some days he could not lift a brush. The court physicians applied every art they knew. They prescribed every herb. They held every ceremony. Nothing helped. He grew thinner. His complexion grew the color of old wax.",
        "Tamamo-no-Mae nursed him. She was tender. She wept at his bedside. She held his hand for hours. The court watched her tenderness and was moved.",
        "But there was, at the court, an older man. His name was Abe no Yasuchika, and he was a diviner — an onmyoji, the imperial reader of strange signs — and he had served three emperors. He had begun, in the past months, to feel a small wrongness whenever Tamamo-no-Mae passed him in the corridor. He could not at first name what it was. He felt only that the woman was casting a wrong shadow. He watched her for a long time.",
        "He went to the Emperor in private. He said: \"Lord. With your permission. There is a ceremony I would like to perform. It is, perhaps, intrusive. It will tell us things we do not currently know about your household.\"",
        "The Emperor, who was now too weak to refuse anything reasonable, gave permission.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The ceremony was held at midnight in the great audience hall. All the senior officers of the court were present. Tamamo-no-Mae was present too. She had been told only that her presence was required. Abe no Yasuchika opened the ceremony with the usual chants. Then he read out, in a voice that carried, the long invocation of the names — the formal listing of every spirit and every shape and every disguise the older books knew of.",
        "When he came to a particular line — a particular phrase used to address one specific kind of disguised creature — Tamamo-no-Mae stiffened where she sat. She had not been aware that she was going to. The stiffening lasted only a heartbeat. The court would not have noticed it. Abe no Yasuchika was watching only for it. He saw it. He read on.",
        "When the ceremony ended Tamamo-no-Mae stood up. She bowed. Her color was very high. She left the hall.",
        "She never returned to the palace.",
        "By morning she had vanished, leaving every silk garment in her chamber neatly folded. The Emperor, hearing the news, sat up in bed for the first time in weeks. By the second day his color was returning. By the seventh he was eating properly. The court physicians, who had not been able to save him, were embarrassed and grateful.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Tamamo-no-Mae was tracked east, into the country. She went into the wilderness. The Emperor sent two of his greatest archers — Miura no Suke and Kazusa no Suke — with their hunting hounds and a small army of beaters, and they ran her down across two provinces. They cornered her at last on the broad treeless plain of Nasu.",
        "What they cornered was not, by then, a woman. It was a fox. A great pale-furred fox the size of a horse, with nine long pale tails fanning behind her like a slow burning flag. She had used the woman shape for a hundred years. She was, perhaps, eight hundred years old by some accounts. She had been at the court of China before she had come to Japan, and at the court of India before that, and the long pattern of her life was a pattern of attaching herself to a king who interested her, draining him, and leaving when she was about to be discovered. She was tired now. She had been seen.",
        "The two archers loosed at the same moment. Both arrows struck. The fox fell. The nine tails fanned out around her in the long grass and went still.",
        "Where the body lay, a black stone formed in the ground. The stone was called the Sessho-seki — the Killing Stone — and for centuries afterward any bird that flew over it fell out of the sky, any animal that walked too near collapsed, any traveler who rested against it died of an unseen poison. The killing in the woman had not stopped at the death of the woman. It had soaked into the stone. The stone became a place pilgrims warned each other about.",
        "Some say a Buddhist priest came many centuries later, prayed at the stone, and the stone split open and the long anger left it at last. The split is visible to this day. People photograph it.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Whoever has the gift of being exactly what each person needs in each moment is a creature with nine tails, fanned, behind her. Watch her. Even when she is not eating you, she is at least counting." },
        "The Emperor Toba lived. He was never quite the same. He kept, in a small lacquered box, the silk fan she had once given him, and on bad evenings he would take it out and look at it and remember the woman who had been there at his bedside, and remember that the love had been real, even if the woman had not — and this puzzle, of how a real love can be wholly extended toward a creature who was never quite a person, is the puzzle the storytellers leave to the listener, because they cannot resolve it themselves."
    ]
}
);

/* ═══════════════════════════ CHINESE ═══════════════════════════ */

window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "pangu",
    title: "Pangu Splits the World",
    subtitle: "How a giant in an egg pushed earth and sky apart, and what became of his bones",
    civilization: "chinese",
    themes: ["Creation", "Sacrifice", "Cosmos", "Body"],
    content: [
        "In the very beginning there was no world. There was only an egg. The egg was vast — larger than any star — and inside the egg was a single sleeping giant. His name was Pangu. He had no parents. He had been there always. He slept inside the egg for eighteen thousand years, curled in the dark, breathing slowly, growing.",
        "On the eighteen-thousandth year he opened his eyes. He saw nothing. He moved his hand. His knuckle struck the inside of the shell. He pushed.",
        "The shell cracked. The cracked egg released its contents. The lighter substance — the clean clear yang — drifted upward and became the sky. The heavier substance — the murky yin — sank downward and became the earth.",
        "But the two substances had been together too long. They wanted to come back together. The sky began to drift down toward the earth. The earth began to rise up toward the sky. Pangu, standing between them, understood that if they met he would be crushed and the world he had just been born into would be unmade.",
        "He set his shoulders against the sky. He set his feet against the earth. He pushed.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He pushed for another eighteen thousand years.",
        "Each day the sky rose ten feet. Each day the earth sank ten feet. Each day Pangu's body grew ten feet to keep pace, because he had to remain the spacer between them. By the end of the eighteen thousand years the sky was as high as it now is, the earth was as deep as it now is, and Pangu was an unimaginably tall column standing between them, exhausted past recovery.",
        "He let out a long breath, and lay down, and died.",
        "His body did not stop being useful. The breath that came out of his mouth became the wind and the clouds. His voice became the thunder. His left eye became the sun. His right eye became the moon. His four limbs became the four cardinal directions and the four great mountains that mark them. His blood became the rivers. His muscles became the fields. His hair became the stars. His beard became the long thin streaks of cloud at high altitude. His teeth and bones became the metals and minerals buried in the earth. His sweat became the rain. The fleas that had lived on him through his eighteen thousand years of sleeping became — by some accounts — the first animals, and by other accounts the first human beings.",
        "Either way, every part of him was used. Nothing was wasted. The world we now stand on is, by parts, the body of the giant who pushed sky and earth apart and could not afterwards rest until he had become the ground we walk on.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "There are subtler details the priests of the older Daoist schools liked to add. They said that the world Pangu made was not only physical. He had also, in his long pushing, organized the principles that govern the physical. The five elements — wood, fire, earth, metal, water — were arranged by him before he died. The eight trigrams of the Yi Jing — the great divinatory pattern of broken and unbroken lines — were said to have been first traced by him with the stub of one fingernail in the new mud of the first earth. The long order that everything still operates by — the careful interleaving of yin and yang in the world's procedures — is the mental architecture of a being who pushed two things apart for so long that he had time to think about what was going to happen between them once they were apart.",
        "Some accounts add that Pangu did not die alone. The four cardinal sacred beasts — the Azure Dragon of the East, the White Tiger of the West, the Red Bird of the South, the Black Tortoise of the North — were born from the four corners of his outstretched limbs in the moment of his death, and they took their stations at the four directions and have stood there as the guardians of the world since. The astrologers of every later dynasty mapped the heavens by them. The architects of every later capital aligned the city walls to them. The compass that the Chinese gave the world a few thousand years later, with its needle pointing south rather than north (in the older Chinese convention), was, at root, an instrument for keeping faith with the Black Tortoise's quarter and the Red Bird's quarter as Pangu had, at his last breath, set them.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Whoever has held two impossible things apart for the long age it required will not, in the end, be left over. They will be made into the very space they kept open, and forgotten by the people who walk freely through it." },
        "There are no temples to Pangu in China — or there are very few — because he is not the kind of god who needs offerings. He has already given everything. The offerings he would have wanted have already been made, and they have been made by him. The peasant who looks up at the moon and sees the right eye of a giant has paid him a tribute the giant requires no priest to solicit. The blacksmith who hammers iron from a vein in the rock has paid him a tribute too. We are all walking around inside Pangu, all the time, in the long quiet aftermath of his eighteen-thousand-year shift."
    ]
},

{
    id: "monkey-king",
    title: "The Monkey King",
    subtitle: "How a stone monkey learned the seventy-two transformations and was nearly contained",
    civilization: "chinese",
    themes: ["Trickster", "Pride", "Pilgrimage", "Cage"],
    content: [
        "On the Mountain of Flowers and Fruit there was a stone. The stone had been on the mountain since the beginning of time. Wind and rain and the gentle accumulating attention of the sun had been working on it for ages. One spring morning, with a small crack and a puff of dust, the stone split, and out of it stepped a monkey.",
        "He was the size of any monkey. He looked like any monkey. But his eyes shone with a strange clean light, because he had not been born of a monkey mother — he had been born of a stone, and a stone is patient, and a stone, when it does at last give birth, gives birth to something that will not stop.",
        "He fell in with the other monkeys of the mountain. He learned to climb. He learned to forage. He distinguished himself within a month by leaping through the great waterfall at the top of the mountain — which the other monkeys had been afraid to do for generations — and discovering, behind it, a wonderful cave they could all live in. They made him their king. They named him Sun Wukong.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He was, however, a stone monkey, and a stone monkey is not satisfied with merely a kingdom of monkeys. He grew restless. He wanted to know things. He left the mountain. He walked east. He walked west. He found at last, in a cave on a far mountain, a Daoist sage named Subhuti, and he knelt at the sage's feet and asked to be taught.",
        "The sage looked at him a long time. \"What do you want to learn?\" he asked.",
        "\"Everything.\"",
        "The sage smiled. He took him in. Sun Wukong learned to read in a year. He learned the techniques of immortality in three. He learned the seventy-two transformations — by which a being can change his shape into any of seventy-two specific things, including a fish, a sparrow, a swarm of midges, a small piece of incense smoke. He learned the cloud-somersault — by which one leap covers eighteen thousand miles. He was, by the end of his apprenticeship, possibly the most dangerous mortal who had ever lived.",
        "He went back to the mountain. He found the Dragon King of the Eastern Sea and demanded a weapon worthy of him. The Dragon King, terrified, gave him a great iron staff that had been used to set the depths of the ocean — a staff that could grow as large as a mountain or shrink to the size of a needle, depending on its master's wish. Sun Wukong tucked the needle behind his ear and went home.",
        "He went next to the underworld. He found the books in which the years of his life had been written. He crossed his name out. He crossed out the names of all his monkey friends too, while he was at it.",
        "He went next to a banquet of the immortals — uninvited — and ate the peaches of immortality, all of them, the fruits that the queen of heaven had been carefully cultivating for nine thousand years for one ceremonial occasion. He stole the elixir of life from the alchemy lab. He drank it. He went home and slept it off.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The Jade Emperor, ruler of heaven, had reached the limit of his patience. He sent the entire heavenly army against the monkey. The army arrived at the mountain. Sun Wukong, who had been napping, took up the iron staff and grew it to the size of a mountain himself, and the heavenly army was scattered in an afternoon.",
        "The Jade Emperor, in despair, sent for the Buddha.",
        "The Buddha came down. He was not in armor. He stood in a quiet robe at the foot of the mountain. He looked at Sun Wukong with mild interest.",
        "\"You are very strong, monkey,\" he said.",
        "\"I am the strongest,\" said Sun Wukong, who liked to be acknowledged.",
        "\"Are you?\" said the Buddha. \"Show me. Jump. If you can jump out of the palm of my hand, I will recommend the Jade Emperor abdicate the throne to you.\"",
        "Sun Wukong laughed. He could leap eighteen thousand miles in one somersault. The Buddha's hand was perhaps a foot across. He coiled. He launched. He flew across the sky for what felt like hours. He came at last to the edge of the world — five great pillars rose in front of him at the rim — and he landed on the central pillar and, in the manner of monkeys, urinated on it to mark his triumph. He carved his name into the base of the pillar with the iron staff. He somersaulted back.",
        "He landed in the Buddha's palm. \"Done,\" he said. \"I have been to the edge of the world.\"",
        "The Buddha lifted his hand and showed Sun Wukong the base of his middle finger. There — small, slightly smudged — was the carving of Sun Wukong's name. There was also a small wet patch.",
        "Sun Wukong understood, for the first time in his life, that he had not been jumping at all. He had been crawling around on a hand he could not see the size of.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The Buddha closed his hand and pressed it down. The mountain that came down on Sun Wukong was Five-Elements Mountain. It pinned him underneath. The Buddha sealed it with a paper sutra. Sun Wukong was held there, head and arms only sticking out, for five hundred years.",
        "After five hundred years a Buddhist monk named Tang Sanzang came past the mountain on a long pilgrimage west — to fetch the true scriptures from India and bring them back to China. He needed a bodyguard. He had been told to look for a monkey under a mountain.",
        "He climbed the mountain. He peeled the paper sutra off. The mountain crumbled. Sun Wukong stepped out, somewhat thinner. He bowed his head, more or less. He agreed, on terms negotiated by the Buddha himself, to escort the monk west.",
        "He kept his iron staff. He kept his seventy-two transformations. But the monk had been given a small gold band that could be tightened on the monkey's head with a chant whenever the monkey misbehaved, and the band could not be removed except by the monk's own permission, and the long pilgrimage they walked together — fourteen years, eighty-one perils, demons and false monks and rivers full of grasping hands — was conducted under the steady mild restraint of that band.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The strongest creature ever born of a stone was bound at last not by an army or a chain but by a small gold ring tied to the small steady purpose of a monk who had a long way to walk. The strongest are bound by the steadiest, in any age." },
        "When the monk reached India and returned with the scriptures, Sun Wukong was made a Buddha himself in honor of his service. The gold band fell from his head of its own accord. He did not need it any longer. He had become, by walking with the steady monk, a creature who would have, of his own will, gone on the long pilgrimage even without it."
    ]
},

{
    id: "change",
    title: "Chang'e and the Moon",
    subtitle: "Of the elixir she drank, and the rabbit who keeps her company",
    civilization: "chinese",
    themes: ["Sacrifice", "Moon", "Husband & wife", "Loneliness"],
    content: [
        "Long ago there were ten suns in the sky. They were the children of the Eastern Emperor Di Jun and his wife Xihe, and their custom was to take turns in the sky — one rising each morning and the others remaining at home in the kingdom of the east, drinking tea, waiting their turn — so that each day the world received a single gentle warming.",
        "One morning the ten of them, who were brothers and who had been bored for centuries, decided to come up all at the same time as a prank. The earth caught fire. The rivers boiled. The forests burned. The cattle died in the fields. The people, in their burning houses, cried out to heaven for relief.",
        "Heaven heard them. The emperor sent down his finest archer, a hero named Hou Yi, with a great red bow and ten arrows. \"Frighten my sons home,\" he said. \"Just frighten them.\"",
        "Hou Yi came down with his wife Chang'e and they walked the burning country and they saw what the ten suns had done. Hou Yi was not a man given to mild measures. He raised the red bow. He shot down the first sun. It fell to earth as a three-legged crow. He shot the second. The third. The fourth. The fifth, the sixth, the seventh, the eighth, the ninth — nine suns came down out of the sky as nine three-legged crows, and the air cooled, and the people in their burning houses fell on their knees with relief.",
        "Hou Yi raised the bow at the tenth sun. Chang'e — who had been watching from a hilltop — ran down to him and put her hand on his arm. \"Husband,\" she said, \"leave one. We need one. Don't punish all of them for the prank of all.\"",
        "He lowered the bow. The tenth sun fled into the high country and stayed alone after that, rising every morning by itself, never tempted to invite siblings.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The Eastern Emperor was relieved that the world had been saved but extremely unhappy that nine of his sons had been killed. He stripped Hou Yi and Chang'e of their immortality and exiled them to live as mortals on the burned earth, and there they made a life — for a hero and his wife make a life wherever they are dropped — but it was a smaller life than they had been used to, and they began to age.",
        "Hou Yi loved Chang'e. He could not bear the thought of her growing old and dying. He went west — across deserts, across rivers — to the palace of the Queen Mother of the West, who lives on the high mountain Kunlun and who keeps in her storehouse the elixirs of immortality. He begged her for one. She gave him one. \"Enough for two,\" she said. \"Drink half each. You will not become gods again, but you will not die.\"",
        "He brought it home in a small jade flask. He showed Chang'e. They agreed to drink it together at the next full moon — for there were ceremonies that should accompany such a thing.",
        "He hid the flask on a high shelf in their bedroom. He went away for two days to a hunting party.",
        "While he was gone, his apprentice Pengmeng — a man Hou Yi had taken in years before, a man Hou Yi trusted — came to the house with a sword. He had heard about the elixir. He had decided to take it for himself. He pushed Chang'e against the wall. He told her to give him the flask.",
        "Chang'e, alone in the house, did not have time to think. She climbed the bedroom shelf, took down the flask, uncorked it — and rather than let the apprentice have it, she drank it. All of it. Both halves.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "She did not become merely immortal. She had taken twice the dose. She began at once to rise. Her feet left the floor. She rose through the rafters. She rose through the roof. She rose into the night sky.",
        "She kept rising. She rose past the tall pines. She rose past the high clouds. She rose toward the sun and felt the heat of it, and turned, and rose toward the moon instead, because the moon was cool, and the moon was the place she had wanted to go for one half-second to escape the apprentice and now could not stop going to.",
        "She arrived at the moon. She landed in a great cool palace that had been there always but had been empty. She looked back. From the moon she could see her husband's house, very small, very far below.",
        "Hou Yi came home that night. He found the flask empty and Pengmeng wounded on the floor. He understood at once. He ran out into the garden. He looked up. There, on the moon — a small figure he could just barely see, a dark silhouette with the long sleeves of a woman's robe — was Chang'e. She was looking down at him.",
        "He set out a small altar in the garden. He laid out her favorite cakes — the small round ones, with the lotus paste, and a single yolk in the center for the moon — and he sat under the moon all night and watched her watching him, and they could not reach each other.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "She has lived on the moon ever since. The Queen Mother of the West, who pitied her, sent up to her a small white rabbit for company, and the rabbit grinds the herbs of the moon in a stone mortar, and the rabbit's pestle is the small dark mark on the face of the moon you can still see at full. There is also, on the moon, a man named Wu Gang who was sentenced to chop down a self-healing tree forever, and you can sometimes see his shadow at the eastern edge of the disk; but Chang'e does not visit him much, because his story is sad in a different way.",
        "Hou Yi did not become immortal. He grew old. He died, eventually. But every year on the night of the harvest moon — the brightest moon of the year — the people of China set out small round cakes in their courtyards and look up, and they say her name, and the woman on the moon, looking down, is comforted by the small remembering, and so are they.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Whoever has had to drink the whole flask in a single emergency will rise so far they cannot come back. The cake on the windowsill on the bright night of the year is the only message that still arrives." },
        "There is also a Chinese space probe called Chang'e. There is a moon-rover named Yutu, which is the rabbit. The astronomers who named these things did not consider themselves religious. They named them anyway. Some stories are folded into the long history of a country in such a way that even the engineers, when they reach for a name to put on the side of a metal craft sailing toward the moon, reach by instinct for the older woman who got there first."
    ]
},

{
    id: "cowherd-weaver",
    title: "The Cowherd and the Weaver Girl",
    subtitle: "How a river of stars was set between two lovers, and the magpies who bridge it once a year",
    civilization: "chinese",
    themes: ["Lovers", "Stars", "Separation", "Bridge"],
    content: [
        "There was a young man on earth who had nothing. His name was Niu Lang. His parents were dead. His older brother had inherited the small family farm, and his older brother's wife, who did not like him, had insisted on his removal. They had given him a single old ox and turned him out.",
        "He took the ox into the hills and set up a small camp by a stream and made a life of sorts. He was poor and lonely but the work suited him. He talked to the ox. The ox, after a year, began to talk back — for the ox was no ordinary ox; it had once been a star spirit who had been demoted to earth for a small infraction at a banquet and was now waiting out his sentence in the body of a draft animal.",
        "One summer afternoon the ox said to Niu Lang: \"Tomorrow at this hour the seven daughters of the Queen Mother of the West will come down to bathe in the lake at the foot of this hill. They are weaver-women. They weave the clouds in the loom of heaven. They will leave their robes on the bank. The seventh sister — Zhinü, the youngest — will weave the most beautiful clouds in heaven if she lives. Take her robe. Hide it. She cannot return without it. She will agree to marry you.\"",
        "Niu Lang was startled. He felt this was not, perhaps, the most courteous form of courtship. The ox, sensing his hesitation, added: \"She will not be unhappy. She has been bored in heaven for a long time. The work is hard and her mother is strict. She will agree gladly. Only — take the robe.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He went down to the lake the next afternoon and hid in the reeds. He saw the seven sisters descend on a long ribbon of cloud. They removed their robes and bathed in the cool water, talking and laughing among themselves. He took the smallest robe — the seventh one, the one folded with most care, the one of pale silk — and he tucked it into the front of his shirt.",
        "When the bathing was over the six elder sisters dressed and rose into the air. The seventh, Zhinü, could not find her robe. She searched the bank. She looked behind the reeds. She found, instead, the young man. He was not handsome but he was earnest. He explained to her, somewhat awkwardly, that he had taken her robe at the suggestion of his ox; that he was lonely; that he had no family; that he would treat her well.",
        "Zhinü, who had been bored in heaven for a long time, thought about it. She accepted. She came up the hill with him. She returned the robe to him for his keeping, since it was now in her interest also that no one in heaven should know where she had gone.",
        "They lived happily for years. They had two children — a boy and a girl. He continued to work with the ox; she wove cloth at a small loom. The cloth she wove was so beautiful that buyers came from three provinces. They were no longer poor.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "But the Queen Mother of the West, in heaven, missed her seventh daughter. She had been searching, in her slow way, for some years. She found her at last. She came down to earth in a fury. She took Zhinü by the wrist and pulled her up into the sky in a single moment.",
        "Niu Lang, in the field, saw his wife pulled up. He ran to the house. The two children were standing in the doorway, crying. The ox was there too. The ox said quickly, \"Take the children. Each in a basket. Carry them on a shoulder pole. I am dying — I have served my time — but my hide will let you fly. Wear it. Run.\"",
        "The ox died on the spot. Niu Lang, weeping, skinned his old companion. He pulled the hide on. He took the two children, one in each basket on a long bamboo pole across his shoulders, and he ran up into the sky after his wife.",
        "He gained on her. He could see her ahead. The Queen Mother of the West, looking back, saw him gaining. She drew a great hairpin from her hair and slashed it across the sky between them.",
        "Where she slashed, a river opened — a river of stars, broad, swift, impassable, the river you can still see arching across the sky on a clear summer night, the long band of light that the West calls the Milky Way and the Chinese call the Heavenly River.",
        "Niu Lang, on his side of the river, fell to his knees. He could not cross. He held out his arms toward his wife on the far bank. The two children, in their baskets, cried. Zhinü, on the other side, wept also. They stood there in the night sky and could not reach each other.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The Queen Mother of the West, watching the four of them — a husband, a wife, two small crying children, a long impassable river — was, at last, moved. She was a strict goddess but she was a goddess who had had her own losses. She made one concession.",
        "Once a year — on the seventh day of the seventh lunar month, the date of her daughter's running away — every magpie in the world, called by an old bird-instinct nobody can quite explain, flies up to the Heavenly River and joins wing to wing to wing across it. They form a bridge — a long fluttering black-and-white living bridge across the river of stars. The bridge holds for one night.",
        "On that night Niu Lang, with his two children in their baskets, walks across the bridge to his wife. They have one night together. The four of them embrace. The children fall asleep on the laps of their mother. The bridge holds until dawn. At dawn the magpies fly back to earth, the bridge is gone, and Niu Lang and the children walk back to their side, and the long year of waiting begins again.",
        "On every clear summer night you can see the two of them — Niu Lang as the bright star Altair on one side of the river, with the two children as the two small stars beside him; and Zhinü as the bright star Vega on the other side. They look at each other across the long luminous water. They wait.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Whoever has been separated from their love by the stroke of a queen's hairpin can still meet, once a year, on a bridge made of every magpie in the world. The world has more solidarity than its rulers always allow for." },
        "The festival of Qixi — the Seventh Night — is still kept in China and in Japan and in Korea. Lovers go out to look at the stars. They tie wishes to bamboo branches. They eat small dumplings. They do not always know whose long story they are commemorating. They feel only that on a particular summer night a particular kind of attention is owed to a particular kind of patience, and they pay it, by long inheritance, without entirely needing to be told why."
    ]
},

{
    id: "jade-emperor",
    title: "The Jade Emperor and the Twelve Animals",
    subtitle: "How the calendar was made by a footrace, and why the cat does not speak to the rat",
    civilization: "chinese",
    themes: ["Order", "Race", "Trickery", "Calendar"],
    content: [
        "When the Jade Emperor — the ruler of heaven, the lord of all gods, the father of every dynasty — first looked down on the early earth and saw that the people there had no way to keep track of years, he decided that he ought to provide them with one. He summoned all the animals of the world to his palace. He told them: there will be a race. The first twelve to cross the river at the bottom of my mountain will each have a year of the calendar named after them. The order of the twelve years will be the order in which you arrive. Begin at dawn.",
        "The animals went home and trained. The race was the talk of every burrow and every hollow tree.",
        "Among the animals were the cat and the rat. They were, at the time, friends. They lived together in a small house at the edge of a marsh. They were both small. They were both worried about the river — the river was wide, the current was strong, and neither of them could swim well.",
        "The night before the race the cat said to the rat: \"Friend. I sleep heavily. I am afraid I will not wake in time. Wake me at dawn. Promise.\"",
        "The rat said: \"I promise.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The rat woke before dawn. The rat looked at the sleeping cat and considered the matter for a long quiet minute. The rat decided not to wake him.",
        "He left. He ran to the river. The race had not yet started. The other animals were assembling at the bank.",
        "The rat saw at once that he could not swim across. The current was too strong. But he saw the ox — large, slow, calm — already wading into the shallows. The rat ran up the ox's tail. The ox, who was a kindly animal, did not protest. The rat climbed up to a comfortable seat on the ox's broad forehead.",
        "The Jade Emperor's signal sounded. The ox began to swim. The rat clung to the ox's horn. They crossed steadily. The other animals — the rabbit, the dog, the snake, the dragon, the rooster, the boar, the horse, the sheep, the monkey, the tiger — were all also struggling across, in various ways, behind them.",
        "The ox approached the far bank. He was clearly going to be first. The Jade Emperor stood at the finish line, waiting. The ox lowered his head to step out onto the sand.",
        "The rat — at this moment — leaped from the ox's forehead onto the sand and scampered across the finish line.",
        "The ox lifted his head, blinked, stepped out, and was second.",
        "The Jade Emperor, who appreciated cunning, laughed. He named the first year of the calendar after the rat. He named the second year after the ox. The ox did not complain. The ox had been raised to be a cooperative animal; he simply lay down on the bank and watched the others arrive.",
        "Third came the tiger, who had had a hard swim. Fourth came the rabbit, who had hopped across on a series of floating logs. Fifth came the dragon — who could have flown across in a blink, but had stopped to make rain over a village in a drought, and so was late. Sixth came the snake, who had hidden in the shoe of the horse and slipped off to come in just before him. Seventh came the horse, startled. Eighth came the sheep, ninth the monkey, tenth the rooster — these three having banded together on a small raft they had made of branches, and they took the order of stepping off — eleventh came the dog, who was a strong swimmer but had been having too much fun in the water to hurry. Twelfth, last by a whisker, came the boar, who had stopped halfway across to take a nap and a snack.",
        "Twelve. The Jade Emperor counted. He named them: Rat, Ox, Tiger, Rabbit, Dragon, Snake, Horse, Sheep, Monkey, Rooster, Dog, Boar. He set them in this order in the calendar of the world. He thanked them and dismissed them.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Sometime later in the morning the cat arrived. He had woken up — alone — to a quiet house, and he had run as fast as he could, but he had reached the river only after the race was over and the bank was empty.",
        "He found the rat, who had lingered to receive his honors. The cat looked at the rat. The rat, who had been preparing his speech, said only: \"Friend. I am sorry. I forgot.\"",
        "The cat understood at once that the rat had not forgotten.",
        "From that day, the cat is not in the calendar. From that day, the cat hunts the rat wherever the cat finds the rat. The friendship that ended on a marsh-edge morning has not been repaired in any of the centuries since.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The friend who would not wake you for the race is the friend you should not turn your back on for the rest of your life. The calendar of the world is full of small remembered betrayals, and the cat does not let go of his." },
        "The twelve years of the Chinese calendar still rotate in the order the animals took at the river. People born in each year are said to share something of the temperament of their year-animal. The cat — though absent from the official record — is honored quietly in some Vietnamese versions of the calendar, where he replaces the rabbit; the Vietnamese have not forgiven the rat either, and have used their own zodiac to issue a small standing rebuke to him across the centuries."
    ]
}
);

