window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "sun-moon-siblings",
    title: "The Sun and Moon Siblings",
    subtitle: "How a brother and sister climbed a rope into the sky to escape a tiger",
    civilization: "korean",
    themes: ["Siblings", "Trickster tiger", "Sky", "Escape"],
    content: [
        "There was once a poor woman who lived alone with her two small children — a boy and a girl — in a small house at the edge of a wood. Her husband had died young. Every day she walked many hours over a hill to the next village to work, and every evening she walked back, and she always brought home a small basket of buckwheat cakes for her children.",
        "One evening she was crossing the hill at dusk when a tiger stepped onto the path in front of her.",
        "The tiger was very large. The tiger was very hungry. The tiger said: \"Old woman. Give me a buckwheat cake or I will eat you.\"",
        "She gave him a cake. He ate it. He let her walk on. She crested the next ridge. The tiger appeared again.",
        "\"Old woman. Give me a buckwheat cake or I will eat you.\"",
        "She gave him another. She crested the next ridge. The tiger appeared again. By the fifth ridge she had no cakes left in her basket. The tiger appeared a sixth time. He was still hungry. He ate her.",
        "He kept her clothes. He put on her dress. He put on her headcloth. He had been planning ahead.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He came down the path to the small house at the edge of the wood. He knocked. The boy and the girl were inside, waiting for their mother.",
        "The tiger called through the door, in the woman's voice — for tigers in such stories can do this — \"Children. Open the door. I have brought your supper.\"",
        "The girl, who was older, did not open the door at once. She listened. The voice was almost right, but not quite. \"Mother,\" she said, \"your voice is rough today.\"",
        "\"I have a cold from the hill wind,\" said the tiger. \"Open the door.\"",
        "\"Show me your hand through the gap,\" said the girl.",
        "The tiger pushed his paw under the door. The paw was furred. \"Mother,\" said the girl, \"your hand is hairy today.\"",
        "\"I have been carrying brushwood,\" said the tiger. \"Open the door.\"",
        "The girl looked at her brother. Her brother looked at her. They did not open the door. They went out the back window and ran into the yard.",
        "There was a tall pine tree in the yard. They climbed it.",
        "The tiger heard them go. He came around the house. He saw them in the tree. He could not climb pines. He looked at them. He said, in the woman's voice that was now half a tiger's voice, \"Children. How did you get up there?\"",
        "The boy, who was small and frightened and did not yet understand that he should not answer, said: \"We rubbed sesame oil on our hands and feet and we climbed.\"",
        "The girl bit her brother's arm. \"Stupid,\" she whispered.",
        "The tiger ran into the house. He came back with the small jar of sesame oil. He rubbed it on his paws. He tried to climb. He slid down. He tried again. He slid down. He looked up at them with his large yellow eye.",
        "The boy, distressed at his own slipperiness, called out: \"No, no — sesame oil is for the climbing kitchen. We used the axe! We notched footholds with the axe!\"",
        "The girl pulled her brother's hair. The tiger ran into the house and came back with the axe. He began to chop notches into the trunk. He climbed up after them.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The two children sat at the very top of the pine tree. The tiger was halfway up. They had nowhere to go. The girl looked up at the sky.",
        "She said, in a voice as steady as she could make it: \"Lord of the sky. Heavenly One. If you have ever loved any small thing on the earth — send down a rope. Send down a rope to save us. Otherwise we are done.\"",
        "From the sky a rope unrolled. It came down through the air. It was a strong new rope, of the kind a god would weave. The girl took her brother's hand. They climbed.",
        "The tiger, halfway up the pine, watched them rising into the sky on the rope. He was not, as a rule, a religious tiger, but he understood the principle. He looked up.",
        "\"Lord of the sky,\" he called, in his roughest voice, \"send me down a rope also. Otherwise the children get away. Send me a rope.\"",
        "From the sky a second rope unrolled. It looked just like the first. It was not. It was an old rope, half-rotten, the fibers giving way at every twist.",
        "The tiger, who could not see the difference from below, grasped it. He climbed. The two children, far above him, were already nearly at the cloud layer. He climbed faster. The rotten rope, halfway up, snapped.",
        "He fell. He fell into a field of sorghum at the foot of the hill. The sorghum stalks pierced him as he landed. He died with his red blood spreading over the broken stalks. The Koreans say this is why sorghum stalks have red roots to this day.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The two children were lifted up into the sky. The Lord of the Sky welcomed them. He did not have the heart to send them back down — for there was no longer any home to go to.",
        "He gave each of them an office. He made the boy the moon. He made the girl the sun.",
        "The girl protested. \"I do not want to be the sun. The sun must walk all day. People will look up at me. I am too shy.\"",
        "\"Then I will give you a small power,\" said the Lord of the Sky. \"When anyone tries to look at you directly, your light will be too bright for their eyes. They will have to look away. You will not have to be looked at.\"",
        "She agreed. She is the sun. Her brother, smaller, gentler, walks at night. They have not seen each other except in passing for many centuries, but they keep each other in mind, and the long sweep of day and night across the world is the long pattern of two siblings who once climbed a rope to get away from something terrible and were given the sky as a kind of permanent shelter.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The rope a god lets down for the small ones who pray well is a strong rope. The rope a god lets down for the creature who has eaten the mother is the rope that breaks. The selection is not arbitrary." },
        "Korean children are told this story before bed. The lesson, if there is a lesson, is partly about not opening the door to anything that is calling itself your mother in a voice you do not quite recognize. But the larger lesson is about what to do when you are at the top of a pine and the tiger is climbing — which is to ask, in a steady voice, for a rope. The rope, the storytellers say, comes more often than the cynics expect."
    ]
},

{
    id: "princess-bari",
    title: "Princess Bari",
    subtitle: "The seventh daughter who walked into the underworld for the medicine to save her parents",
    civilization: "korean",
    themes: ["Daughter", "Underworld", "Medicine", "Shaman"],
    content: [
        "There was a king and queen who wanted a son. Each year the queen bore a daughter. The first six daughters were kept in the palace and raised as princesses. The seventh daughter, when she came, was the breaking point. The king had been told by an oracle that no son would be born after a seventh daughter, and the king could not bear to look at her. He ordered her to be put into a small jade box and thrown into the river.",
        "The queen, weeping, did as the king ordered. The box was set on the water at midnight. The water carried it. The water carried it past the city walls and past the rice paddies and past the small fishing villages and out into the wide country, and at last the box came to rest in the reeds at the edge of a pond near the hut of an old childless couple. The old couple, hearing the small cry, opened the box. They lifted the baby out. They named her Bari, which means abandoned. They raised her as their own.",
        "Bari grew up. She was kind. She was strong. She knew nothing of her birth.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Years later — fifteen years later — the king and queen of the country fell ill. They did not get better. The court physicians applied every art they knew. They were dying.",
        "The court diviner was consulted. He cast the bones. He said: \"This illness has only one cure. There is a medicine, called the Water of Life, that flows in a single spring at the western edge of the underworld. Whoever fetches it will heal them. Whoever does not, no one survives.\"",
        "The king sent for his six daughters. He asked, one by one, which would go. Each one bowed and said, in tones of careful daughterly regret, that she could not — she had a husband, she had children, she had a household. Six refusals.",
        "The diviner, gently, said: \"There is a seventh daughter. Find her.\"",
        "The king and queen wept. They had not known that the seventh daughter had survived. They sent men out to look. The men found her — by signs the diviner had given — at the small hut by the pond. She was now fifteen.",
        "She was brought to the palace. She was told everything: who her parents were, what they had done to her, why they were now asking. She did not weep. She had been told the story by her foster-mother years before; she had had time to grow into it.",
        "She agreed to go. She did not negotiate. She asked only for one set of plain travel clothes and a staff.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "She walked west.",
        "She walked through the country until the country ended. She walked into a long grey land that was not quite the upper world and not quite the lower. She crossed seven mountains. She crossed seven rivers. At each mountain there was a fierce guardian who tried to turn her back; at each river there was a ferryman who demanded payment; at each crossing she gave what was asked, and she went on.",
        "She came at last to the western edge of the underworld. She came to the gate. The gate was guarded by an enormous man whose face she could not properly see. He was — the books say — the lord of the western reach himself, in some accounts a god, in some accounts simply a very tall keeper.",
        "He looked at her. He said: \"You may not have the Water unless you serve me. Three years carrying water. Three years cutting wood. Three years tending fire. Then nine years as my wife. Then I will give you the medicine.\"",
        "She bowed her head. She said: \"Yes.\"",
        "She served three years carrying water. She served three years cutting wood. She served three years tending fire. She married him. She bore him seven sons over the nine years that followed.",
        "At the end of the nine years she did not need to ask. He gave her the Water of Life — three small jade bottles of it, all he had — and he gave her three living flowers from the garden of resurrection that grew only by the spring of that water. He let her go.",
        "She had been gone twenty-one years. She came up out of the underworld carrying her seven sons in a basket on her back and the three small bottles in her sleeves and the three flowers in her hair.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "She came home. She came to the palace. The king and queen were already dead. They had been dead, in fact, for some weeks. Their bodies were laid out in the great hall, awaiting the elaborate funeral rites that were being arranged.",
        "She walked into the hall. She set the seven sons down. She uncorked one of the jade bottles. She poured a single drop on the lips of the king. She poured a single drop on the lips of the queen. She put one of the flowers on each of their chests.",
        "They breathed. They opened their eyes. They sat up. The king saw the woman who had healed him. He understood, after a moment, who she was. He fell on his knees in front of her. He could not look at her.",
        "She lifted him gently. She did not gloat. She did not reproach. She had had twenty-one years in a foreign country to think about what she would say in this moment, and what she had decided to say, in the end, was: \"I am glad you are alive.\" She said only that.",
        "The king and queen recovered. The king offered her, in restitution, anything she wanted — half the kingdom, the throne itself, a temple in her name. She refused all of it. She said she did not want a throne. She did not want a temple. She wanted only one office.",
        "\"Make me,\" she said, \"the guide of the dead. Make me the one who escorts every soul, in this country, from the upper world to the lower. I have walked the road. I know the way. I will bring no one through that road who is not ready, and I will leave no one on the road who is.\"",
        "The king, weeping, granted it.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The seventh daughter who was thrown away on the morning of her birth became, in time, the only one who knew the road down to the western land. The kingdom that did not want her became the kingdom that needed her, and she did not turn her face away from it." },
        "She is, to this day, the patron goddess of Korean shamans — the muga, the women who sing the dead into their next lives. They invoke her at every funeral. They sing the long song of her abandonment, and her walking west, and her years of service, and her return with the bottles and the flowers, and they sing it as a kind of professional inheritance: she is the one who first walked the road we walk on every funeral day, and we walk it because she walked it first, and she walked it because no one else would."
    ]
}
);

