window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "hero-twins",
    title: "The Hero Twins of Xibalba",
    subtitle: "How two brothers played ball with the lords of death and won",
    civilization: "mayan",
    themes: ["Twins", "Underworld", "Trial", "Ball game"],
    content: [
        "Hunahpu and Xbalanque were twin boys. Their father, Hun Hunahpu, had been a great ball-player who had once made the mistake of playing too loudly above the city of Xibalba — the lords of the dead lived in Xibalba, beneath the world, and they did not like noise overhead — and the lords had called him down on the pretext of a friendly game and had killed him there. They had hung his head in a calabash tree at the edge of the underworld court as a trophy.",
        "A young woman of Xibalba named Xquic, daughter of one of the lords, had passed beneath that tree one afternoon and the head — for the head, even severed, kept some of the magic of the man — had spoken to her. It had spit a small drop of saliva into her open palm. She had become pregnant from the saliva. Her father, when he discovered her condition, had ordered her killed; she had escaped, walked up out of the underworld, and given birth in the upper country to twin boys.",
        "The twins grew up in their grandmother's house. They grew up to be ball-players too. They had inherited their father's gear — the gear had been hidden in the rafters of the grandmother's hut — and they began to play in the same court above the city of Xibalba.",
        "The lords of Xibalba, beneath, heard the bouncing of the ball and the running of the feet. They sent up a messenger. The messenger said: \"The lords below request your presence for a game. Come down at once.\" The boys understood at once that this was the same summons their father had received. They went down anyway. Their grandmother wept. The boys had decided. They would not be eaten by the same trick twice.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The lords of Xibalba had prepared a series of trials. They had prepared them for the father; they had refined them since.",
        "First was the welcome. The lords sat on a long stone bench. They had set up two wooden carved figures at the end of the bench, dressed in the same robes as the lords, painted with the lords' faces. The polite traveler would bow to those first and address them as \"My lord\" and earn the laughter of the actual lords. The boys, walking in, did not bow to the wooden figures. They walked past them. They went directly to the actual lords. \"Lord One Death,\" they said. \"Lord Seven Death. We are here.\"",
        "The lords were displeased.",
        "Second was the seat. The lords offered the boys a long stone bench to sit on. The bench was secretly a hot griddle, glowing red beneath the surface. The polite traveler would sit and would burn his thighs and would stand up screaming. The boys looked at the bench. They sat on the floor. \"We prefer the floor,\" they said politely.",
        "The lords were more displeased.",
        "Third came a series of houses. Each night the boys had to spend in a different house. Each house was its own trial. The House of Cold — full of hail and freezing wind. They built a small careful fire and survived. The House of Jaguars — full of pacing pacing jaguars. They threw the jaguars some bones from the kitchen and the jaguars settled to gnawing and ignored the boys. The House of Bats — full of large stone-knife-billed bats. They hid inside their own blowguns. (Hunahpu, peering out of the end of his blowgun, had his head bitten off by a passing bat — an inconvenience the boys would have to repair the next morning, but they were resourceful boys, and they did, with a substituted gourd-head, until the real one could be reattached.) The House of Razors — the razors were instructed to behave themselves and lay down still. The boys had a quiet word with them.",
        "By the end of the houses the lords were considering whether to simply admit defeat.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Then came the ball game.",
        "The lords had cheated at the game with the father. They cheated again. The ball they brought out was a sharpened ball of obsidian, designed to cut the boys' shins. The boys laughed. \"Use a real ball,\" they said. \"This is not a game, this is an assassination. Use a real ball or there is no game.\"",
        "The lords, embarrassed, brought out a real ball. The game began. The boys were good. They were very good. They were better than the lords. The lords had not played in a long time. By the end of the first quarter the score was clearly going to be on the boys' side.",
        "But the boys understood — without having to be told — that to win the game outright would mean instant death. The lords would not tolerate being beaten in their own court. So the boys played a long careful game in which they kept the score close, kept it teasing, let the lords think they were winning, then evened it again.",
        "At nightfall they called it a draw. The lords, growing more suspicious, sent them back to a different house. The trials of the houses continued. The game resumed each morning. This went on for some days.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "At last the boys understood that nothing was going to be enough. The lords had decided to kill them no matter what. The boys decided to control the manner.",
        "They volunteered. They walked, hand in hand, to the great oven at the center of Xibalba. They climbed in. They burned to ash.",
        "The lords celebrated. They ground the ash. They threw the ash into the river that ran through the underworld.",
        "But the boys had spoken to the river beforehand. The ash, in the water, swirled, gathered, recomposed. Within five days the two boys had reformed in the river — not as twin boys exactly, but as twin fish-men, the same souls in slightly different bodies — and they walked up out of the river and into the city of the dead in the disguise of two traveling magicians.",
        "They went around the city performing tricks. They could set fire to a house and put it back together. They could kill a dog and bring it back to life. They could even kill a man and bring him back. The lords of Xibalba, hearing about these wandering magicians, sent for them.",
        "\"Show us,\" said Lord One Death. \"Kill one of us and bring him back.\"",
        "The boys bowed. They asked which lord. Lord One Death indicated himself, half in jest, perhaps thinking it would be one of the smaller lords. The boys cut his throat. The boys did not bring him back.",
        "\"Now me,\" said Lord Seven Death, before he had quite finished thinking about what he was asking. The boys cut his throat too. They did not bring him back.",
        "The remaining lords of Xibalba, looking at the two open-throated bodies of their two greatest, finally understood who the magicians were. They knelt. They begged.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The boys did not kill the rest. They were not interested in killing them. They had killed the two heads of the council that had killed their father, and that was enough. But they imposed terms.",
        "\"You,\" said Hunahpu, \"will no longer be the great lords of the dead. You will be reduced. You will receive only the lowest sacrifices — the small offerings of the poor and the broken. You will not eat the flesh of warriors. You will not eat the flesh of the well-spoken. You will eat the small offerings, and you will be content with them, and you will not call any noisy ball-player down to your court ever again.\"",
        "The remaining lords agreed. They have kept the agreement, more or less, for a long time.",
        "Hunahpu and Xbalanque climbed up out of Xibalba. They climbed all the way up — not just to the upper world, but past it, into the sky. Hunahpu became the sun. Xbalanque became the moon. Their father's head, in the calabash tree, fell from its branch and rolled away and was buried by the gods, and where it was buried became a quiet mound that the maize first sprang from.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Whoever has been called down to a hostile court for a friendly game should consider that the game is not the game. The hosts are the game. Refuse the bench they offer you. Sit on the floor. Refuse the cut ball. Demand a real one. Win, but do not let them know you have won, until the moment you have already won." },
        "The Mayan ball court is still standing in many places — at Chichen Itza and at Copan and at Yaxchilan — and the long stone walls and the great stone hoops and the rough stone floor where the heroes played are still there. The story of the twins is the founding story of every match that was ever played on those courts, and the seriousness with which the players took the game — for the losers in some courts were sacrificed at the end of it — was inherited from the seriousness of the original game between the boys and the lords."
    ]
},

{
    id: "maize-people",
    title: "The Creation of the Maize People",
    subtitle: "The four false makings of human beings, and the dough at last that worked",
    civilization: "mayan",
    themes: ["Creation", "Failure", "Maize", "Patience"],
    content: [
        "Before there were any human beings the gods of the Maya had made several attempts. They had wanted creatures who would speak their names, who would offer sacrifices on their behalf, who would keep the calendars and watch the stars and remember which gods deserved which festival. The first three attempts were unsuccessful.",
        "The first attempt was made out of mud. The gods sat by a riverbank and shaped a mud man. He was lumpy. He could not stand without sagging. When the gods tried to speak with him his mouth filled with water from his own crumbling face. He could not speak. He fell apart in the first rain. The gods scraped him back into the river and started over.",
        "The second attempt was made out of wood. The gods carved a wooden man — and a wooden woman — and set them up in the world. They could stand. They could walk. They could speak — somewhat — in stiff jerky sentences. They had children, also of wood. They built houses. They cooked their food. They forgot, however, to thank the gods. They never lit a candle for the gods. They never held a festival. They never spoke a divine name. They forgot, in fact, that there were gods at all.",
        "The gods watched this with growing irritation. After a while they decided to undo the wooden people. They sent down a great rain. They sent down the household objects of the wooden people in animate vengeance — the cooking pots, the grinding stones, the corn-sheller — all of them rose up and beat their owners. The dogs of the wooden people, who had been kicked too often, also rose up. The wooden people fled in terror, climbed onto roofs, climbed into trees. Most of them drowned. Those that survived hung in the trees and grew long tails and shrunk, and they became, the priests said, the monkeys you can still see in the high jungle, who remember dimly what it was to be people but cannot quite recover the language.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The third attempt was not really an attempt. It was a brief experiment with making people out of reeds. The reeds proved insufficiently sturdy. They blew apart in the first wind. The gods did not even bother to gather the pieces.",
        "After the third failure the gods sat in a long quiet council. They were embarrassed. They had set out to make creatures who would speak their names and remember them, and they had succeeded only in making mud and wood and reeds. They were, frankly, beginning to wonder whether the project was even possible.",
        "Then a small grey fox came running up the path from the south. The fox had a story. The fox had been wandering in a far country and had seen, in a hidden valley, a strange new plant — tall, green, with long flat leaves and a thick golden ear at the top. The plant was called maize. The animals of that valley had been quietly eating it for some time and growing strong on it.",
        "The gods sent four animals south to fetch maize. The fox went. The coyote went. The parrot went. The crow went. They came back with armloads of yellow corn and white corn, which they laid at the gods' feet.",
        "The grandmother goddess Xmucane took the maize. She ground it on a stone — for hours, for the slow and patient hours of a woman grinding for her family — until the dry kernels were a fine yellow flour. She mixed the flour with water. She made a soft dough.",
        "She shaped the dough into figures. She shaped a man. She shaped a woman. She shaped four men and four women. Then she sat back.",
        "She held a small candle to the figures. They opened their eyes.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "These were the first people who worked.",
        "They could speak. They could speak well. They named the gods. They sang the gods' praises. They lit the candles. They built the temples. They learned the calendars. They watched the stars. They wrote.",
        "But there was an unintended consequence. The first four maize men could see too well. They could see — when they tried — to the very edge of the world. They could see through mountains. They could see through the walls of houses. They could read the thoughts of other beings. They were, in effect, almost as wise as the gods who had made them.",
        "The gods looked at this and saw at once a problem they had not anticipated. If the people they had made were nearly as wise as the gods themselves, the people would not need the gods. They would speak the gods' names out of courtesy only, not out of need. The whole project — to have someone to keep the festivals, to make the offerings, to need the gods — would be undermined.",
        "The gods, in council, decided on a small adjustment. They blew a soft mist across the eyes of the four maize men. From that morning the people could no longer see to the edge of the world. They could see only as far as the next ridge, and not past. They could no longer see through mountains, or through walls, or through skin. They had ordinary human sight. They were still wise — they were still the speaking, candle-lighting, calendar-keeping people the gods had hoped for — but they were now also, for the rest of their lives and the lives of all their children, slightly limited. They had to ask the gods for the rest.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "From the four men and four women came the people of every nation of the Maya. They were the maize people. Their bones, the priests said, were corn cobs. Their flesh was corn dough. Their blood was the small juice that comes out of fresh kernels when you bite them. They lived on maize. They had been made of maize. They were, more than any other people in any other tradition, exactly what they ate.",
        "And every spring, when the corn was planted, and every autumn when the corn was harvested, the people of the Maya remembered — they did not have to be told — that they were planting and harvesting the substance of their own great-great-grandparents. The cycle of their food and the cycle of their bodies and the cycle of the gods' patience was a single cycle. They walked carefully on it.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The gods made three drafts of human beings before they got it right. There is no shame in the early failures. The shame is in not finding, eventually, the maize. Whoever is paying attention to the small fox running up the path is closer to the right material than the council of frustrated gods who are not yet listening." },
        "The Popol Vuh — the great Mayan creation book, written down in the sixteenth century by a Quiche Mayan scribe to preserve what the conquistadors were busy burning — recounts this in its opening sections. The book survives. The maize survives. The people survive. The mountains remain unseeable through, and that is the mild handicap the gods, in the end, decided we needed in order for them to remain useful to us — and we have, by and large, paid them the courteous candle the original people promised."
    ]
}
);

