window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "baba-yaga",
    title: "Baba Yaga",
    subtitle: "Of the witch in the chicken-legged hut, who eats some who knock and helps others",
    civilization: "slavic",
    themes: ["Crone", "Forest", "Test", "Wisdom"],
    content: [
        "There is a hut in the deep forest. The hut stands on two enormous chicken legs. The legs are scaly and yellow and they walk where they please, stalking through the birch trees, turning the hut to face whichever way the inhabitant wishes. The fence around the hut is built of human bones, with skulls set on each post. The skulls have small candles in them at night. The gate is the jaw of some enormous animal whose species is no longer remembered. The pestle in the yard is the size of a tree. The mortar is the size of a small boat — and the mortar is also, if needed, a vehicle: the witch travels in it, propelling herself with the pestle, sweeping her tracks behind her with a broom.",
        "The witch's name is Baba Yaga. She is very old. She has long iron teeth. She sleeps with her feet at one wall of the hut and her head at the other and her nose pressed against the ceiling. She is not a fairy in any soft sense. She is the forest itself, given a face and a kitchen.",
        "Travelers who come into the deep forest sometimes find the chicken-legged hut. The hut, sensing them, turns its door away. The travelers must say the right words. \"Hut, hut, turn your back to the forest, your front to me.\" The hut turns. The door opens. Baba Yaga is inside, on her great stove. She looks up.",
        "She looks at the traveler. She decides at once whether to eat them or to help them. She has a method. The method is not exactly clear to outsiders. But it has to do with whether the traveler answers her questions cleanly, whether the traveler does the small tasks she asks of them without complaint, and whether the traveler, in some deep way, has been sent to her or has merely wandered in by mistake. The wanderers she eats. The sent ones she helps.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "There was once a girl named Vasilisa. Her mother died when she was small. Her mother, dying, gave her a small wooden doll and said: \"When you are in trouble, give the doll a little food and ask its advice. Trust it. It is your mother in another shape.\" Vasilisa kept the doll in her pocket.",
        "Her father remarried. The new wife had two daughters of her own. They were cruel to Vasilisa in the small ways stepmothers and stepsisters in such stories are usually cruel. They gave her the worst tasks. They saved the best food for themselves. They mocked her at every opportunity. The doll in her pocket consoled her every night.",
        "One winter the stepmother decided she could no longer bear Vasilisa in the house. She put out all the fires and pretended that there was no light left to cook by. She sent Vasilisa, alone, into the forest, ostensibly to fetch fire from the only known house in the forest. The only known house in the forest was Baba Yaga's.",
        "Vasilisa walked. She walked all day. The trees grew larger. The forest grew darker. She walked all night. The doll in her pocket said: \"Keep going. The way is long but the way is right.\" She kept going.",
        "She came at dawn to a clearing. In the clearing the chicken-legged hut was standing on its two great legs, the bone-fence around it, the candle-skulls on the posts. The gate of jaw stood open. The hut turned to face her.",
        "Baba Yaga came out. She was even taller than the stories said. Her iron teeth caught the morning light.",
        "\"What do you want?\" she said.",
        "\"Fire,\" said Vasilisa. \"My stepmother's hearth has gone out. I was sent.\"",
        "\"You may have it,\" said Baba Yaga, \"but you must work for it. Three days. While you are here you will sweep my yard. You will cook my meals. You will sort the wheat from the chaff in my granary. You will sort the poppy seed from the dust in my pantry. If at the end of three days the work is done, I will give you fire. If not, I will eat you. Begin.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Vasilisa got to work. The work was enormous. She could not have finished any of it on her own.",
        "But each night, when Baba Yaga had gone to bed, Vasilisa fed the small doll a crust of bread and a sip of broth and asked its advice. The doll worked while Vasilisa slept. By morning the yard was swept. By morning the meals were cooking. By morning the granary was sorted, every wheat grain in one bin and every chaff in another. By morning the poppy seed was clean.",
        "Each morning Baba Yaga inspected the work. She frowned. She had set tasks she was sure could not be done. She found them done. She could not eat the girl on the agreed terms.",
        "On the third morning she sat the girl down at her great kitchen table. \"Tell me, child,\" she said, the iron teeth showing slightly. \"How did you finish all this work?\"",
        "Vasilisa thought for a moment. Then she said the truthful thing, because she had been raised to be truthful. She said: \"My mother's blessing helped me.\"",
        "Baba Yaga went very still. The iron teeth disappeared back behind her lips. She stood up. She said: \"Then go. I will not have a blessed child in my house. Take your fire. Take it now. Quickly.\"",
        "She gave Vasilisa a small skull from the fence-post. The skull's eye-sockets glowed with a low red fire. \"Carry this back to your stepmother,\" said Baba Yaga. \"It will give you your light.\"",
        "Vasilisa took the skull and walked the long road home. She arrived at her stepmother's house at dusk. The stepmother and the two stepsisters had been waiting in the cold dark for two days. They opened the door. They saw the small skull glowing in Vasilisa's hand.",
        "The skull's eye-sockets turned. They fixed on the stepmother. They fixed on the two stepsisters. The fire from inside the skull leaped out. The stepmother and the two stepsisters were burned to ash in a single moment, in three small piles in the doorway. Vasilisa stood in the empty house, holding the skull, untouched.",
        "She set the skull on the mantelpiece. She rebuilt the hearth fire from its glow. She lived in the house alone after that.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The witch in the chicken-legged hut does not eat everyone who comes to her door. She eats the ones who come without their mother's blessing in their pocket. The wise traveler carries something small and well-fed to ask, and the witch in turn does not always insist on the meal she had been planning." },
        "Baba Yaga has many other stories. She helped some heroes. She ate some heroes. She baked some children for breakfast. She set some children up for life. The principle is consistent: the heart of the visitor is what is being measured. The fence of bones is the warning. The stove is the ambivalence. The travelers who survive her are the travelers who were ready to meet her, and the travelers who do not are the travelers who were not."
    ]
},

{
    id: "firebird",
    title: "The Firebird",
    subtitle: "Of a tsar's apple-thief, the prince's long quest, and a feather that lit a tower",
    civilization: "slavic",
    themes: ["Quest", "Beauty", "Patience", "Brothers"],
    content: [
        "There was a tsar who had a beautiful orchard. In the center of the orchard grew a single apple tree, and on the tree grew apples of pure gold — small, perfect, glowing softly even at noon. The tsar valued the tree above all his other possessions. He counted the apples each evening.",
        "One morning he counted and found one apple missing. He set a guard. The next morning, another apple was missing. He set two guards. The next morning, another apple was missing.",
        "He had three sons. The eldest was the proudest. The middle was the quickest. The youngest was the quietest, and the most overlooked, and his name was Ivan.",
        "The tsar set his eldest son to watch the tree at night. The eldest son sat by the tree until midnight, then fell asleep. He woke in the morning to find another apple gone. He could not say what had happened. The tsar set the middle son next. The same thing happened. He fell asleep at midnight. An apple was gone in the morning.",
        "Then it was Ivan's turn.",
        "Ivan sat by the tree at midnight and pricked his finger with a small knife each time he felt himself nodding off. He did not sleep.",
        "At the third hour of the night a brightness came over the orchard. A great bird descended out of the sky. Its feathers were all of fire — orange and gold and red, every feather glowing — and the orchard was lit by it as by a lantern. The bird landed in the apple tree. It picked an apple in its beak.",
        "Ivan reached up. He grabbed at the bird. The bird startled and flew up. Ivan held — for one heartbeat — its tail. He came away with a single tail-feather. The bird was gone. The orchard was dark again.",
        "Ivan brought the feather to his father at dawn. The feather, set on the throne-room table, lit the entire room as if a lamp were burning. The tsar gasped.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He sent his three sons out to find the firebird and bring it back alive. The eldest set out, then the middle, then Ivan, in turn.",
        "Ivan's brothers wandered for a season and gave up and went home. Ivan rode farther. He came at last to a fork in the road. There was a stone at the fork. Carved on the stone were three lines. \"Take the right-hand road, lose your horse but keep your life. Take the left-hand road, lose your life. Take the middle road, become rich.\"",
        "Ivan took the right-hand road.",
        "Within a day a great grey wolf came out of the trees and ate his horse. Ivan stood beside the bones and was not sure what to do.",
        "The grey wolf, having eaten, said in a clear human voice: \"Ivan. I am sorry about the horse. The sign at the fork was specific. But I will carry you wherever you need to go in exchange. Climb on my back. Tell me what you need.\"",
        "Ivan climbed on. \"I need the firebird,\" he said.",
        "The wolf ran. The wolf ran for days. The wolf could cover, in a single bound, a distance that would have taken a horse a week. They came at last to a far country and a far palace.",
        "The wolf set Ivan down at the wall. \"Inside,\" said the wolf, \"is the cage of the firebird. It is in the central garden. The cage is gold. Take only the bird. Do not, for any reason, take the cage. The cage is enchanted to scream if it is moved.\"",
        "Ivan went over the wall. He found the cage. The firebird was in it, sleeping, its feathers dim in the night. The cage was gold. Ivan, who had never seen anything so beautiful as the cage, decided he would take it too.",
        "He lifted the cage. The cage screamed. The guards came running. Ivan was caught.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He was brought before the tsar of that country. The tsar said: \"Why are you stealing my firebird?\"",
        "Ivan, who had been raised to be honest, told him the whole story. The tsar listened. The tsar said: \"Very well. I will not punish you, on one condition. There is a king named Afron in another country, and he has a horse with a golden mane. Bring me that horse. Then I will give you the firebird.\"",
        "Ivan, despondent, went back over the wall. The grey wolf was waiting. \"You took the cage,\" said the wolf gently. \"I told you not to.\"",
        "\"I know,\" said Ivan.",
        "They went to Afron's country. The wolf set him down at the wall. \"The horse,\" said the wolf, \"is in the central stable. Take the horse. Do not, for any reason, take the bridle. The bridle is enchanted. It will scream.\"",
        "Ivan went over the wall. He found the horse. The horse was beautiful. The bridle hanging beside it was even more beautiful. Ivan, who had not yet learned, took the bridle too.",
        "The bridle screamed. Ivan was caught.",
        "He was brought before King Afron. \"Why are you stealing my horse?\"",
        "Ivan told him the whole story. Afron listened. Afron said: \"Very well. I will not punish you on one condition. There is a princess named Helen the Beautiful in another country. Bring her to me as my bride. Then I will give you the horse.\"",
        "Ivan, more despondent, went back to the wolf.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The wolf carried him to Helen the Beautiful's country. \"This time,\" said the wolf, \"do not even try. I will fetch her myself. Wait at the bridge.\"",
        "The wolf vanished into the gardens of the princess. He came back, carrying the princess in his teeth — gently, by the hem of her dress, the princess riding sideways and laughing in spite of her own surprise. The princess, set down at the bridge, looked at Ivan. Ivan looked at her. They liked each other immediately. The wolf rolled his eyes.",
        "But Ivan now had a problem. He had to give the princess to King Afron. He could not bear it. He had ridden two days with her on the wolf's back, talking, and he could not bear the thought of handing her over.",
        "The grey wolf considered. The wolf said: \"I can take Helen's shape. I will go in to Afron. I will be his bride for one night. In the morning I will revert and run away. You take the horse and ride after.\"",
        "They did this. The wolf in Helen's shape married Afron in a hurried ceremony. In the morning the wolf became the wolf again and ran out of the palace, leaving Afron in considerable shock. Ivan rode out on the golden-maned horse with the real Helen riding behind him.",
        "But Ivan had now another problem. He had to give the horse to the firebird's tsar. He had grown attached to the horse too. The wolf considered again. The wolf said: \"I can take the horse's shape too. Same trick. Hand me over. I will run away in the morning.\"",
        "They did. Ivan handed over the wolf-as-horse to the firebird's tsar. The tsar, delighted, gave him the firebird and its cage. In the morning the wolf-as-horse became the wolf and ran out of the stables, leaving the tsar in considerable shock.",
        "Ivan rode home with Helen the Beautiful behind him, the firebird in its cage at the saddle, the golden-maned horse beside him, and the grey wolf padding alongside.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "His two older brothers met him on the road. They had not found anything. They saw what Ivan had brought back. They were, in the way of older brothers in such stories, instantly furious.",
        "They killed him in his sleep. They cut him in three pieces. They took the firebird and the horse and Helen and rode home to the tsar, threatening Helen with terrible deaths if she said one word about what they had done.",
        "The grey wolf, returning from a hunt, found Ivan in pieces by the road. The wolf, who had grown fond of Ivan, was furious. The wolf put Ivan back together. The wolf went out and caught a small black bird that was rumored to know the spring of the water of life and brought back, in a small leaf, a single drop. The wolf put the drop on Ivan's lips.",
        "Ivan sat up. He was alive. The wolf told him what had happened.",
        "Ivan rode home on the wolf's back. He arrived at his father's palace just as the wedding of Helen the Beautiful and his eldest brother was about to take place. Helen, when she saw Ivan come into the hall, fainted with relief and then, when she recovered, told the entire story to the tsar.",
        "The tsar exiled the two elder brothers. He restored Ivan to favor. Ivan married Helen. The firebird, in its cage, sang at the wedding feast — the only known recorded singing of a firebird, and the songs of every nightingale ever since are said to be small approximate echoes of it.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Whoever has been told not to take the cage and takes the cage anyway has earned a longer story than they had bargained for. But the longer story, in the right company, can become the only story worth having lived." },
        "The grey wolf went back into the deep forest. He had said, on parting, that he would come if Ivan needed him again. Ivan needed him a few times more, in further small adventures, and the wolf always came, and what became of the wolf in the very end the storytellers do not specify — perhaps because no story would feel complete in which a creature so reliable was finally said to have died."
    ]
},

{
    id: "veles-perun",
    title: "Veles and Perun",
    subtitle: "The yearly war of the thunderer and the snake at the root of the world tree",
    civilization: "slavic",
    themes: ["Storm", "Serpent", "Cosmic struggle", "Seasons"],
    content: [
        "Above the world, in the sky, sits Perun — the thunder-god, the lord of the upper hall, the one with the great oak in his courtyard. He is bearded. He carries an axe and a great stone hammer. His chariot is drawn by a goat. When his wheels turn, thunder sounds; when his hammer falls, lightning falls.",
        "Below the world — in the deep, in the marshes, under the roots of the great world-tree — slithers Veles. Veles is a serpent and also a man, depending on the hour. He is the lord of cattle and of magic and of the dead. He has horns. He keeps the souls of the departed in long quiet pastures, where they graze contentedly until they are released into the next life. He also has, on his lower coil, a quality of theft.",
        "The two of them, Perun above and Veles below, are kept in a long uneasy balance. The world depends on the balance. When Perun is in the upper hall and Veles is in the lower marsh and neither of them is moving, the world is well.",
        "But Veles is restless. He has, periodically, a strong desire to climb. Sometimes he climbs the world-tree itself — for the world-tree connects upper and lower country, root and crown — and tries to take, from the upper hall, some of Perun's possessions. Sometimes he tries to steal Perun's wife. Sometimes he tries to steal Perun's son. Sometimes — most often — he tries to steal Perun's cattle, because cattle are wealth, and wealth is a thing a serpent-lord understands, and the souls of the dead in his pastures are a kind of cattle to him also, but the upper cattle are different cattle, and he wants them.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "When Veles climbs, Perun sees from his high seat. Perun does not negotiate. He picks up his stone hammer and his axe and he comes down off the high seat and he gives chase.",
        "Veles, surprised at the speed of the descent, slips back down the world-tree. He hides in the long grass. He hides as a snake in a cow-byre. He hides as a tree, a stone, a man, a horse — for he is a god of transformations and he takes what shape he needs.",
        "Perun follows. Perun finds him. Perun strikes wherever he finds him. Lightning is the trail of these searches. The reason lightning splits an oak in a particular field is because Veles had, briefly, taken the form of that oak. The reason lightning strikes a particular cow on a particular hillside is because Veles had, briefly, taken the form of that cow. The reason lightning strikes a particular man, struck by his own front door, is because Veles had, briefly — improbably — taken the form of that man.",
        "Veles, after enough strikes, gives up the climb. He retreats into the marsh. He flows back under the roots of the world-tree. He returns the cattle, or the wife, or the son, or whatever he had stolen. The rains come. The rains are Perun's relief, the long letting-down of the storm-god's anger, and the rains soak the earth, and the seeds in the earth take the rains, and the year's crops come up.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "This pattern repeats every year. The Slavs of the old country marked it on their calendars without quite knowing they were marking it. The dry hot weeks of late summer were the weeks Veles was climbing — the weeks the rivers shrank and the cattle grew thin and the storms had not yet broken. The storms, when they came, were Perun's pursuit. The relief of the autumn was the slow re-establishment of the balance.",
        "Veles is not, in this telling, a villain. He is the necessary opposite. Without his climbing, Perun would not strike. Without Perun's striking, the rains would not fall. Without the rains, there would be no harvest. The world depends on the long predictable quarrel of the two of them — the snake who keeps wanting more, the thunderer who keeps insisting on the law — and the priests of the old country knew it, and the priests blessed both, and the festivals of both were held in the same season, sometimes in the same field, sometimes by the same priest who had no difficulty holding both ends of a paradox in his hands.",
        "When the Slavs were converted to Christianity, the missionaries inherited this paradox. They renamed Perun as Saint Elijah — for Elijah, in the older book, also rode a chariot and brought thunder. They renamed Veles as Saint Vlas — and assigned him to the patronage of cattle, which had been his portfolio all along. The festival days line up exactly with the older festivals. The peasants brought their cattle to be blessed on Veles's day under his Christian name. The peasants prayed for the rain on Perun's day under his Christian name. They had not noticed any meaningful conversion. The gods had simply been given new clothes.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The thunder above and the snake below are not two enemies. They are the same paragraph in two languages. Whoever lives between them and prays for both is the only honest practitioner of either religion." },
        "The world-tree at the center of all this — the great oak, the great ash, the great larch, depending on which Slavic country you are in — is still standing in some quiet places. The roots are still in the marsh. The crown is still in the high air. The eagle that lives at the crown and the snake that coils at the root still send insults to each other through a small messenger, and the squirrel that runs the trunk in this version of the story is not Ratatosk — he has another name — but his job is the same, and the long quarrel he ferries has been going on for as long as there have been people to keep track of it."
    ]
}
);

