window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "anansi-stories",
    title: "Anansi and the Sky-God's Stories",
    subtitle: "How a small spider bargained the entire treasury of the world's stories down out of heaven",
    civilization: "african",
    themes: ["Trickster", "Stories", "Cleverness", "Bargain"],
    content: [
        "In the early days of the world all the stories belonged to Nyame, the sky-god. He kept them in a small carved wooden box at the top of his hall in the upper sky. The box was small but the stories inside were many — every story that had ever been told and every story that ever could be told, all of them folded down very compact, like silk in a chest. Nyame was fond of the box. He would sometimes take a story out, look at it, fold it back. He did not let any of them go down to the world below. The world below, he had decided, did not need stories. The world below had work to do.",
        "The people on the world below worked hard and were tired and had nothing to say to each other in the evenings. They would sit by their fires after a day in the fields, and they would have only the small daily things to talk about — the weather, the cattle, the price of yams — and the conversations would peter out by the third hour, and they would go to bed early because they could think of nothing else to do.",
        "Anansi the spider — small, grey, eight-legged, vain, perpetually scheming — saw this and decided he would do something about it.",
        "He climbed up the long thread of his own making, all the way to the upper sky. He came to the door of Nyame's hall. He knocked.",
        "Nyame looked up from his throne. \"Who is at the door?\"",
        "\"Anansi,\" said the small voice. \"I have come to buy the box of stories.\"",
        "Nyame laughed. He laughed for a long time. Then he wiped his eye and said: \"Little spider. The box of stories cannot be bought. But — but — if you wish to entertain me, I will set you a price. Bring me four things. Bring me Onini, the python who is longer than a palm tree. Bring me Osebo, the leopard with teeth like razors. Bring me Mmoboro, the swarm of hornets that fills a tree. Bring me Mmoatia, the dwarf-spirit who lives in the deep forest and cannot be caught. Bring all four. Then we will discuss.\"",
        "Anansi bowed. He climbed back down to earth.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He went home to his wife Aso. She was patient. She had been married to him a long time. He told her the assignment. She thought for a moment.",
        "\"Onini the python is the easiest,\" she said. \"He is vain about his length. Bring a long stick. Tell him you and your wife disagreed about whether he is longer than the stick. He will offer to lie down beside the stick to prove it. Tie him to the stick while he is lying down.\"",
        "Anansi did. The python was vain. The python lay down. Anansi tied him with vine. He carried him, very heavy, up to the upper sky.",
        "Nyame was mildly impressed. \"One. Three more.\"",
        "Anansi went home. \"Now Osebo,\" he said.",
        "Aso said: \"The leopard is too proud to ask for help. Dig a deep pit on his evening path. Cover it with leaves. He will fall in. Then offer to help him out — but only after he has agreed to whatever you ask.\"",
        "Anansi did. The leopard fell in. He raged. Anansi looked down at him. \"I will get you out,\" he said pleasantly, \"if you let me bind your paws so you cannot scratch me by accident.\" The leopard, embarrassed, agreed. Anansi let down a long thread. He bound the leopard's paws. He pulled the leopard out. He carried the bound leopard up to the upper sky.",
        "Nyame was more impressed. \"Two. Two more.\"",
        "Anansi went home. \"Now Mmoboro the hornets,\" he said.",
        "Aso said: \"Hornets are afraid of rain. Take a calabash of water. Pour it over their tree on a dry day. Tell them the rain has come and they should take shelter in your calabash. They will go in. Cap it.\"",
        "Anansi did. He carried the heavy buzzing calabash up to the upper sky.",
        "Nyame was nearly amused. \"Three. One more — and the one I think you will not get. Mmoatia, the dwarf-spirit. She lives in the forest and she is not vain and she does not fear rain.\"",
        "Anansi went home. He thought a long time. Aso thought also.",
        "She said: \"Carve a small wooden doll. Cover it with sticky gum. Put a bowl of yams in front of it. Sit it under a tree. Mmoatia is curious. She will come up to the doll. She will speak to it. She will be insulted when the doll does not answer. She will hit it. She will get stuck.\"",
        "Anansi did. He carved a small wooden doll. He covered it with the gum that comes from a particular tree. He placed it under the tree where he knew Mmoatia walked. He put the bowl of yams in front of it. He hid in a branch above and waited.",
        "Mmoatia came at evening. She saw the doll. She greeted it politely. The doll did not respond. She greeted it more loudly. The doll did not respond. She struck the doll across the cheek. Her hand stuck to the gum. She tried to pull it free. She struck with the other hand. Both hands stuck. She kicked. Both feet stuck.",
        "Anansi climbed down. He freed the doll from the gum (with the dwarf-spirit attached). He carried the whole sticky package up to the upper sky.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Nyame was now genuinely impressed. He had set the four tasks expecting that Anansi would fail on at least one. The little spider was sitting on his hall floor with all four delivered.",
        "\"Very well,\" said Nyame. \"You have earned it. Take the box.\"",
        "Anansi took the small carved wooden box. He climbed back down the long thread. He came home.",
        "He opened the box on his table. The stories tumbled out — silken, glittering, alive — and they flew out the windows of his house and out into the world. They went into every village. They went into every home. They settled around every fire. The people who had been sitting silent began to speak. They told the stories to each other. The stories were instantly the property of everyone who heard them.",
        "Anansi did not keep them. He could not have. They were too many. He was happy to let them go. He had wanted to be the one who brought them, not the one who kept them.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The stories are no one's. The stories belong to whoever picks them up at whichever fire and tells them onward. The little spider who climbed to heaven for the box did not buy the stories — he ransomed them, on behalf of every fire that has been lit since." },
        "From that day all stories told in any village in the country are called Anansesem — the spider's stories — even when they have nothing to do with Anansi. The name was given as a small permanent thank-you to the spider who climbed for them. The peasants fold the silken stories around their evenings still, and the silence after dinner is no longer absolute, and the long unfilled hours that used to send everyone to bed early have been filled, generation after generation, by the contents of that box."
    ]
},

{
    id: "ogun",
    title: "Ogun, the Iron God",
    subtitle: "How the road to the world was opened by a smith who would not let a forest stop him",
    civilization: "african",
    themes: ["Iron", "Path", "War", "Solitude"],
    content: [
        "In the early days the upper gods looked down at the earth and saw that it was overgrown. There were no roads. There were no fields. There was only forest — dense, endless, full of vines that strangled trees and trees that strangled vines, full of large animals with appetites and small biting things with appetites also, and the gods could not get down to live among the people because there was no path. The people, for that matter, could not get from village to village. They lived in small isolated clearings and shouted news to each other across the canopy.",
        "The upper gods held a council. They decided to send one of their number down to clear a road. They asked: who will go?",
        "The first god sent down was Orunmila, the god of wisdom. He went down with a soft cloth and a book of incantations. He stood at the edge of the forest. He read his incantations. The forest did not move. He came back up.",
        "The second god sent down was Obatala, the god of creation, the white-cloaked one. He went down with his sculptor's tools. He looked at the forest. He could not figure out where to begin. He came back up.",
        "Several other gods went down and came back up. None of them could begin. The forest was not the kind of obstacle their tools were for.",
        "Then Ogun came forward.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Ogun was the smith of the gods. He worked at a great forge on a high cliff in the upper country. His arms were black with the soot of the work. His apron was burned through in many places. He did not speak much. He spent most of his days hammering metal — for the other gods needed swords, and chains, and pots, and Ogun's hands were the hands that made them.",
        "He stepped forward in the council and said: \"Give me iron. I will go.\"",
        "They gave him iron. He took a great mass of it. He went back to his forge. He hammered out, over a long week, every implement he would need. He made a long broad-bladed cutlass. He made a heavy axe with two edges. He made a bush-knife. He made a hook on a long pole. He made the short curved scythe. He made the large flat hoe. He sharpened all of these on his great whetstone until they bit the air.",
        "He went down. He stood at the edge of the forest. He did not speak any incantations. He swung the cutlass.",
        "The first vine fell. The second vine fell. The first tree fell. He kept moving.",
        "He swung for an hour. He swung for a day. He swung for many days. The road appeared behind him — a wide cleared track, the ground bare, the small obstacles cleared away by his other tools.",
        "He cut for many years. He did not eat much. He did not sleep much. He cut all the way from the high northern mountains to the southern sea. He cut, where needed, sideways, to connect village to village. He cut switchbacks up cliffs. He cut bridge-fords through the worst marshes. The road appeared behind him as a network — a long arterial system of cleared land — and the people of every village began, for the first time, to walk from one to the other.",
        "When Ogun had finished — when the road was complete — he went home to the upper country. The other gods were sitting in their council. They had not done anything in his absence except watch the road appear.",
        "He stood in the doorway. He was thin. He was burned by the sun. His hands were calloused beyond recognition. His apron was in shreds. He set down the cutlass.",
        "\"It is done,\" he said.",
        "The other gods said: \"Excellent. Now we will go down.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "They went down. They walked the new roads. The people, seeing the gods on the new roads for the first time, fell on their faces. The gods accepted the offerings. They set up the festivals. They became the patrons of the various towns. They were honored in song and in sacrifice.",
        "But none of them praised Ogun.",
        "Ogun, in the upper country, watched. He had been the one to clear the road. He was not getting credit for it. The other gods were taking the seats and the offerings and the candles, and Ogun, who had done the actual cutting, was being treated as if he were merely the maintenance department.",
        "He grew angry. He grew slowly, deeply, for a long time, angry. He went down to a small village and demanded an offering. The village, surprised, asked what offering would be proper. He said: \"A dog. White. Slaughtered properly. The blood poured at the foot of an iron tool. That is my offering. Do that and I will protect you. Fail to do it and I will not.\"",
        "The village did. From that day Ogun received his offerings. He received them from blacksmiths. He received them from soldiers. He received them from anyone whose work involved iron — surgeons, butchers, farmers with iron plows, eventually railwaymen, eventually mechanics, eventually computer engineers, in some modern Yoruba towns even now. Ogun is a god of iron, and iron is what cuts and what shapes and what defends. Wherever iron is the substance of the work, Ogun is the patron of the worker.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The god who cleared the road was not at first praised for it. He had to come down and ask. There is a lesson in this for every patient laborer whose work made the conditions for everyone else's praise: do not wait for it to be offered. Walk down the road and stand in it." },
        "Ogun lives, in some traditions, alone in a small house at the edge of a wood. He prefers the company of his forge to the company of other gods. He came back among the gods only to make a point. Once the point was made he returned to the forge. He is still hammering. The clear ringing sound that comes faintly out of certain forests at certain hours of the night, the storytellers say, is Ogun on his anvil. The people who can hear it leave a small white offering at the door of their iron tools and the iron tools, in return, do not break."
    ]
},

{
    id: "mwindo",
    title: "Mwindo, the Hero in the Belt",
    subtitle: "Of the boy his father tried to drown, who walked through the underworld and came back king",
    civilization: "african",
    themes: ["Father & son", "Quest", "Underworld", "Return"],
    content: [
        "Shemwindo was a chief of the Nyanga people in the deep equatorial forest, and Shemwindo had seven wives, and Shemwindo had announced — long before any of his wives had borne anything — that he would tolerate only daughters in his household. A son, Shemwindo had said, would be killed at birth. Sons threatened the throne. Sons were rivals. He wanted only daughters, and he wanted his daughters to bear sons later that he could control.",
        "Six wives bore six daughters. The seventh wife, Iyangura's sister, became pregnant. She felt at once that the child in her was different. She felt it speak to her in a voice she had not had to teach. She felt it move in a pattern.",
        "The boy was born from the middle finger of her left hand — for he had refused, in his small wisdom, to be born the usual way. He came out wearing a small bag of charms across his chest, holding a small drum, and singing a song he had composed in the womb. He was already speaking. He was already walking. His name, he announced, was Mwindo.",
        "Shemwindo, hearing of the birth, came running. He had a spear. He intended to kill the boy at the doorway. The boy, sitting calmly on the floor of the hut, looked up at his father and continued his song. Shemwindo's spear-arm froze. He could not strike. The boy went on singing.",
        "Shemwindo, raging, ordered the boy buried alive. The villagers, who were afraid of Shemwindo, dug a hole. They put the boy in the hole. They covered the hole with earth. The next morning the boy was sitting on top of the hole, eating breakfast.",
        "Shemwindo, raging more, ordered the boy sealed in a drum and thrown into the river. The villagers sealed him in a drum and threw the drum into the river. The drum floated downstream. The boy was singing inside the drum. The drum floated through several villages. People along the bank could hear the singing. They came running but could not catch the drum.",
        "The drum floated, finally, into the village of his aunt Iyangura, who was now married to a chief downstream. Iyangura saw the drum, heard the singing, recognized the song — for it was the song her sister had hummed as a child — and waded into the river and pulled the drum to shore. She broke it open. Mwindo stepped out, dry, smiling.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He told her the story. She wept. She had not seen her sister in years. She kept Mwindo with her. He grew up — visibly, rapidly, in the way of the children of myth — into a young man within a season.",
        "He decided he would go back. He had business with his father.",
        "He took his small bag of charms. He took his small drum. He took, also, an enchanted scepter that had been given to him by his aunt. He walked back upstream.",
        "He came to his father's village. The village was different than he remembered. The crops were thin. The cattle were thin. The villagers were tired. Shemwindo, on his stool, had grown old and bitter, and his daughters had not married, and his throne was not what it had been.",
        "Shemwindo saw his son walking up the path. He stood up in horror. He turned. He ran out the back of the village. He ran into the forest. He kept running. He ran for so many days that he passed beyond the borders of the upper world. He went down — into the country of the dead — and he hid himself in the hall of Muisa, the lord of that country, and he refused to come out.",
        "Mwindo followed.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He walked west. He walked into the deep forest. He walked into the country where the road ends. He came at last to a great cleft in a rock — the entrance to Muisa's country — and he walked in.",
        "Muisa was an enormous god, half-skeletal, very black. He sat on a stool of bones. He looked at the small bright boy walking into his hall.",
        "\"What do you want, child?\"",
        "\"My father.\"",
        "\"Your father is here. He came in for shelter. I will not give him up easily. There are tasks. Three. Whoever passes them may have what they came for.\"",
        "Mwindo agreed.",
        "First task: Muisa gave him a wooden mallet and told him to break a great rock into gravel by sundown. Mwindo struck the rock with his small drum and the rock shattered into gravel in one beat.",
        "Second task: Muisa gave him a small calabash and told him to fetch all the water of the Eastern River into the calabash. Mwindo dipped the calabash. The calabash, by his charms, expanded inside but stayed small outside, and the river ran into it, and by sundown the river was dry and the calabash was as small as it had been.",
        "Third task: Muisa gave him a hoe and told him to plant, water, harvest, mill, and bake bread from a field of millet, all by sundown. Mwindo, by song, called the millet to do its growing. By sundown there was a small loaf of fresh bread in his hand.",
        "Muisa, who had been hoping the boy would fail at one of these, sighed and gave him his father.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Mwindo brought his father back up the long road. They came to the village.",
        "The villagers expected — perhaps even hoped — that Mwindo would now kill his father. He had been buried alive. He had been thrown in a drum. He had walked into the country of the dead to retrieve the man who had done it. The villagers thought there would be vengeance.",
        "Mwindo did not kill him.",
        "He took his father's hand. He led him to the chief's stool. He sat his father down on it. \"You are still chief,\" he said. \"You will rule alongside me. We will rule together. I cannot let you go unpunished — but the punishment will be that you will have to live with what you did, in the same hall as the son you tried to kill, and will have to look at me every morning. That is the punishment.\"",
        "Shemwindo wept. He sat on the stool. He could not look at his son for a long time. He grew older. He grew gentler. He spent his last years instructing the village on the subjects he was sure of, which were not many, and he grew into a kind of dignified senior advisor by the end. Mwindo did most of the actual ruling. The village prospered. The cattle grew fat again.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The son who has every right to kill his father, and who instead seats his father on the stool beside his own, has chosen the harder rule. The harder rule is the one that keeps a village together for the next generation." },
        "The full epic of Mwindo runs to many days of telling among the Nyanga, and there are dozens of episodes the storytellers can drop in or leave out, depending on the audience and the hour and the strength of their voice. The center of it, however, is always the same: a boy who would not be killed, who walked through every country to find what was owed him, and who chose, when he had it, to rule beside the man who had tried to bury him, rather than to bury him in turn."
    ]
}
);

