window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "simurgh",
    title: "The Simurgh",
    subtitle: "The bird as old as memory, who raised an outcast prince in a nest above the world",
    civilization: "persian",
    themes: ["Bird", "Outcast", "Foster", "Healing"],
    content: [
        "On the highest peak of Mount Alborz, at the very crown of the world, in a nest of cedar branches and lapis-lazuli twigs, lives the Simurgh. She is a bird older than every human memory. She has the head of a dog and the claws of a lion and the body of a peacock and the tail of a serpent and the breast of a person, and her wings, when they spread, can shadow a country. She has lived for ten thousand years. She remembers ages no one else remembers.",
        "She does not, as a rule, come down. She watches. She waits. She listens. She has been there long enough to have lost interest in most of what happens, though every once in a long while a particular event catches her attention.",
        "One such event was the birth of a boy named Zal.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Zal was born to Sam, a great noble of Persia. Sam had hoped for a strong handsome son. The boy who was born was — the midwife reported — entirely white-haired. White from birth. White as old snow. The hair was thick and long and the eyebrows were white and the skin was pale.",
        "Sam, when he saw the boy, recoiled. \"This is a demon,\" he said. \"This is not my son. This is some abomination. Take him. Take him out of my sight.\"",
        "He ordered the infant exposed on the slopes of Alborz. The servants, weeping, did so. They left the small bundle on a high stony place at the foot of the mountain and walked away.",
        "The Simurgh, in her nest at the top, heard the small wailing. She flew down. She lifted the infant in her great soft talons. She carried him back up to her nest.",
        "She raised him. She fed him on the meat she fetched. She covered him in winter with her own wing. She taught him language — for the Simurgh knew every language, and Zal grew up speaking the speech of birds and the speech of beasts and the speech of every nation of men, all simultaneously, all from infancy. He became, growing up in that nest, a young man of unusual gifts. He had no peers. He had only the Simurgh, and she was peer enough.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Sam, meanwhile, in the years that passed, had begun to dream. He dreamed that a man on a strange horse came riding to him in the dust of his own house and held out his hand and said, \"You threw me away. I have come back.\" He woke shaking. He had the dream once a week. He had it for years.",
        "He went, finally, to a wise man. The wise man heard the dream. The wise man said: \"You have a son. He is not dead. Find him. Bring him home. The dream will stop.\"",
        "Sam was old now. He gathered a small expedition. He rode to Mount Alborz. He climbed as high as he could climb. He stood at the foot of the great peak and called.",
        "The Simurgh, in her nest, heard. She knew at once who was calling and why. She had, in her ten thousand years, seen many such returnings. She turned to the young man beside her — Zal, now eighteen, white-haired, beautiful, fluent in every tongue — and she said: \"Your father has come for you. He wants you back. He has changed.\"",
        "Zal was startled. He had not known he had a father. He had thought the Simurgh was both his parents. He looked at her.",
        "She said: \"Go. Go down. You have outgrown my nest. The world is a country of men, and you are a man, and you must live among them. But — \" and she plucked from her own breast three feathers, three of her great long feathers, and pressed them into his hand. \" — when you need me, burn one. The smoke will reach me. I will come. There are three. Use them only when there is no other help.\"",
        "He took the feathers. He embraced her wing. He wept. He climbed down the mountain. He came to his father.",
        "Sam, at the foot of the mountain, fell on his knees. He embraced his white-haired son. He brought him home. The dreams stopped.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Zal grew up among men. He became a great noble of Persia. He married Rudaba, a princess from a neighboring kingdom — they had fallen in love through poems sent over a wall — and they had a child.",
        "But the child was huge. He was so large in the womb that Rudaba could not deliver him. She had been in labor for three days. The midwives had given up. She was dying. Zal stood by her bed, holding her hand, watching her grow weaker.",
        "He remembered the feathers.",
        "He went out into the courtyard. He took one of the three feathers from his bag. He held it to a small candle. The feather caught fire. The smoke went up.",
        "Within minutes a great shadow fell across the courtyard. The Simurgh landed in his garden — vast, red, green, golden, her serpent-tail trailing across the grass.",
        "She listened to his explanation. She nodded. \"Cut her open,\" she said. \"On her left side. With a fine knife. Take the child out. Then sew her up with this — \" and she gave him a small phial of her own milk \" — and apply this paste of leaves I am laying down here at her wound, and she will heal. The child will be enormous and he will be the greatest hero Persia has ever known. His name will be Rostam. Care for him.\"",
        "Zal did. The midwives, instructed, performed the cesarean — perhaps the first in Persian history. Rudaba lived. The child was born. He was huge. He grew, the storytellers say, to be the greatest hero of Persia, capable of single-handedly defeating armies. His story is its own long tale.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Many years later, in the matter of Rostam's son Sohrab, Zal would burn a second feather. The Simurgh would come again. She would heal. The third feather, the storytellers say, has not yet been burned. It is still, somewhere, in the keeping of the descendants of Zal, who are the descendants of Rostam, who are the descendants of every great Persian hero who came after, and the feather is still red and gold and waiting.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The bird as old as memory does not come down for everything. She comes down for the white-haired boy left on a stone. She comes down for the labor that has gone three days. She comes down for the wound that no surgeon's hand can close. The feathers are precious because they are few." },
        "The Simurgh has appeared in many later stories, including the great Sufi poem The Conference of the Birds, in which thirty birds make a long pilgrimage to find her and discover, at the end, that they are her — that simurgh in Persian punningly means \"thirty birds\" — and so the bird at the top of the world is also the assembly of seekers who set out to find her, and the long journey is the bird's own meaning. The white-haired boy in the cedar nest grew into a man who never quite forgot which one of those thirty birds he had been, and he passed the small inheritance down with the feathers."
    ]
},

{
    id: "rostam-sohrab",
    title: "Rostam and Sohrab",
    subtitle: "Of the father who killed his son before learning his name",
    civilization: "persian",
    themes: ["Father & son", "Recognition", "War", "Tragedy"],
    content: [
        "Rostam was the greatest hero of Persia. He was the son of Zal — the white-haired one, raised by the Simurgh — and he was tall as a tree and strong as ten oxen, and his horse Rakhsh was a horse who had refused every other rider and had chosen Rostam himself by walking up to him in a paddock and laying its head on his shoulder. Rostam had killed white demons. He had killed dragons. He had been the chief defender of Persia for forty years.",
        "On a hunting expedition, far from home, in the country of Turan, Rostam slept under a tree. His horse Rakhsh wandered off in the night to graze. While Rostam slept, the horse was found by the cavalry of the local lord and led away. Rostam, waking in the morning to find Rakhsh gone, walked into the nearest town to inquire.",
        "The town belonged to King Saman, whose daughter was named Tahmineh. Tahmineh, hearing that the great Rostam — whose deeds were sung in every Persian and Turanian tavern — was at her father's gate, came down to meet him. She had loved his reputation since girlhood. She offered him every hospitality.",
        "He stayed three nights. On the third night Tahmineh came to his chamber. She offered herself. She asked, in return, only one thing: a child. \"Let me bear your son,\" she said. \"You will leave in the morning. I do not ask you to stay. I ask only for what your name and your blood would be in a child.\"",
        "Rostam, not unmoved, agreed. He gave her, before he left, a single onyx armband — old, ancestral — and he said: \"If our child is a daughter, put this in her hair. If our child is a son, fasten it on his arm. He will know whose son he is by it. So will any man who knows me.\"",
        "He rode home on the recovered Rakhsh. He did not return.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Tahmineh bore a son. She named him Sohrab. He grew, as Rostam's son, abnormally fast. By eight he was the size of a man of twenty. By twelve he was the strongest fighter in his country. By fourteen he was a young giant.",
        "She had not, however, told him his father's name. She was afraid. She was afraid that if Sohrab learned he was Rostam's son, he would go to Persia to find his father, and either Persia would absorb him, or worse — for there were always wars between Persia and Turan — he would meet his father on a battlefield. She kept the secret. She told him his father was a noble who had died young. She did not show him the onyx armband; she kept it locked in a chest.",
        "Sohrab, however, was not a fool. He had seen his own size. He had seen his own strength. He demanded, when he was sixteen, the truth.",
        "She gave him the truth. She gave him, also, the armband.",
        "He fastened it on his arm. He resolved to lead an army against Persia, to find his father, to put his father on the throne of both kingdoms — for he had decided he would conquer them both — and to rule with him.",
        "He raised an army. He marched.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The Shah of Persia, hearing that a young giant from Turan was coming with an army, called for Rostam. Rostam came.",
        "On the borderlands the two armies camped opposite each other. Sohrab, walking through the Persian camp at night in disguise, had been searching for Rostam — to recognize him, to embrace him, to end the war before it began. He had not found him. He could not find him because Rostam was not in his usual tent — Rostam had gone hunting, having heard there would be no battle that day.",
        "In the morning the herald rode out from the Turanian camp. The herald announced: \"Sohrab of Turan challenges any Persian champion to single combat. The winner takes the field. The loser dies.\"",
        "Rostam, returning from his hunt, accepted the challenge. He did not know the boy. He had no reason to.",
        "They met on the open plain. Sohrab, looking at Rostam, felt — though he did not know why — a strange small flicker in his chest. He had a sudden urge to ask the man's name. He said, in the moment before the first blow: \"Champion. Tell me your name. There is something in your bearing — \"",
        "Rostam, who had been told by the Shah not to reveal his identity (lest the Turanians realize they were facing the great Rostam and panic into a different attack), said only: \"I am a soldier of Persia. My name is not your business. Fight.\"",
        "They fought. They fought all morning. Neither could overcome the other. They fought all afternoon. Their swords broke. They wrestled. They were equally matched. At dusk they parted, agreeing to resume in the morning.",
        "That night Sohrab said to his lieutenants: \"This is a great warrior. He may be Rostam himself. I felt it. Tomorrow I will press him for his name.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "In the morning they met again. They wrestled. The day grew long. Rostam, fearful of losing — for the boy was very strong — at last threw the boy to the ground and pinned him. He drew a dagger.",
        "Sohrab, on his back, looked up. He said, gasping: \"Strike then. But know this — when I am dead and my mother hears, she will weep. And my father, who is somewhere in your army, who is the great Rostam — he will hunt you down, when he learns you killed his son.\"",
        "Rostam's hand, holding the dagger, paused.",
        "He said: \"What did you say?\"",
        "Sohrab, with the strange flicker again: \"My father is Rostam. I came to find him. I wear his armband. Look at my arm.\"",
        "Rostam, with a hand that had begun to shake, pulled back the boy's sleeve. He saw the onyx armband — the very armband he had given Tahmineh on a single morning sixteen years before.",
        "The dagger fell from his hand into the dust. He cried out. He cried out a sound that would be remembered in Persian poetry for a thousand years.",
        "It was, however, too late. He had already, before pinning him, struck a wound. The wound was mortal. The blood was running down the boy's side onto the sand. He had moments.",
        "Rostam knelt. He gathered the boy in his arms. He wept. He said his son's name. He said his son's mother's name. He said all the names he had not gotten to say in the boy's life and was now saying at the end of it. The boy, looking up, was — for one strange terrible moment — at peace. He had found his father. He died in his father's arms a few minutes later.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The father who could not learn his son's name in time has the rest of his life to learn it. The greatest hero of a country is also a man who killed his own boy on a plain because he would not say his name when asked." },
        "Rostam carried Sohrab's body home. He did not lead any more wars. He buried his son in his own family's tomb. He sent the body back to Tahmineh's country with a letter — a letter so brief it could be read in a moment, and so full it could be wept over for the rest of a life. He lived for many years afterward in his castle, in a kind of quiet that was not exactly remorse and was not exactly grief, but was, in the words of the Persian poet who set this story down, \"the long heaviness of a man who has met his own son too late.\""
    ]
},

{
    id: "jamshid-cup",
    title: "Jamshid's Cup",
    subtitle: "How a king saw all the seven climes in a small bowl, and lost what the cup had shown him",
    civilization: "persian",
    themes: ["Kingship", "Vision", "Pride", "Fall"],
    content: [
        "Jamshid was the fourth king of the world in the Persian count of kings. He came to the throne in the long age before the prophets. He inherited a small kingdom from his father. By the end of his reign the kingdom had grown to encompass the whole earth — for Jamshid was, by every measure, a great king.",
        "He divided his people into four classes — the priests, the warriors, the farmers, the artisans — and he gave each class its proper occupation, and the classes did not quarrel. He taught his people how to weave fine cloth. He taught them how to make weapons of metal. He taught them how to extract perfume from flowers. He taught them how to build ships. He taught them medicine. He drove out the demons that had been bothering the borders of his country. He made roads. He set up the calendars.",
        "And among the treasures of his court was a small cup. The cup was made of clear crystal. It was perhaps the size of a man's two cupped hands. The cup, when it was empty, would on certain occasions show — to the eye of the king who held it — a small swirl of color, and in the colors a vision. The vision was of any place in the world. The seven climes — the seven great lands of the earth — could be seen in the cup. Jamshid would lift the cup, look in, and see what was happening at any border, in any province, in any market. He could rule with information no other king had ever possessed. The cup was called Jam-i Jam, the Cup of Jamshid.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He ruled for three hundred years.",
        "In the first hundred years he ruled with the cup as a ruler should rule with a window into his country: he saw where the harvest was poor and sent grain. He saw where the river was about to flood and ordered the dikes built. He saw where a band of robbers was beginning to gather and sent soldiers before the band had grown large. The kingdom flourished. The people prospered.",
        "In the second hundred years he ruled with the cup as a slightly bored ruler. He had begun to use it for entertainment. He would look in to see what was happening at a banquet at a far governor's house. He would look in to see whether a particular general was being faithful to a particular wife. He learned things he should not have learned. He used the cup as a king who has run out of difficult problems uses any toy.",
        "In the third hundred years he made his great mistake. He had begun, by then, to think that the cup was an instrument of his own greatness rather than a gift placed in his hand by older powers. He summoned a great court. He held up the cup. He said, in front of the assembled nobles of the world: \"There is no god above me. The world is in my hand. I see all of it. I rule all of it. I have made it. Worship me as the maker.\"",
        "The light in the cup, at that moment, went out.",
        "He did not notice at first. He went on with his speech. He commanded, before dismissing the court, that all the priests of all the religions should now redirect their offerings to him.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The world began to fall apart very quickly.",
        "It did not fall apart visibly at first. There was a small drought in one province. Then a small disease in another. Then a small rebellion. Then an earthquake. Then a famine. The cup, when Jamshid lifted it, no longer showed him anything. He could not see the seven climes. He could see only the inside of his own crystal cup, empty, beautiful, useless.",
        "He sent armies to put down the rebellions. The armies were defeated. He sent food to the famines. The food spoiled on the road. Every measure he took did not work. He had had, for three hundred years, an information advantage that was now gone.",
        "And from the south came a terrible king. His name was Zahhak. Zahhak had two snakes growing out of his shoulders, the result of a kiss from a demon, and the snakes had to be fed every day on the brains of two young men, and Zahhak had been gathering an army to march on Persia for years, and Jamshid had — in his vain and bored phase — failed to see Zahhak coming, because the cup had been turned to less serious matters.",
        "Zahhak invaded. The Persian army, demoralized, scattered. Jamshid fled. He fled across the seven climes he had once been able to see in his crystal cup. He fled for a hundred years — for he was still a king of the older line and his life was very long — but Zahhak's hunters pursued him.",
        "They caught him at last in a remote province. They killed him. They sawed his body in half with a fishbone saw — for that was the only saw that was sharp enough for the body of a long-lived king — and the cup was lost in the looting of his palace.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Zahhak ruled the world for a thousand years afterward. He was a tyrant. The two snakes on his shoulders ate two young men a day, every day, for that millennium, and the population was thinned, and the kingdom suffered. The cup of Jamshid was, all that time, lost — buried, perhaps, in a treasury, perhaps stolen, perhaps melted down by an invader who did not know what it was. The seven climes were unwatched.",
        "At last a smith rose up against Zahhak. His name was Kaveh, and his sons had been eaten by the snakes, and he tied his blacksmith's apron to a spear as a flag and led the people in revolt. Zahhak was defeated. He was chained for the rest of time inside a mountain. The kingdom was restored. But the cup did not come back. Search parties were sent. Holy men were consulted. The cup, the consensus eventually was, would not be returned to the world until a king arose who would not misuse it.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Whoever has been given a cup that shows the seven climes should remember whose cup it is. The moment they begin to take credit for the view, the view goes out. Pride is the only veil the cup will not see through." },
        "The Cup of Jamshid has appeared in Persian poetry ever since as a metaphor — as the metaphor for the inner sight of the wise person, for the heart that has been polished enough to reflect the world, for the soul that has finally learned what its eye is for. The poet Hafez, fifteen hundred years after Jamshid's death, was still writing about it. \"For years,\" he wrote, \"I sought the cup of Jamshid from those who had it. What was within me, I was demanding from elsewhere.\" He had figured out, at last, where the cup had been all along — and that is the answer the storytellers, since Hafez, have agreed on, and the search-parties for the literal cup have, since then, mostly given up."
    ]
}
);

