window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "maui-fishing",
    title: "Maui Fishes Up the Islands",
    subtitle: "How a small trickster, with his grandmother's jaw for a hook, pulled up the land",
    civilization: "polynesian",
    themes: ["Trickster", "Brothers", "Patience", "Land"],
    content: [
        "Maui was the smallest of his brothers and the youngest. There were five of them in the household. The other four were tall, broad, good-looking fishermen who had inherited the family canoe and the family nets and the family routes around the offshore reefs. Maui was small. Maui was clever. Maui's mother had given birth to him prematurely and had wrapped him in a topknot of her own hair and set him adrift on the sea, expecting him to drift to a death no one would have to be embarrassed about. He had not died. He had been raised by his grandmother in the underworld for a season, and he had come back. His brothers had not been entirely happy about this.",
        "His brothers, when they went fishing, would not take him. They said he was too small. They said he would tip the canoe. They said his magical reputation would frighten the fish. They left at dawn each day without him, and they came back at dusk with their catch.",
        "Maui worked, in the meantime, on a fishhook. He went to his grandmother — who had remained close to him after the underworld interlude — and he said: \"Grandmother. Give me your jawbone.\"",
        "She said: \"My jawbone is in my face, child. I am still using it.\"",
        "He said: \"Grandmother. Please.\"",
        "She considered. She had loved this small grandson since the day she had pulled him out of the surf in his hair-bundle. She removed her own lower jawbone — for she was a goddess of the underworld, and she could do this — and gave it to him. She continued speaking afterward in a slightly altered voice; nothing of consequence had been lost.",
        "Maui carved the jawbone into a great fishhook. He bound it with magical cord. He hid it under his loincloth.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The next morning, before dawn, he climbed into the bottom of his brothers' canoe and lay flat under a folded sail.",
        "His brothers came down at dawn. They pushed off. They paddled out beyond the reef. They began to fish. They were, by midmorning, well out of sight of land. Maui, in the bottom of the canoe, sat up.",
        "His brothers were furious. They had told him not to come. They threatened to throw him overboard. He apologized in the calm reasonable voice of someone who has gotten his way. He helped them paddle further out.",
        "By noon they were further out than any fisherman of their village had ever been. The sea was deep and dark blue. The horizon was empty.",
        "Maui produced his hook. His brothers laughed. \"That is no fishing hook,\" they said. \"That is a curiosity. Where is your bait?\"",
        "He had no bait. He thought a moment. He punched himself in the nose. The blood ran. He wiped the blood onto the hook. He cast the hook.",
        "The hook sank. It sank for a long time. The line played out, and out, and out. The brothers watched, half-curious. The hook caught at last on something far below. The line went taut.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Maui began to pull.",
        "He pulled with his arms. The canoe began to tilt. He pulled with his back. The canoe rose at the bow as if rising up a wave. He pulled with his legs. The canoe groaned. The brothers, alarmed, took up their paddles to balance.",
        "Maui said, in a strained voice through his teeth: \"Help me pull. Whatever you do — do not look behind. Do not look at what is rising. Pull.\"",
        "His brothers, taking the line in their hands, pulled. The line was hot. The line vibrated. The sea around them began to churn.",
        "And out of the deep — slowly, with a long groaning of stone against water — a great mass began to rise. It rose at the back of the canoe, behind them, where Maui had told them not to look. The mass was gray. The mass was vast. It was the floor of the ocean, lifted in one piece on the great hook.",
        "It rose into the air. The air around it filled with white spray and falling fish and small startled crabs. It became, as it rose, an island. It rose to its full height. The island stood there, dripping, in the open sea.",
        "And one of Maui's brothers — the youngest of the four, the most curious — turned his head and looked.",
        "The island, in the moment of being looked at, broke into pieces. It cracked along long fault lines. It split into many smaller islands. The mountains separated. The valleys became sea-channels. The single great mass that Maui had been pulling — what would have been one continuous land — became, instead, the long broken archipelago of every Polynesian island, scattered across a wide sea.",
        "Maui let go of the line. He sat down in the bottom of the canoe. He sighed. He looked at his brothers. He did not need to say it. They understood.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The single continent the small trickster was pulling up by his nose-blood and his grandmother's jaw was broken into a thousand islands by the impatience of one curious eye. We have been sailing between those pieces ever since." },
        "The Polynesian peoples, sailing in their long canoes from one of those islands to the next over many centuries, knew which island was Maui's first hooking. They sang about it on the long voyages. The hook itself, the storytellers say, became a constellation — the curve of stars now called by Western astronomers Scorpius is, by the Polynesians, the great fishhook of Maui, hanging in the sky as a permanent souvenir of the morning the floor of the sea came up. Look up at it on a clear southern night. The hook is still there, still bright, still slightly bent at the place where it strained."
    ]
},

{
    id: "pele",
    title: "Pele's Wrath",
    subtitle: "The fire-goddess who walks her sister's island in a stranger's clothes",
    civilization: "polynesian",
    themes: ["Volcano", "Sisters", "Hospitality", "Fire"],
    content: [
        "Pele is the goddess of the volcano. She lives, by long preference, in the crater of Halemaumau on the island of Hawaii. The crater steams. The lava in it glows and shifts. She has been there for a long time. The Hawaiian people speak of her with the careful courtesy a sensible person uses around any creature whose arrival is the arrival of moving stone.",
        "She came to Hawaii from Tahiti — many centuries ago, by the people's reckoning — driven out by her older sister Namakaokahai, the goddess of the sea. The two of them had quarreled about a husband, the way sisters in many old stories quarrel about a husband. Pele had taken him; Namaka had pursued her. Pele had fled across the sea, island to island, and at every island she had tried to make a home, Namaka had washed in behind her with a great wave and unmade it. Pele had finally arrived at the high volcanic island of Hawaii, and she had dug a crater so deep that her sister's sea could not reach the bottom of it, and she had settled.",
        "She was, the people said, beautiful when she chose to be. She had black hair the length of her body. Her eyes were dark and a little smouldering. When she walked among the villages — for she sometimes did — she wore the simple skirt of any Hawaiian woman. There was nothing in her appearance that announced her name.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "It is told that an old woman came down a mountain road one evening, walking slowly, leaning on a staff. Her hair was white. Her face was creased. She wore a tattered red skirt. She came to a village. She stopped at the first house she came to. She knocked.",
        "The man who opened the door looked at her. He was eating his evening meal. He had a roast pig on his table. He said: \"What do you want, old woman?\"",
        "\"A small piece of pork,\" she said. \"I have walked a long way today. I am hungry.\"",
        "He laughed shortly. \"There is no pork here for beggars. Move on.\"",
        "He shut the door.",
        "She walked on through the village. At every house she stopped. At every house she was refused. The villagers were rich. The pigs had been roasted in the festival earlier that day. There was plenty of pork. None of them gave her any.",
        "She walked through the village and out the other side. She was tired. She came to the last house — a small thatched hut at the edge of the lava field — and she knocked there too.",
        "The woman who opened the door was poor. She had only a small fish on her table — half a fish, in fact, since her child had eaten the other half. She looked at the old woman in the tattered red skirt.",
        "\"Come in, mother,\" she said. \"There is half a fish. Sit.\"",
        "The old woman came in. She was given the half fish. She ate. She thanked the poor woman. She rose to leave. The poor woman, embarrassed at having had only the small fish to offer, pressed into the old woman's hand a small wreath of dried leaves she had been making.",
        "The old woman accepted the wreath. She paused at the door. She turned. \"Daughter,\" she said gently. \"In two days. Come up the mountain road on the western side. Bring nothing. Bring only your child. Walk early. Be at the high meadow by sunrise. Do not look back.\"",
        "The poor woman, frightened, agreed. The old woman walked off into the dusk.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Two mornings later the poor woman, with her child on her hip, walked up the mountain road on the western side. She was at the high meadow by sunrise.",
        "Behind her, in the village, she heard the first of the rumblings. The mountain shook. The crater of Halemaumau, which had been quiet for years, opened.",
        "A great wall of lava began to flow down. It came in slow steady arms — bright orange, then deep red, then black where it began to cool — and it covered the village. Every house. Every byre. Every roasted pig in every kitchen. The villagers, fleeing, did not all make it. The lava was patient and it was thorough and it took everything.",
        "The poor woman, in the high meadow, stood with her child. The lava, when it reached her ridge, parted. It went around her in two streams and met again on the far side, and the meadow was untouched.",
        "She watched her village disappear under the slow tide of fire. She wept. But she had been spared. And the old woman in the red skirt — Pele, of course it had been Pele — had repaid her hospitality with the only currency a volcano-goddess ever has, which is the difference between being inside the lava-flow and being outside it.",
        { style: "quote", text: "There are gods who walk in the rags of old women looking for the small pork at the side of the road. The houses that turn them away are the houses the lava reaches. The houses that give half a fish are the houses the meadow keeps." },
        "The Hawaiian people have, ever since, been careful with travelers. They have been particularly careful with old women. The pork is offered. The half fish is offered. Pele still walks, in the storytellers' accounts, in the same red skirt — sometimes as an old woman, sometimes as a young one, sometimes with a small white dog at her heels — and the visitor who turns her away does so at a real cost, and the visitor who feeds her does so to a real return. The lava field around her crater is full of small graves of villages that did not believe this. The high meadows around the same crater are full of small farms that did."
    ]
},

{
    id: "hina-eel",
    title: "Hina and the Eel",
    subtitle: "How the coconut tree grew, and what its three eyes remember",
    civilization: "polynesian",
    themes: ["Love", "Gift", "Transformation", "Coconut"],
    content: [
        "Hina was a young woman who lived by a stream on the island of Savai'i. Each morning she went down to the stream to bathe. The stream was cool and clear and the small fish ran around her ankles, and she would sit afterward on a rock and let the sun dry her hair, and the mornings were her own.",
        "There was an eel in the stream. He was longer than she was tall. He had been there for years before she had begun to bathe; he had observed her since she was a small girl. He had grown used to her. He had begun, in the way of certain water-creatures with the long quiet stories of their kind, to love her.",
        "He took, eventually, a man's form. He came up out of the water one morning as a tall handsome young man with skin the color of wet stone. He stood on the bank. He greeted her. He told her, with the courtesy of a being who had been preparing the speech for years, that he loved her and would like to court her.",
        "Hina was startled but not afraid. She had grown up with stories about creatures of this kind. She liked his face. She agreed.",
        "They walked together along the bank. He was charming. He was also, Hina noticed slowly, a little too still — when he stopped walking he stood with the stillness of an eel under a rock, and his eyes did not blink quite at the rate a person's would. But he was kind. They walked for many afternoons.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He was, in the end, an eel. He had a body that was not finally a man's body. He had also, in the way of the older eel-people, a certain limit to what he could imitate. He came one night to her house. He proposed marriage. She refused — gently, but she refused.",
        "He went back to the stream. He grew sad. He grew angry. He grew, by slow underwater degrees, dangerous.",
        "Some weeks later, when Hina went down to bathe, the eel came up out of the water in his eel-form — full size, longer than she was tall — and he wound around her legs, and he would not let her out of the stream. He was no longer asking. He was holding her against her will.",
        "She cried out. The cry carried up the path. Maui — yes, the same Maui from the long fishing story; the islands have only a few major figures and they walk through several stories — was passing on the road and heard her. He came running with his great shark-toothed club. He waded into the stream. He struck the eel one mighty blow. The eel's head was severed from its body in a single moment.",
        "The eel's head fell to the bank.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Hina, freed, stood shaking on the rock. Maui took up the head to throw it into the deep water. Before he could throw it, the eel — dying, his old man's voice coming weakly out of the eel-mouth — spoke.",
        "\"Hina,\" he said. \"Hina. I am sorry. I should not have done this. Listen — take my head with you. Plant it. Plant it deep. The thing that grows out of it will be a tree no other tree resembles. Its fruit will feed your people. Its juice will refresh them. Its meat will keep them alive on long voyages. Its leaves will roof their houses. Its trunk will become the keels of their canoes. Take this gift from me, in apology, and so I will not have died for nothing.\"",
        "He died. The voice stopped.",
        "Hina considered. She had been hurt; she had been frightened. But she could see, in the dying eyes of the eel, the eyes of the young man who had walked beside her on the afternoons. She could not refuse the gift.",
        "She took the head. She walked it to a high spot above the village. She dug a deep hole. She planted the head, eyes upward.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "From the head grew a tree.",
        "It was a tree no one in the village had seen. It grew tall and straight. It had a single tuft of long pinnate leaves at the top. After some years it began to bear large round fruit at the crown — fruit the size of a man's two fists, brown, fibrous on the outside, hard on the inside, with a sweet white meat and a clear sweet liquid in the inner cavity.",
        "The fruit had three small dark spots on the base of its inner shell — three small round eyes, set in a triangle. The first time the villagers cracked one open, an old woman who had been there on the morning of the eel pointed at the three spots silently and the others understood.",
        "The three spots were the eel's eyes. Two side by side and one above. The mouth, looking up at you, of the head you had planted.",
        "The villagers did not stop eating the coconut. The coconut was too useful. But every Polynesian people, ever since, has known what they were eating. The face on the bottom of every coconut is the face of the eel-man whose love had been refused, whose head had been struck off by Maui, and who in his last moment had given, by way of apology, the most useful tree the islands would ever know.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Whoever has loved badly enough to die for it can sometimes be redeemed by the gift they leave. The fruit at the top of the long bare trunk has a face we should not, when we drink from it, forget to acknowledge." },
        "Hina herself, in some versions of the story, climbed into the moon afterward, the way Chang'e did, and lives there still — beating tapa cloth against a rock, the rhythmic sound of her beater being the soft sound the moon sometimes makes against a quiet sea. The coconut tree was the gift she left behind. The gift was acknowledged. The story is still told. The face is still on the fruit."
    ]
}
);

