window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "sedna",
    title: "Sedna, Mistress of the Sea",
    subtitle: "Of the woman whose father cut off her fingers, and what each finger became",
    civilization: "inuit",
    themes: ["Sea", "Father & daughter", "Sacrifice", "Animals"],
    content: [
        "Sedna was the daughter of a hunter. They lived together in a small skin tent on the edge of the great northern sea. Her mother had died when she was small. She kept her father's house. She was beautiful. Many young men had come from many villages to ask for her in marriage, and she had refused all of them. She had not given a reason.",
        "One spring a stranger came across the ice. He was tall. He wore a fine fur cloak. His face was hidden in the hood. He spoke softly. He offered her, if she would come away with him, a tent of the softest skins, and as much meat as she could eat, and a soft warm bed.",
        "Sedna, who had refused everyone else, somehow agreed. She did not afterward remember why. There had been a quality in his voice that had unmoored her judgment. She packed her small bundle. She went with him across the ice to his canoe. They paddled away.",
        "He paddled her to a small distant island. He brought her to his tent. The tent was not soft skins. It was made of fish-bones, lashed together, smelling of old fish. The bed was a hard pile of rotting weeds. The food was raw fish. Her husband, when he removed his hood, was not a man at all but a great fulmar — a sea-bird with a long ugly beak — and his fine cloak had been a clever weaving of feathers, and his soft voice had been a trick.",
        "She had been lured. She wept. She lived on the island for a long time, eating what the bird-husband brought her, sleeping on the rotting weeds, watching the horizon for a sail.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Her father, after a year, came in his canoe to find her. He had been searching all the islands of the cold northern sea. He pulled up on the beach. He found her in the bone tent. She wept. He hid her under the skins in the bottom of his canoe and pushed off.",
        "They paddled hard. They were a good way out when the bird-husband came home. He saw the canoe in the distance. He flew up. He raised a storm.",
        "The storm was enormous. The waves rose to the height of a small mountain. The canoe began to swamp. The father, terrified — for his canoe could not survive the storm with two people in it — made a decision.",
        "He pushed Sedna over the side.",
        "She caught the gunwale with her hands. She held on. She begged him to pull her back in. He did not. He took his knife. He cut off the first joint of her fingers — the small joint at the tip of each finger — and the small joints fell into the sea and her grip weakened. She still hung on.",
        "He cut the second joints. The second joints fell. Her grip weakened more. She still hung on.",
        "He cut the third joints — the joints at the knuckle. The joints fell. Her hands were now stumps. She could not hold. She slipped backward off the canoe and into the cold sea.",
        "She sank.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "She sank and she sank. She sank to the bottom of the cold sea. She did not die — for she was a woman with the long anger of a woman who had been betrayed first by a husband and then by a father, and the long anger sustained her — and she settled on the floor of the deepest part of the ocean. She found, there, that she could breathe water. She had become, by the slow drowning, a goddess.",
        "The joints of her fingers, falling earlier through the water, had become, by the time they reached the bottom, the animals of the sea. The first joints had become the fish — small, bright, swift. The second joints had become the seals — sleek, dark-eyed, intelligent. The third joints had become the great whales — slow, dark, immense.",
        "She had become, by the loss of her hands, the mother of every creature that swam.",
        "She built a hall on the floor of the sea. She lived there. She was, after a while, dignified. She combed her long black hair with the stumps of her hands — slowly, painfully, for she had no fingers to braid with — and the combing was difficult, and her hair grew tangled, and the tangles in her hair had a consequence.",
        "When her hair was tangled she would, in her irritation, withhold her animals. The seals would not come close to the surface. The whales would dive deep and not come up. The fish would scatter. The Inuit hunters above, on the sea-ice, would catch nothing. Their families would starve.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "When the catch failed for too long the people would call for an angakkuq — a shaman — and the shaman would go down. The shaman would prepare for many days. He would fast. He would chant. He would, at last, send his soul down through the sea. He would arrive in Sedna's hall.",
        "He would find her with her hair in long matted tangles, and her face turned away.",
        "He would sit down beside her. He would, gently, with his soul-fingers, comb her hair. He would untangle it strand by strand. He would talk to her quietly while he worked. He would tell her the news of the surface. He would apologize, on behalf of every hunter who had recently been careless with the animals — for she insisted on certain rituals being kept; the seal's bladder returned to the sea, the whale's bones placed in a particular order, the small offerings made — and the shaman would acknowledge, on the people's behalf, the carelessnesses, and would promise reform.",
        "When her hair was smooth and she had heard the apology, she would turn her face. She would release the animals. The seals would come back to the surface. The whales would rise. The hunt would succeed. The people would eat.",
        "This pattern has gone on for centuries.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The mother of the animals had her fingers cut off by her own father in a storm and was given, in compensation, the entire sea. She is still combing her hair. The catch will come if you have remembered to apologize for the small carelessnesses." },
        "There are still angakkuit in some Inuit communities — though fewer than there were — who go down in vision to comb Sedna's hair. There are still hunters who throw the bladder back, who arrange the bones, who whisper the small thank-yous. The gestures look small. They are not small. The mother of the sea is still in her hall, and she is still grieving the morning of her father's knife, and the only currency she will accept from the people above is the slow patient comb of an apology."
    ]
},

{
    id: "raven-light",
    title: "How Raven Stole the Light",
    subtitle: "Of the trickster who became a pine needle to slip into a chief's house and take back the sun",
    civilization: "inuit",
    themes: ["Trickster", "Light", "Disguise", "Gift"],
    content: [
        "In the very beginning the world was dark. It had been dark since there had been a world. The people stumbled around. They could not see each other. They could not see the country. They tripped over rocks. They walked off cliffs. They argued in the dark and could not see whose face they were arguing with.",
        "Light existed. The light had been gathered by a great chief at the head of a long fjord, who lived in a long plank house with his daughter. He had three boxes. The largest box held the sun. The middle box held the moon. The smallest box held the stars. He kept the boxes in the back of his house. He did not let any light out. He had hoarded it, in the way certain old chiefs hoard wealth, and the country he had taken it from had been in the dark for as long as he had had the boxes.",
        "Raven, who flew over the world, had grown tired of the dark. He could not, for that matter, see his own black feathers in the dark, and what is the use of having been made beautiful if you cannot occasionally enjoy yourself in a small mirror of light? He decided to take the light back.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He flew to the long fjord. He landed in a small fir tree near the chief's spring. He observed.",
        "The chief's daughter was a young woman of perhaps eighteen. She came down to the spring every morning to fetch water. She walked alone. She was beautiful in a quiet way. The chief loved her dearly.",
        "Raven thought a long time. He flew up onto a higher branch of the fir tree. He plucked a single small needle from the tip of a twig. He dropped the needle.",
        "The needle fell into the spring. It floated on the water — small, green, almost invisible.",
        "The next morning the chief's daughter came down. She bent to fill her bucket. She did not see the small needle floating. She drank a deep cup of the water. The needle went down with the cup, into her stomach.",
        "Months later — for these things take time — she gave birth to a small dark-haired baby boy.",
        "The chief, surprised but delighted, claimed the boy as his grandson. He had not had a grandson. He doted on the child.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The boy grew. He grew very fast — for he was Raven, in the boy's body, and Raven was an impatient creature. By two he was walking. By three he was talking. By four he was a small boy with bright dark eyes who had begun, the chief noticed, to develop strange interests.",
        "He had, in particular, become fascinated by the three boxes in the back of the house. He kept asking to see them. The chief, who had a soft spot, eventually gave in.",
        "He let the boy hold the smallest box. The boy turned it in his hands. He looked at the chief with very wide pleading eyes. \"Grandfather,\" he said, \"may I take it outside? Just for a moment? I want to see what is in it under the sky.\"",
        "The chief, who could refuse the boy nothing, said yes. The boy carried the box outside. He stood on the bank of the fjord. He opened the lid.",
        "The stars came out. They flew out of the box in a great silver flock. They spread across the dark sky in their constellations. They have stayed there ever since.",
        "The chief came out and saw what the boy had done and was, for a moment, furious. But the stars were beautiful — even he could see they were beautiful — and he could not bear to be cross with the small boy. He let it pass.",
        "Some weeks later the boy asked for the middle box. The chief, more careful this time, hesitated. The boy looked at him with the same pleading eyes. \"Just for a moment, grandfather. I want to see it under the sky.\"",
        "The chief gave in. The boy carried the box outside. He opened the lid. The moon rose out of the box and floated up into the night sky. It hung there, full and pale, looking down. It has stayed there ever since.",
        "The chief, this time, was angrier. But the moon was also beautiful. He let it pass.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Then the boy asked for the largest box. The chief refused. \"You have had the stars and you have had the moon,\" he said. \"You will not have the sun.\"",
        "The boy wept. The boy refused to eat. The boy lay on the floor and would not get up. He wept for three days. The chief, after three days, broke. He could not bear to see his grandson in such grief. He fetched the largest box.",
        "The boy took it in his small arms. He walked toward the door. The chief followed him.",
        "At the threshold the boy did not stop. He stepped outside. He shifted his shape — and where the small dark-haired boy had been there was suddenly a large black bird with the box in his beak.",
        "The chief shouted. The chief reached. Raven flew up. He flew up out of the long house and out of the fjord. The chief stood weeping in the doorway. He had been outwitted. He understood what he had been raising for four years.",
        "Raven flew up into the sky with the largest box in his beak. At a high altitude he set the box down on the air and opened it.",
        "The sun came out.",
        "It rose. It hung in the sky. The world below was bathed in light for the first time. The people, who had been stumbling in the dark, looked up. They saw each other for the first time. They saw the country for the first time. They saw the long fjords and the high mountains and the rivers and the trees, and they wept with the wonder of it.",
        "Raven, exhausted from the long carrying, settled on a high cliff. The sun, in its new sky, kept rising. The hours moved. The day, which had not before been a thing, became a thing. The night came afterward — for he had let the moon and stars out also, and they took the night-shift — and from then on the world had a rhythm.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The light hoarded in a back room belongs to no one. The trickster who slips in as a pine needle and is born as a grandson and weeps for three days for the largest box is doing what no army could do. The smaller the disguise, sometimes, the larger the theft." },
        "Raven kept some of the light on him afterward. His feathers, the storytellers say, used to be white. They became black on the long flight up out of the chief's house, with the sun-box in his beak — black from the heat of the box, black from the smoke of his own escape, black ever since. He paid that small price. The world was lit. The chief in the long house at the end of the fjord eventually came out, blinking, into the new day, and even he had to admit that the world looked better this way."
    ]
}
);

