window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "hanuman",
    title: "Hanuman's Leap",
    subtitle: "How the monkey-god jumped the strait to Lanka and brought back the herb of life",
    civilization: "hindu",
    themes: ["Devotion", "Strength", "Mountain", "Service"],
    content: [
        "Rama was the prince of Ayodhya, exiled to the forest by an old promise his father had given a long time ago. His wife Sita was with him. His brother Lakshmana was with him. They lived in a small hut in the forest of Panchavati. The forest had its difficulties. The forest had also its beauty. Sita gathered flowers in the morning. Rama hunted. Lakshmana kept watch.",
        "On a particular morning a golden deer appeared in the clearing in front of the hut. Sita had never seen anything so beautiful. She begged Rama to catch it for her. Rama, suspicious — for he had been told to be wary of beautiful things in the forest — went anyway, because he could not refuse Sita. The deer led him a long way away. He understood, too late, that the deer was an illusion. He shot it. The illusion died screaming for help in Rama's voice.",
        "Lakshmana, hearing the cry, ran toward it. Sita, alone in the hut, was abducted. The demon-king Ravana of Lanka had laid the trick — he had wanted Sita for himself for some time — and he carried her off in his great flying chariot, south over the strait, to his island fortress.",
        "Rama and Lakshmana, returning to the empty hut, understood at once. They began the long pursuit south.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "On the road they made allies. The most important ally was Hanuman.",
        "Hanuman was a monkey. Or — he was a being in the shape of a monkey. He was the son of the wind-god Vayu, and he had as a child mistaken the sun for a piece of fruit and tried to eat it. He had been struck down by Indra for the impertinence and had been somewhat humbled, but he had retained the strength and the speed and the cheerfulness of his lineage. He was a chief of the monkey kingdom of Kishkindha. He met Rama on the road. He bowed. He pledged his service.",
        "He served Rama with the kind of devotion that other beings spend lives trying to learn. He was tireless. He was cheerful. He was, in his way, the perfect servant — not because he had no will of his own, but because his will and Rama's had, by the moment of meeting, simply aligned.",
        "When the army of monkeys reached the southern shore and saw the strait that lay between them and Lanka, they were daunted. The strait was wide. None of them, except possibly Hanuman, could cross it.",
        "Hanuman stepped to the cliff. He took a long breath. He grew. He grew until he was the size of a small mountain. He bunched himself. He leaped.",
        "He leaped across the strait in a single bound. He passed over the water with the wind of his passing flattening waves below. He passed mountains that rose, in his way, to challenge him — for some of the older mountains in the strait still had a mind — and he greeted them politely and went over the top of them. He was met by sea-monsters who tried to swallow him; he passed straight through their open mouths and out the other side, leaving them confused. He landed on Lanka.",
        "He shrank. He took the small form of an ordinary monkey. He went into the city.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He found Sita in the garden of the palace, under a tree where Ravana had been keeping her. He spoke to her. He gave her Rama's ring as proof of his identity. He promised that the army would come.",
        "He was, however, captured on his way out — for he had decided, in his cheerful way, to do a small additional thing while in Lanka, which was to set the city on fire. He had set his tail on fire (the demons had set it for him, hoping to humiliate him) and had then run across the rooftops, lighting them as he went. The city of Lanka burned. Ravana himself stood on his terrace and watched his capital burn, and Hanuman, having lit it, leaped back across the strait to the army on the far shore and reported.",
        "The army crossed the strait — slowly, on a long bridge of stones the monkeys built across the gap — and the great war for Lanka began. It lasted many days. Many monkeys died. Many demons died. Lakshmana, in the thick of one battle, was struck by a poisoned arrow and fell, and could not be roused, and would die by sunrise unless a particular medicinal herb was applied to the wound.",
        "The herb grew only on a single mountain in the high Himalayas, far in the north. There was no time to send a runner. The army's healer turned to Hanuman.",
        "\"Bring it,\" she said. \"The mountain is called Dronagiri. The herb has four kinds — sanjivani, vishalyakarani, savarnyakarani, sandhani. They glow in the dark. You will know them. Hurry.\"",
        "Hanuman grew again. He leaped north. He covered, in a single long arc, the distance from the southern strait to the high northern mountains. He landed on the slopes of Dronagiri.",
        "He looked at the mountainside in the moonlight. There were many herbs growing there. Many of them looked similar. He could not tell which was the sanjivani. He had not been told the leaf-pattern in detail.",
        "He thought a moment. Then he simply uprooted the entire mountain.",
        "He held the mountain over his head — the entire peak, the entire summit, with all the herbs growing on it — and he leaped back south. He flew through the night sky carrying a mountain. The peasants below, looking up, saw the unprecedented silhouette of a flying monkey-god holding an entire mountain peak above his head, and they did not know what they were seeing, and they would not believe it, except that the same observation was made in many villages along the route.",
        "He landed on the southern shore. The healer ran out. She found the four herbs. She applied them. Lakshmana woke. Hanuman, satisfied, carried the mountain back north to put it where it had been, and apologized politely to the local gods of that range for the brief disturbance.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The servant who, when asked for an herb, brings the entire mountain has not done too much. He has done what was required, when the time was short and the herb was uncertain. The mountain can be returned afterward. The brother cannot be revived twice." },
        "Hanuman is, in some Hindu households, the most beloved of all the gods. There are temples to him in many cities. He is the patron of wrestlers. He is the patron of devotees. He is the patron of anyone whose work involves carrying something larger than themselves on someone else's behalf. The image of him uprooting the mountain is reproduced in painting and stone all across India, and the small statues of him with the mountain over his head sit on many home altars, where the householders see him every morning and remember whose service is the highest service."
    ]
},

{
    id: "shiva-tandava",
    title: "Shiva's Tandava",
    subtitle: "The dance that destroys and remakes the cosmos",
    civilization: "hindu",
    themes: ["Dance", "Destruction", "Renewal", "Cosmic"],
    content: [
        "Shiva is one of the three great gods of the Hindu cosmos. Brahma creates. Vishnu preserves. Shiva destroys. The destruction is not gratuitous — it is the necessary clearing-away that lets the next age begin. Without Shiva there would be no room for Brahma to make anything new. The three gods work in a long quiet rotation, and each of their tasks is as honorable as the others.",
        "Shiva's principal instrument of destruction is his dance.",
        "The dance is called the Tandava. He performs it on a small drum. He has four arms. He carries fire in one hand. He carries the drum in another. A third hand is raised in the gesture of \"do not be afraid\" — the abhaya mudra — for even in the moment of destruction he wishes the witness to be unafraid. The fourth hand points down to his foot, which is planted on the back of a small dwarf, which is the dwarf of ignorance, and the dwarf is being kept down by the foot. The other foot is raised. The raised foot is the foot of liberation. Whoever the dance is for, that foot is for them.",
        "Shiva dances in a ring of fire. The ring is the cosmos. The fire is the energy of the cosmos. The dance is what the cosmos does, in the long run, when it is being entirely itself.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He danced once, alone, in his hall on Mount Kailash. He had been brooding. His wife Parvati had gone south to visit her sister. He had been alone for a long time. He had begun the slow brooding that a god of destruction sometimes falls into when there is nobody to bring him tea.",
        "He stood up. He took his drum. He took the fire. He began the dance.",
        "The dance was slow at first. Then it built. He turned. He stamped. The drum beat in his hand without his striking it — for the drum was a self-playing drum when his hand merely held it, as long as the dance was in motion — and the rhythm was the rhythm of his heart, and his heart was old, and the rhythm was correspondingly old.",
        "But Shiva had a particular kind of dance, and the particular kind of dance, when he did it long enough alone, did a particular kind of thing. The hall began to shake. The mountain began to shake. The ranges around the mountain began to shake. The plains below the ranges. The continents. The seas. The stars in the sky.",
        "The cosmos was being unmade. It had not happened in a long time. It was overdue, perhaps. But the gods — Brahma in his hall, Vishnu on his serpent in the cosmic ocean — felt the early signs and looked at each other in alarm. They sent messengers up to Mount Kailash. The messengers reported that Shiva was alone in his hall and was beginning the Great Tandava — the cosmos-ending dance.",
        "There was no time to argue him out of it. He could not, in any case, be argued out of it once it had begun. The Tandava is, when fully launched, a self-completing process.",
        "Brahma and Vishnu, in council, sent for Parvati. \"Come back,\" they sent. \"Come back at once. He has begun.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Parvati came. She walked into the hall. She did not, at first, do anything. She watched.",
        "Her husband was a tall blue-skinned figure spinning in the center of the hall. The drum beat. The ring of fire was around him, growing brighter. The mountain was shaking. She could see, in the drum-beat and the foot-stamping and the brilliance of the eye, that he was both her husband and not her husband — he was, in this moment, the dance itself, and the dance had no wife.",
        "She did not interrupt him. She waited.",
        "She watched the dance build. She watched it reach a particular height. She watched it pause for a single second at its summit — a small stillness in the spin, like the moment a top makes before it falls — and in that small stillness she stepped forward, gently, and she met his raised hand with hers, and she joined him.",
        "She danced.",
        "She danced opposite him. She danced as the slow soft female counterpart to the fierce destruction. She danced the Lasya — the gentle dance, the dance of creation, the dance of renewal — to his Tandava. They danced together.",
        "And the cosmos, which had been unmaking, began to remake. The shaking eased. The stars settled. The seas returned to their bowls. The mountains stopped trembling. The ring of fire around the dancing pair brightened — not in destruction now, but in the bright clean light of a new beginning. The two of them danced together in the center of the cosmos, and the cosmos turned itself out into a fresh new arrangement, and the long unmade was being made again, and the small dwarf of ignorance under Shiva's foot was, this time, shifting slightly, as if remembering that the dance is not always against him.",
        "They danced for a long time. They had been doing this for ages.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The destruction the universe needs is also the dance. The renewal the universe needs is also the dance. The two are the same dance, danced by two people, who happen to be married to each other, in the small bright ring at the center of everything." },
        "The image of Shiva Nataraja — Lord of the Dance — was cast in bronze first by the South Indian craftsmen of the Chola dynasty about a thousand years ago. It is one of the great images of world art. The four-armed dancer in his ring of fire stands in museums and on home altars all over the world. Some people who have never heard the story of Parvati's joining still feel, when they look at the image, that someone is missing from it — that the dance, alone, is too much, and that there ought to be a partner. They are sensing what the bronze does not always show: she is there, and the cosmos has been continuously remade because she came back into the hall on time."
    ]
},

{
    id: "narasimha",
    title: "Narasimha, the Man-Lion",
    subtitle: "How Vishnu kept the letter of an unbreakable promise by becoming, briefly, neither man nor beast",
    civilization: "hindu",
    themes: ["Promise", "Loophole", "Father & son", "Devotion"],
    content: [
        "Hiranyakashipu was a demon king. He had performed a long penance — many decades of standing on one foot in the forest, eating nothing — and at the end of the penance Brahma had been compelled, by the rules of such things, to grant him a boon. Hiranyakashipu had asked carefully. He had thought about it for years. He had wanted to be unkillable.",
        "He had said: \"Grant me that I cannot be killed by any creature you have made. Not by a man. Not by an animal. Not by a god. Not by a demon. Not by any weapon. Not in the daytime. Not at night. Not inside any building. Not outside, on any ground. Not in the sky. Not in the water. Not in the earth. Grant me all of these conditions and I will be satisfied.\"",
        "Brahma, who was the maker of the boons but not always the calculator of their consequences, had granted it. Hiranyakashipu, now effectively unkillable, had returned home and begun the work of being a tyrant.",
        "He conquered the upper kingdom. He drove the gods out of their hall. He installed himself on the throne of Indra. He demanded that all beings, in every world, worship him as the supreme god. Most beings, frightened, complied. The gods, who could not kill him, hid.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "But Hiranyakashipu had a son. The son's name was Prahlada.",
        "Prahlada was a quiet boy. He was thoughtful. From the time he could speak, he had been a devotee of Vishnu — the preserver, the great god. He chanted Vishnu's name in his small bedroom. He composed small hymns. He carried, in his small chest, a quiet steady devotion that could not be argued out of him.",
        "His father noticed. His father was furious. His father had banned the worship of all other gods in his kingdom. He summoned the boy. He demanded the boy chant his father's name instead of Vishnu's. The boy refused. He chanted Vishnu.",
        "Hiranyakashipu, enraged, ordered the boy killed. Servants threw the boy off a high cliff. The boy chanted Vishnu as he fell. He landed unhurt. They put him in a pit of poisonous snakes. He chanted Vishnu. The snakes did not bite him. They poured boiling oil on him. He chanted Vishnu. The oil did not burn him. They tied him to a post and his aunt Holika, who had a boon of fire-resistance, sat in his lap with a flaming brazier, intending to burn him while she sat unburnt. The boy chanted Vishnu. The aunt's boon failed for that one occasion. She burned. The boy did not.",
        "Hiranyakashipu, after every failed murder, became more enraged.",
        "At last, in the great hall, he confronted Prahlada in front of the entire court. He shouted: \"Where is your Vishnu? You speak of him constantly. Where is he? Show me. Is he in this column?\" And he struck a marble column at the side of the hall with his great mace.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The column shattered.",
        "Out of the column stepped a creature.",
        "It was not a man. It had the body of a man — broad-chested, four-armed — but the head was the head of a lion, gold-maned, with great fangs and burning eyes. It was not an animal. It walked upright on man's legs. It was Vishnu, in his fourth avatar, in the form he had chosen specifically for this moment. Narasimha. The Man-Lion. Half man, half beast — therefore neither. Therefore a creature outside the boon's exhaustive list of exclusions.",
        "Hiranyakashipu, looking at the creature, understood at once how he had been outwitted. He had specified men and animals. He had not specified the chimera between. He drew his weapon.",
        "Narasimha leaped at him.",
        "He carried the king to the threshold of the great hall. The threshold was a doorway — neither inside the building nor outside it. He sat down in the doorway. He laid Hiranyakashipu across his thighs. The thighs were not the ground; they were not the sky; they were not water. The hour was twilight. The hour was neither day nor night.",
        "He used no weapon. He had only his bare claws. The claws were not weapons in the sense the boon had specified.",
        "He tore the king's chest open.",
        "It was, in technical legal terms, a perfect satisfaction of every clause of the boon and every loophole. The boon held; the king died. Brahma, watching from above, sighed. He had not been outwitted by his own boon — he had been outwitted by the more careful god — but at the end of it, he understood that someone had been needed to outwit him, and someone had.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Narasimha, having killed the king, sat in the doorway with the body across his thighs. His eyes were still burning. His chest was still heaving. He was, in that moment, a god in the full fury of his role, and the gods around him — who had emerged from their hiding places to watch — were, frankly, terrified.",
        "Nobody could approach him. He was too hot. He was too dangerous. He sat there with the body and would not be calmed.",
        "Then Prahlada, the boy, walked up to him.",
        "Prahlada was perhaps eight years old. He had been the cause of all of this. He walked up to the man-lion in the doorway with the calm of a small child who has never doubted his god. He laid one small hand on the great lion-furred chest.",
        "Narasimha's burning eyes, looking down, saw the boy. The eyes softened. The chest stopped heaving. The roar that had been in his throat subsided.",
        "He laid down the body. He took the boy in his great arms — gently, the way a tired father takes a sleeping child — and the great wrath of Vishnu was put down for that day by the small touch of a boy who had not been afraid.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The boon of unkillability cannot stand against a god who reads contracts carefully. The fury that follows the killing cannot be calmed by any council of the great. It can be calmed only by the small hand of the believer who never doubted." },
        "Prahlada became, in time, the ruler of his father's kingdom. He ruled gently. He continued to chant Vishnu's name every morning. The image of Narasimha — the man-lion in the doorway with the king across his thighs and the boy at his side — is in temples across India and in Indonesia and in Nepal. The image is fierce. It is also, in the small detail of the boy's hand on the chest, tender. The two qualities, the storytellers say, are not in tension. They are the same single thing, seen from two different angles, in the long quiet attention of a god who came when called."
    ]
}
);

