window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "erlik-han",
    title: "Erlik Han, Lord of the Lower Country",
    subtitle: "How the dark brother shaped the first body and was sent below",
    civilization: "turkish",
    themes: ["Brothers", "Creation", "Underworld", "Imitation"],
    content: [
        "In the very beginning, before the world was made, there were only two beings: Tengri Ülgen and his younger brother Erlik. They were not yet quite gods. They were two large floating beings on the surface of an endless dark sea. Above them was nothing. Below them was the dark water. They had no business yet, because there was no world to do business in.",
        "Tengri Ülgen, who was the elder, decided to make the world. He sent Erlik down into the depths of the dark sea to fetch up some mud. Erlik went. He swam down a long way. He came back up with mud cupped in his mouth. He hid a small pinch of it in his cheek before spitting the rest into his brother's hands.",
        "Tengri Ülgen took the mud and shaped it on the surface of the water. The mud spread. It became land. It became continents and mountains and rivers. The world emerged.",
        "But the small pinch of mud Erlik had hidden in his cheek — concealed for his own purposes, in case he wanted to make something of his own later — also began to grow. It grew, awkwardly, in his cheek. He had to spit it out. When he spit it out, it fell into the water and became a separate small ugly land, full of swamps and bad things. This was the beginning of the conflict between the two brothers. Erlik had been caught secreting some of the maker's substance for himself. The relationship was, from then on, never wholly easy.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "They worked together, mostly, on the next phase. Tengri Ülgen made the first human bodies out of clay. He shaped them carefully — heads, arms, legs, hands — and laid them out on the new ground. He could not, however, give them souls. The soul had to come from above.",
        "He went up to fetch the soul-fire. He left the bodies under a single dog as a guard.",
        "Erlik came up while the elder brother was away. He looked at the rows of clay bodies. He looked at the dog.",
        "\"Dog,\" he said gently. \"You must be cold.\"",
        "The dog, who had no fur — for Tengri Ülgen had not yet given the dog its fur — was indeed cold. The wind was sharp. The dog shivered.",
        "Erlik said: \"I have a coat for you. A warm coat of soft fur. I will give it to you. Just step away from the bodies for a moment so I can fit it.\"",
        "The dog, who was simple, stepped away. Erlik gave the dog a thick coat of warm fur — which the dog kept, and which is why dogs have fur to this day — but while the dog was being measured, Erlik turned to the bodies and spat on them. He spit on every one of them. He covered their pristine clay with his own dark wet spittle.",
        "Then he walked away.",
        "When Tengri Ülgen returned with the soul-fire, he saw what had happened. He could not undo it. The bodies were spoiled. He could not, with the soul-fire, animate clean clay; he had to use what he had, which was now spit-covered.",
        "He turned the bodies inside out before placing the soul. The skin he had originally made — the smooth pristine outer layer — became the inner layer, the organs and the flesh. The spit-covered surface became the outer layer, the skin we see. So our bodies, the storytellers said, are inside-out: what we show to the world is what was originally to be hidden, and what is now hidden was originally meant to be the surface. Erlik's spit is in our skin. It is why we get sick. It is why we age.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Tengri Ülgen was angry. He did not strike his brother — he could not bring himself to — but he banished Erlik. He sent him down. Down, not to the small ugly land Erlik had spit out, but further — to the deep underworld, the cold lower country, where the bad dead would go.",
        "Erlik went. He built a hall of black iron in the lowest place. He surrounded himself with assistants — the small dark spirits, the kortyks — and he set up a court. He waited.",
        "When the first humans began to die, he received them. The good went up to Tengri Ülgen. The bad came down to Erlik. Erlik judged them. He punished. He held them in his court for a long time. He was not entirely cruel. He was, more accurately, exacting. He took the cases that did not deserve the upper hall, and he ran the lower hall as a place of long quiet detention, full of the small subtle punishments suited to the small subtle crimes most of the dead had committed.",
        "He has continued to do this. The shamans of the steppe — the old ones, before the Russians, before the Soviets, before everyone — used to descend in vision to bargain with Erlik for the return of a sick person's soul. He would receive them politely in his black iron hall. He would name a price. They would pay it. He would, sometimes, release the soul. He was open to negotiation.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The dark brother who hid mud in his cheek is the dark brother in every creation. Without him there is no spit on the body, no aging, no death. The shape we have is the shape both brothers made together, the elder reluctantly, the younger by sleight." },
        "Tengri Ülgen rules above. Erlik rules below. They have not spoken to each other in a very long time. The shamans, who go between them, are perhaps the only beings still maintaining a quiet diplomatic line. The world we walk on is held together by the long balance of the two of them, and the small spit-shadow of Erlik in our skin is the small permanent reminder, every morning, that we are not pure clay, and never were."
    ]
},

{
    id: "asena",
    title: "Asena, the Mother Wolf",
    subtitle: "How a wounded boy was raised by a she-wolf in a hidden valley, and the nation that came of it",
    civilization: "turkish",
    themes: ["Wolf", "Survival", "Foundation", "Mother"],
    content: [
        "There was, in the old time, a small tribe of the Turks living on the western edge of a great steppe. They were attacked one morning by a much larger neighboring tribe. The fighting was brief. Every member of the small tribe was killed — every man, every woman, every child — except for one boy.",
        "The boy was perhaps ten. He had been wounded in the leg in the fighting and left for dead in a ditch. The enemies had walked over him without noticing. They had been busy with other killing.",
        "When they had moved on, the boy crawled up out of the ditch. He could not walk. He dragged himself on his elbows. He found a small marsh nearby. He hid in the reeds.",
        "He did not die. He should have. He was small and bleeding and there was no one to help him. But a she-wolf had been hunting in the marsh that evening. She found him. She smelled him.",
        "She did not eat him. She licked the wound on his leg until it stopped bleeding. She brought him a freshly killed hare. She lay down beside him in the reeds to keep him warm through the night.",
        "She came back every evening. She brought meat. She protected him while he healed. By the time the boy could walk again — many weeks later — he could not have said when she had stopped being a threat and had started being his mother.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The enemies, however, had not forgotten the small tribe entirely. Word came to them, after a while, that a single boy had survived. They were a thorough people. They sent a hunting party to find him.",
        "The she-wolf, sensing the hunters, picked the boy up by the back of his clothes and ran. She ran for many days. She ran west across the steppe. She crossed a river. She crossed another river. She came at last to a great range of mountains in the west. She found, in the heart of those mountains, a hidden valley.",
        "The valley was reached only through a single narrow pass. The pass was overgrown with thorns. Once you were in the valley, you could not be seen from outside. The valley had its own small river. It had grass for grazing. It had pine trees and wild fruit. It was, in short, a perfect hidden country.",
        "She brought the boy in. She set him down in the meadow at the center of the valley. She lay beside him. She had carried him for many days; she was thin. She rested.",
        "She bore him children, after a while. The children were not entirely wolves and not entirely human. They were ten of them. They were the founding mothers and fathers of a new line.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Generations passed. The hidden valley grew populated. The descendants of the boy and the she-wolf — who had each, the storytellers said, retained a small wolfish quality, a small steady stare, a quiet endurance — grew into a small but tough nation. They were skilled iron-workers. They had found, on the high slopes of their valley, a vein of iron, and they had taught themselves to forge it. The iron of the hidden valley was the best in any country.",
        "After many centuries the valley was no longer big enough for them. They had grown numerous. They needed to come out. The thorned pass had narrowed over the generations and was now too small to push a wagon through. The eldest of the iron-workers struck the pass with his great hammer; the rock split; they came out into the world.",
        "They came out as a strong, organized, well-armed people. They went east across the steppes. They began to conquer. They went under several names in different periods — Hsiung-nu, Göktürks, Khazars, Seljuks, Ottomans — but the founding story they kept was always the same: a wounded boy, a she-wolf in a marsh, a hidden valley behind a thorned pass, the iron from the slopes, the long quiet generations before the coming-out. The wolf was the mother of every Turkic people that ever rode anywhere.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The boy left for dead in a ditch can become the founder of a long line, if the right she-wolf finds him before the night is over. The mother is not always the mother who bore him. Sometimes the mother is the one who carried him out." },
        "The Turkic peoples of Central Asia and Anatolia — the Turks of Turkey, the Turkmen of Turkmenistan, the Uzbeks, the Kazakhs, the Kirghiz, the Uighurs, and the others — preserve, in different versions, this story. The grey wolf appears on the flag of some Turkic political movements to this day. The Turkic peoples, asked about their oldest mother, will not always say a human name. They will, often, point to the wolf in the marsh, and they will mean it as literal genealogy, not as metaphor."
    ]
}
);

