window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "shahmaran",
    title: "Shahmaran, Queen of the Snakes",
    subtitle: "Of the woodcutter who fell into a cave of serpents and the queen who taught him medicine",
    civilization: "arabian",
    themes: ["Snake", "Wisdom", "Betrayal", "Queen"],
    content: [
        "There was a young woodcutter named Jamasp. He lived with his mother in a small house at the edge of a forest. He went out every morning to gather wood; he came back at evening with a load on his shoulder. They were poor but they ate.",
        "One day Jamasp followed his usual path past a stand of old oaks and found, by chance, a cleft in the rock he had not seen before. The cleft opened into a cave. He looked in. He saw, at the back of the cave, a faint glimmer.",
        "He went in. He went deeper than he had intended. The glimmer grew. He came at last into a great underground hall lit by a soft greenish light, and the hall was full of snakes — thousands of snakes, every color, lying coiled on the floor and hanging from the rafters and looped around small jeweled pillars. At the center of the hall, on a low throne, sat a creature he had never seen before.",
        "She had the upper body of a beautiful woman — pale-faced, dark-haired, wearing a gold diadem — and from the waist down she was a great snake's body, the long sinuous coils of an enormous python, the scales gleaming green and gold. She looked up at him. Her eyes were calm.",
        "\"You are Jamasp,\" she said softly. \"You took the wrong turning. You may not now leave. The snakes of my hall do not tolerate those who know our home. But — \" and she smiled gently \" — you may stay. I am Shahmaran. I am their queen. I will teach you. You will not be unhappy.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He stayed. He could not have done otherwise.",
        "He lived in her hall for many years. The snakes did not bite him; they had been told. Shahmaran taught him. She taught him the names of every herb and what each one cured. She taught him the language of the dreams of the body — what each pain in each part of the body was reporting, and what each could be eased by. She taught him the small surgeries. She taught him the careful preparation of antidotes. She taught him, in short, the entire art of medicine, in a curriculum no school in the upper world has ever matched.",
        "He grew. He became, in the underground hall, the wisest physician in the world. The snakes liked him. He fed them. He read to them. He sang to them in the long quiet hours. They had not had a human in the hall for centuries. They were, in a quiet way, fond of him.",
        "After many years he became homesick. He had not seen his mother since the morning he had walked into the cave. He had not seen the sun in years. He asked Shahmaran, gently, if he might be allowed to visit.",
        "She considered. She had grown to love him in her own way. She knew also what would happen if he left. The snakes had been patient with one human in their hall. They had told her, on his admission, what the rule was: the human could stay forever, but the human could never leave. If he left, the snakes' country would be exposed.",
        "She did, however, after long thought, agree. She made him swear one thing: he would never, in the upper world, bathe in the public baths. She did not explain why. He swore.",
        "She let him out. He climbed the long passage. He emerged into the sun. He went home. His mother had grown old; she wept; he wept; he settled in.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He set up as a physician. His skills were of a different order than any other physician's in the country. He healed cases that had been written off. He composed antidotes that worked. He was famous within a year.",
        "The Sultan of the country fell ill. The Sultan's court physicians could not heal him. They sent for Jamasp.",
        "Jamasp went. He examined the Sultan. He saw at once that the Sultan was suffering from a poison — a slow poison, administered in his food, by an enemy in his court. He named the poison. He composed the antidote. The Sultan recovered.",
        "The Sultan was grateful. The Sultan was also surprised. He had grown suspicious. He asked his vizier — for the vizier, secretly, had been the one administering the poison — \"Who is this Jamasp? Where did he learn his medicine?\"",
        "The vizier, who had reason to want Jamasp dead, said: \"Sire. There is an old story. Whoever has spoken with Shahmaran, the queen of the serpents, has on their skin a small mark — a small set of fine green scales, just below the breastbone. The mark cannot be hidden. If we send him to the public baths and have him observed, we will know.\"",
        "The Sultan, intrigued, summoned Jamasp. He invited him, as an honor, to use the imperial baths.",
        "Jamasp paled. He remembered his promise. He tried to refuse. The Sultan, surprised at the refusal, insisted. Jamasp, with no graceful way out, went.",
        "He undressed. The bath attendants saw at once the small patch of fine green scales just below his breastbone. They reported it.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The Sultan, on hearing the report, summoned Jamasp again. \"Tell me,\" he said, \"where she is. The queen of the serpents. Her body — her flesh — has properties. Whoever boils her flesh and drinks the broth becomes wise beyond mortal limit. Tell me.\"",
        "Jamasp wept. He had not wanted this. But the Sultan's question was a sword to his neck, and his old mother was at home, and the Sultan would not be refused. He told. He took them to the cave. He led the soldiers down.",
        "Shahmaran was on her throne. She did not flee. She had known he would come back this way. She looked at him.",
        "\"Jamasp,\" she said gently. \"You promised.\"",
        "\"I am sorry.\"",
        "\"I know.\"",
        "She offered, before they killed her, one piece of teaching. \"There are three pots,\" she said. \"You will boil my flesh in three pots. The first broth will be poison. Anyone who drinks it will die. The second broth will be ordinary food. The third broth will be the elixir of wisdom. Tell the Sultan to drink the third. Drink only the third yourself.\"",
        "She bowed her head. The soldiers killed her. They cut her into pieces. They set up the three pots.",
        "Jamasp brought the broths back to court. He gave the Sultan a cup. The Sultan, greedy, demanded the first cup brought — the first to be ready. Jamasp, weeping, gave him the first broth. The Sultan drank. The Sultan died, in great pain, on the throne. He had taken the poison.",
        "The vizier, who had hoped to take credit, was struck dead by the soldiers in the confusion. The court was in chaos.",
        "Jamasp, alone, drank the third broth — the wisdom broth. He felt the world open inside him. He understood every disease and every cure of every disease that would be discovered for the next thousand years.",
        "He became the great physician of the country. He healed every patient who came to his door. He had paid for the knowledge with the woman who had taught him; he never spoke of her again, but he kept a small green-scaled patch on his chest until the day he died, and on the morning of his death he laid his hand over the patch and said her name once, in apology, for the last time.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The promise to the queen of the serpents is the kind of promise that, if broken, costs the queen her life. The wisdom that comes of the broken promise is real wisdom — but the cost is real also, and it does not diminish with the years." },
        "Shahmaran is still depicted, in the southern Turkish and northern Iraqi villages, on small painted glass tiles hung in the kitchen — the woman from the waist up, the snake from the waist down, the gold diadem on her dark head. She is the patron, in those traditions, of doctors. The image hangs in many doctors' offices. Some of them know the story. Some of them do not. The image hangs anyway, and the patients, in their long waits, look at her, and they receive — without quite knowing how — a small calm of the kind she used to give Jamasp in her green-lit hall."
    ]
},

{
    id: "roc",
    title: "Sindbad and the Roc",
    subtitle: "How a sailor was carried over the cloud-line by the foot of an enormous bird",
    civilization: "arabian",
    themes: ["Sailor", "Bird", "Cunning", "Wonder"],
    content: [
        "Sindbad the Sailor had made many voyages. The sea was the only country he was at peace in, and yet on every voyage some catastrophe befell him — shipwreck, mutiny, sea-monster, storm — and he would arrive home, on each occasion, both ruined and somehow more wealthy than before, the calculus of his trade being entirely opaque to anyone who tried to follow it. He sat in his garden between voyages and told the stories. The stories grew with the telling. The merchants of Baghdad came to listen.",
        "On his second voyage Sindbad was sailing with a small company of merchants when they made landfall on what they took to be a small uninhabited island. The island was strange. There was no vegetation. The ground was perfectly smooth. There were no rocks, no streams, no trees. There was a single low dome at the center, a great pale dome the size of a small house, perfectly white.",
        "The sailors stretched their legs. They went exploring. They lit a small fire to cook their meal. The dome was warm under their hands. \"What kind of building is this?\" they wondered.",
        "Sindbad walked around the dome. He looked up. He saw, very high overhead, a small dark shape circling. The shape was getting larger.",
        "He understood, slowly, what he was looking at.",
        "The dome was an egg. The island was not an island. It was a flat shoal of sand. The egg belonged to a bird called the Roc — a bird the legends spoke of but the sailors had not believed in — and the dark circling shape was the mother coming back to her nest.",
        "Sindbad shouted. The sailors ran. They reached the boat. They cast off. They rowed.",
        "But Sindbad — Sindbad the Sailor, who could not, for some reason, ever resist the next idea — had a different thought. He stayed behind.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He let the boat sail without him. He watched the Roc descend.",
        "The Roc was the largest bird he had ever seen. Her wings, when she folded them to land, were the size of two ship-sails. Her foot — when she set it on the sand beside her egg — was the size of a small farmhouse. She settled onto the egg with the patient soft motion of any mother bird settling onto a nest.",
        "Sindbad, on the sand, walked very quietly to one of her great talons. He took the long heavy linen turban off his head. He unwound it. He used it as a rope. He tied himself to the talon — bound himself in three secure loops, the way a man secures a parcel — and he waited.",
        "He spent the night that way, lashed to a Roc's claw, the great bird breathing slowly above him.",
        "At dawn she stood up. She stretched her wings. She lifted off the nest. She flew.",
        "Sindbad, lashed to her foot, flew with her. He had not known what kind of country she would fly to. He had only known that wherever she went, it would be a place worth seeing.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "She flew over the sea. She flew for hours. Sindbad, dangling, watched the world below — the small ships, the white-tipped waves, the long blue horizon — and was, in his terror, also moved.",
        "She landed at last in a deep narrow valley between two cliffs. Sindbad, hidden behind her foot, untied himself in the moment she was preoccupied with hunting. He slipped down. He hid in a rock.",
        "The Roc, having caught a small snake she had been after, flew off. Sindbad came out.",
        "He looked around the valley. The valley floor was strewn with — diamonds. Diamonds the size of his fist. Diamonds in every crack. Diamonds in heaps. The valley had not been visited by any human being, because no human being could reach it. The cliffs on either side were sheer. There was no way out except by flight.",
        "He gathered as many diamonds as he could carry. He stuffed them into the pockets of his cloak. He stuffed them into the folds of his sash. He stuffed them into his shoes.",
        "Then he sat down to think.",
        "He noticed, after some time, a strange occurrence. From the top of the cliffs, occasionally, a great hunk of raw meat would fall down into the valley. The meat would land in the diamonds. Diamonds would stick to it. Then a great Roc — sometimes the same Roc, sometimes a different one — would swoop down, take the meat in her claws, and carry it back up.",
        "Sindbad understood, slowly, that there were merchants on top of the cliffs. They had figured out a way of harvesting the diamonds. They threw down meat. The Rocs carried it back to their nests in the cliff-tops. The merchants, climbing the cliffs from the outside, robbed the nests of diamonds.",
        "Sindbad sat with this for a moment. Then he saw a particularly large piece of meat fall. He ran to it. He lay down on it. He bound himself to it with another length of linen.",
        "A Roc swooped down. The Roc took the meat, with Sindbad attached, and flew up to the cliff-top.",
        "The merchants, on the cliff-top, ran to the nest. They saw — instead of an unconscious slab of meat — a man, lying flat on his back, opening his eyes. They screamed. They believed, briefly, that they had stolen a corpse from a grave. Sindbad sat up. He explained.",
        "He sold them most of the diamonds in his pockets. He paid for his passage home. He arrived in Baghdad several months later, considerably richer than when he had left.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Whoever has lashed himself to the foot of an unimaginable bird and has flown over a country no merchant has ever reached has earned, by the lashing alone, the right to whatever he can carry out. Wisdom and audacity are not always different things." },
        "The Roc has appeared in many later stories — in Marco Polo's travel book, in the European medieval bestiaries, in the imaginations of generations of children who have wondered how big a bird could really be. The diamond valley has appeared in many later geological dreams of explorers. And Sindbad, who told the story in his garden in Baghdad over wine, smiled as he told it, because he had not, by then, any need to embellish — the bare facts were already nearly impossible to believe, and the impossibility was where the wonder lived."
    ]
},

{
    id: "layla-majnun",
    title: "Layla and Majnun",
    subtitle: "How a young man went mad in the desert for a love that could not be permitted",
    civilization: "arabian",
    themes: ["Love", "Madness", "Desert", "Poetry"],
    content: [
        "There was a young man named Qays who lived in the deserts of the Najd. He was the son of a rich Bedouin chief. He was educated. He could compose poetry without effort, the way other young men could throw a spear. He was tall and handsome and gentle, and his father had hopes for him.",
        "He met Layla at school. She was the daughter of a different tribe's chief. They were perhaps thirteen. They sat near each other in the lessons. He looked at her once across the courtyard. She looked back. The look held for one second, perhaps two. By the time they had looked away again, both of them had been changed in a way neither of them yet understood.",
        "He went home that night and could not sleep. He composed his first poem about her by lamplight before dawn. He composed his second the next afternoon. He composed his third the next morning. By the end of the first month his bedroom was full of small papers, every one of them about her.",
        "He began to recite the poems publicly. He could not help it. He recited them in the marketplace. He recited them at family gatherings. His friends, embarrassed for him, advised him to stop. He could not stop. He was, by this point, in a condition the older Arabs of the desert had a specific word for: he had become a man for whom the beloved had become the only subject. He was Majnun — the one driven mad by love.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He went to Layla's father and asked for her in marriage.",
        "Her father refused. He had been hearing the poems. He had been hearing his daughter's name in every marketplace from the Hijaz to the Persian gulf. He was not pleased. To him the poems had not honored Layla — they had exposed her. A respectable young woman did not have her name carried around by a wild-eyed young poet in every public square. Her father said no.",
        "He arranged a different marriage for her. He gave her to a man named Ibn Salam, a wealthy older noble of a respectable tribe. Layla was given no choice. She was married. She moved to Ibn Salam's house. She did not consummate the marriage. She refused him. She was respectful. She tended his household. But she would not let him touch her. Ibn Salam — to his credit, perhaps — accepted this. He did not force her. He waited. He kept waiting for the rest of his life.",
        "Qays, when he heard, walked out of his father's house. He walked into the desert. He did not come back.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He lived in the desert. He lived among the wild animals. The lions and the gazelles and the desert hares grew used to him. They did not fear him. He fed them when he had food; he sat with them when he did not. He composed poetry continuously, scratching the lines in the sand with a stick, where the wind would erase them by evening.",
        "His clothes wore through. His hair grew long. His skin was burned dark. He talked to himself. He talked to the lions. He talked to the wind. He sometimes appeared at the edge of a passing caravan and asked for water in a courteous voice and accepted it and walked back into the dunes. The caravan-traders, who had heard of Majnun, would always give him water. They would also remember to mention, on returning to civilization, that they had seen him.",
        "Word of him reached Layla. She had no way to go to him. Her household watched her closely. She wept in private. She composed her own poetry, in her own room, never showing it to anyone. The two of them had become, in their separate quarters, the parallel halves of a single long composition.",
        "Years passed. Layla's husband Ibn Salam died of an illness. She was a widow. She was, by Arab custom, free to remarry — or even to seek out the lover she had been refused.",
        "She walked into the desert. She found him. He had become very thin. His eyes were the eyes of a man who had been talking to lions for a decade. He looked at her.",
        "He did not recognize her. Or — more accurately — he recognized her, but not as Layla. He had been carrying, in his head, the image of the thirteen-year-old he had met across a courtyard, and the woman in front of him, who was thirty, was not that image. He was polite. He offered her a cup of water from a small clay pot. He asked her name.",
        "She said her name.",
        "He said: \"Layla. That is a beautiful name. I knew a Layla once. I love her. Sit. Let me tell you about her.\"",
        "He talked to her about herself for an hour. She listened. She did not interrupt. She understood at last what had happened. The Qays she had known had been replaced, by the long years in the desert, by a man who loved an idea — an idea more pure than any actual woman could now embody, an idea his beloved herself was no longer the right vessel for. She had been outgrown by his own love for her.",
        "She wept. She walked back. She did not see him again. He died not long after, alone in the sand, with her name on his lips. Some shepherds found him. They buried him.",
        "She died a few months later, of nothing in particular, in her own room, with his name on her lips. Some say her servants buried her in a tomb on a small hill near her family's village.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The lover whose love has eaten him entirely will sometimes be unable to recognize the beloved when she finally arrives. The love has become, by then, larger than any actual person could fill. The beloved walks home from the desert understanding that she had been loved, in the end, beyond herself." },
        "The story of Layla and Majnun was first told in the seventh century in the deserts of Arabia and was retold in the twelfth century by the Persian poet Nizami in a famous long poem and has been retold in many languages since — in Turkish, in Urdu, in English. The qawwali singers of Pakistan still sing it. Eric Clapton wrote a song called \"Layla\" about it. The shape of a love so total that it consumes the lover before the beloved can be reached has become, in the long Arabic and Persian and Indian poetic traditions, the central metaphor for the love of God — the lover who burns himself away in the desert until the beloved is everything and the lover is nothing — and Majnun, who began as a thirteen-year-old in a school courtyard, has ended as the patron saint of every Sufi who has ever set out, alone, into the desert, looking for an entirely too large idea."
    ]
}
);

